{"title_page": "Gaya, India", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Gaya\n| other_name              = Gaya ji\n| settlement_type         = City\n| image_skyline           = Vishnupadh Temple.jpg \n| image_alt               = Vishnupad Temple\n| image_caption           = [[Vishnupad Mandir|Vishnupad Temple]] in Gaya, contains footprints of [[Vishnu|Lord Vishnu]]\n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Location of Gaya in Bihar\n| pushpin_map             = India Bihar#India \n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|24.75|N|85.01|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and union territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Administrative divisions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Divisions of Bihar|Division]]\n| subdivision_type4       = [[List of districts in India|District]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Bihar]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Magadha]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Magadh Division]]\n| subdivision_name4       = [[Gaya district|Gaya]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = [[Municipal corporation]]\n| governing_body          = Gaya Nagar Nigam\n| leader_title            = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name             = Birendra Kumar\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = <ref name=CDP-Gaya>{{cite web | url=http://urban.bih.nic.in/Docs/CDP/CDP-Gaya.pdf | format=PDF | page=4 | title=City Development Plan for Gaya: EXECUTIVE SUMMARY | publisher=Urban Development and Housing Department, Government of Bihar | accessdate=8 October 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913030335/http://urban.bih.nic.in/Docs/CDP/CDP-Gaya.pdf | archivedate=13 September 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| area_total_km2          = 308.31\n| area_rank               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 111\n| population_total        = 470,839<ref name=\"census2011\"/>\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_density_km2  = 9490\n| population_rank         = 98th (India)\n                            2nd (Bihar)\n| population_demonym      = Gayaite, Gayavi <ref>{{cite web |url=http://huntnews.in/p/detail/458673712122865?xlang=en&uc_param_str=dnfrpfbivesscpgimibtbmntnijblauputoggdnw&pos=1462975380148&channel=education&chncat=category_english |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-12 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816020056/http://huntnews.in/p/detail/458673712122865?xlang=en&uc_param_str=dnfrpfbivesscpgimibtbmntnijblauputoggdnw&pos=1462975380148&channel=education&chncat=category_english |archivedate=16 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 823001 - 13\n| area_code               = 91-631\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-BR]]\n| registration_plate      = BR-02\n| website                 = {{URL|www.gaya.bih.nic.in}}, [http://apnagaya.com Apna Gaya Official]\n| footnotes               = \n| demographics1_info1     = [[Angika language|Maithili]], [[Hindi language]]\n| demographics1_title2    = Spoken\n| demographics1_info2     =[[Magadhi]], [[Hindi]], [[Maithili language|Maithili]], [[Urdu]]\n| blank1_name             = Railway Station\n| blank1_info             = [[Gaya Junction]]\n| blank2_name             = Airport\n| blank2_info             = [[Gaya International Airport]]\n}}\n\n'''Gaya''' is of historical significance and is one of the major tourist attractions of the state of [[Bihar]] Southern Part. Gaya is {{convert|100|km|mi}} south of [[Patna]], the capital city of Bihar. It is the state's [[List of cities in Bihar by population|second-largest]] city, with a population of 470,839, and is the headquarters of [[Gaya district]] and [[Magadh division]]. The city is surrounded on three sides by small, rocky hills ([[Mangla Gauri|Mangla-Gauri]], Shringa-Sthan, Ram-Shila, and Brahmayoni), with the [[Phalgu|Phalgu River]] on its fourth (eastern) side.\n\nGaya is sanctified in the [[Jain]], [[Hindu]], and [[Buddhist]] religions. Gaya district is mentioned in the great epics, the ''[[Ramayana]]'' and the ''[[Mahabharata]]''. It is the place where [[Rama]], with [[Sita]] and [[Lakshmana]], came to offer [[Pinda (riceball)|pind-daan]] for their father, Dasharath, and continues to be a major Hindu pilgrimage site for the pind-daan ritual. [[Bodh Gaya]], where [[Buddha]] is said to have attained [[Enlightenment in Buddhism|enlightenment]], and is one of the four holy sites of [[Buddhism]]. The [[Mahabodhi Temple]] complex at Bodh Gaya is a [[World Heritage site]].\n\n==Etymology==\nGaya is one of the best historical sites in India. Gaya is named after the demon ''Gayasur'' (meaning \"the demon Gaya\"). According to [[Vayu Purana]], Gaya was the name of a demon ([[Asura]]) whose body became pious after he performed strict penance and secured blessings from Lord [[Vishnu]].<ref name=MSME /> It was said that the body of Gayasura was transformed into the series of rocky hills that make up the landscape of Gaya.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.harekrsna.com/philosophy/associates/demons/vishnu/gayasur.htm |title=The Hare Krsnas - Battles of Vishnu Avatars - Gayasur |publisher=Harekrsna.com |accessdate=2016-01-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115138/http://www.harekrsna.com/philosophy/associates/demons/vishnu/gayasur.htm |archivedate=4 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Gayasisa1.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Brahmayoni Hill, where Buddha preached the ''[[Fire Sermon|Adittapariyaya Sutta]]'' (the ''Fire Sermon'').]]\n\n===Ancient history===\nAccording to modern scholars, the [[Kikata Kingdom|Kikata kingdom]] from rigvedic period was located at Gaya, Bihar.\n\nGaya is an ancient city, with a Buddhist documented history dating back to the 6th century BCE when the sage [[Gautama Buddha]] attained enlightenment at [[Bodh Gaya]], {{convert|16|km|abbr=on}} from the modern city, and became the [[Buddha (title)|Buddha]].<ref name=\"Nomination\">{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/uploads/nominations/1056rev.pdf |title=World Heritage Scanned Nomination - Site Name: Mahabodhi Temple Complex at Bodh Gaya |last=World Heritage Committee |website=www.whc.unesco.org |date=29 June 2002 |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nEven before this time, Gaya was a place of pilgrimage for people from around the world. The fame of ancient Gaya derived from the account in the ''[[Ramayana]]'' of the  god [[Rama]] coming here to the banks of [[Phalgu|Phalgu River]] (called the [[Niranjana]]), accompanied by his wife and younger brother, to offer [[Pinda (riceball)|pind-daan]] for their father [[Dasharatha]], for the [[moksha]] of his soul.<ref name=\"R\u00e1may\u00e1n\">{{cite book |last=Griffith |first=Ralph T. H. |title=The R\u00e1may\u00e1n of V\u00e1lm\u00edki Translated into English Verse |publisher= London: Tr\u00fcbner & Co.; Benares: E. J. Lazarus and Co |date=1870-1874 |page=761 |url= https://www.gutenberg.org/files/24869/24869-pdf.pdf#page=761}}</ref><ref name='pind daan'>{{cite book |last=Bhalla |first=Prem D |title= Hindu Rites, Rituals, Customs and Traditions: A to Z on the Hindu Way of Life |publisher= Pustak Mahal |date=2006 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MOgAnbOmu08C&pg=PT307&lpg=PT307&dq=pind+daan&source=bl&ots=WQj4gS8wxk&sig=ySbZEo66vvlIQkTtS6WHhg1vNMU&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwijrvecr9ndAhUKL8AKHcHKAIA4HhDoATAGegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=pind%20daan&f=false|pages=314\u2013319 |chapter=Chapter N6-N7: What is the importance of pind daan for the deceased?; What is the purpose of the Shraddh ceremony? |isbn=978-8-122-30902-7 |access-date=28 September 2018 }}</ref> In the ''[[Mahabharata]]'', Gaya is referred to as Gayapuri.\n\nGaya flourished in the [[Maurya Empire]] (321\u2013187 BCE), which ruled from the city of [[Pataliputra]] (adjacent to modern [[Patna]]) over an area that extended beyond the Indian subcontinent. During this period, Gaya witnessed the rise and fall of many dynasties in the [[Magadha]] region, where it occupied an important place in cultural history over some 2,400 years between the 6th century BCE and the 18th century CE.\n\nThe city's cultural significance began with the dynasty founded by Sisunaga, who exercised power over Patna and Gaya around 600 BCE. [[Bimbisara]], fifth king of the dynasty, who lived and ruled around 519 BCE, had projected Gaya to the outer world. Having attained an important place in the history of civilization, the area experienced the influence of Gautama Buddha and Bhagwan Mahavir during the reign of Bimbisara. After a brief period under the [[Nanda Empire|Nanda dynasty]] (345\u2013321 BCE), Gaya and the entire Magadha region came under Mauryan rule. Mauryan Emperor [[Ashoka]] (272\u2013232 BCE) embraced and promoted Buddhism. He visited Gaya, and built the first temple at Bodh Gaya to commemorate the [[Buddha]]'s attainment of supreme enlightenment.<ref name='UNESCO WHC'>{{cite web |url= https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1056 |title= Mahabodhi Temple Complex at Bodh Gaya, Description |website=www.whc.unesco.org |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |access-date=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe period of Hindu revivalism began with the [[Gupta Empire]] during the 4th and 5th centuries CE. [[Samudragupta]] of Magadha brought Gaya into the limelight, making it the capital of Bihar district during the Gupta empire.\n\nIn 750 CE, Gaya became a part of the [[Pala Empire]], under the rule of its founder, [[Gopala]]. It is believed that the present temple of Bodh Gaya was built during the reign of Gopala's son, Dharmapala.\n\nIn the 12th century CE, Gaya was invaded by [[Muhammad Bakhtiyar Khilji]] of the [[Ghaznavid Empire]]. By 1557, it had become part of the [[Mughal Empire]], and remained under its power until the [[Battle of Buxar]] and the beginning of [[British Raj|British rule]] in 1764. Gaya, along with other parts of the country, gained its independence in 1947.\n\n===Modern history===\nAs attested by [[Francis Buchanan-Hamilton]] in the early nineteenth century, the city was divided into two areas: a sacred area in the southern part of the city, called Gaya; and the larger secular area, which may have been known by the Muslim community as Allahabad. During the [[British Raj|British rule]], the commercial and administrative area of the secular zone was formally named Saheb Ganj by British policy reformer [[Thomas Law (1756\u20131834)|Thomas Law]], who was a district officer in Gaya in the late nineteenth century.<ref name='Vidyarthi'>{{cite book |last=Vidyarthi |first=Lalita Prasad |title=The Sacred Complex in Hindu Gaya |publisher=Concept Publishing Company |edition=2nd |date=1978 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=S4FidiusPr0C&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=gaya+priests+district&source=bl&ots=C-SjM5JD0j&sig=dQ7Ocyj2wyAm07DU2yG-d02-WEI&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtwvqyrN3dAhXSxIUKHRE9CMgQ6AEwCHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=gaya%20priests%20district&f=false\n|pages=1\u201329 |chapter=Chapter 1: The Sacred Centres of Gaya |isbn=978-1-234-56789-7 |access-date=28 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Swami Sahajanand Saraswati]], founder of the [[All India Kisan Sabha]] peasant movement in 1936, established an ashram at [[Neyamatpur]], Gaya, which later became the centre of the freedom struggle in [[Bihar]]. Many prominent leaders of the [[Indian National Congress]] visited frequently to meet [[Pandit Yadunandan (Jadunandan) Sharma|Yadunandan (Jadunandan) Sharma]] when he was leader of Kisan Sabha, residing in the ashram set up by Swamiji. Yadunandan Sharma became the leader of the peasants of [[Gaya district]] and second-in-command to Swami Sahajanand Saraswati.\n\nGaya played a significant role in the [[Indian Independence Movement]]. From 26 to 31 December 1922, the 37th session of the [[Indian National Congress]] was held in Gaya<ref>{{cite news |last=Indian National Congress |date=1923 |title=Report of the Thirty-Seventh Indian National Congress held at Gaya on the 26th, 27th, 29th, 30th and 31st December 1922 |url=https://dspace.gipe.ac.in/xmlui/handle/10973/17967https://dspace.gipe.ac.in/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10973/17967/GIPE-038654-Contents.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y |access-date=26 September 2018 }}</ref> under the presidency of [[Chittaranjan Das|Deshbandhu Chittaranjan Das]]. It was attended by prominent leaders and luminaries of the Independence Movement, including [[Mahatma Gandhi|Mohandas K. Gandhi]], [[Rajendra Prasad|Dr. Rajendra Prasad]], [[Anugrah Narayan Sinha|Dr. Anugrah Narayan Sinha]], [[Sardar Patel]], [[Maulana Azad]], [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] and [[Sri Krishna Sinha]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Roy |first=Evelyn |date=1923 |title=Politics in Gaya |format=PDF |url=https://dspace.gipe.ac.in/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10973/17967/GIPE-038654-Contents.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y | work=The Communist International, Organ of the Executive Committee of the Communist International, English Edition |location=London, England |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nGaya is the birthplace of eminent nationalist ''[[Honorary titles of Indian leaders|Bihar Vibhuti]]'', [[Anugrah Narayan Sinha|Dr. Anugrah Narayan Sinha]], Bihar's first [[Deputy Chief Minister of Bihar|deputy Chief Minister]] and Finance Minister. Former Bihar Chief Minister [[Satyendra Narayan Sinha]] also hailed from Gaya. Shri Ishwar Chaudhary, a member of the [[5th Lok Sabha|Fifth]], [[6th Lok Sabha|Sixth]] and [[9th Lok Sabha|Ninth]] [[Lok Sabha]]s from 1971 to 1979 and from 1989 to 1991, represented the Gaya constituency of Bihar.\n\n==Administration==\nUntil 1864, Gaya was a part of the district of Behar and Ramgarh (now in the state of [[Jharkhand]]). It became a district of Bihar in its own right on 3 October 1865.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/gaya-celebrates-154th-establishment-day/articleshow/66059602.cms|title=Gaya celebrates 154th establishment day}}</ref> In May 1981, the Bihar state government created the [[Magadh division]], comprising the district of [[Gaya district|Gaya]], along with [[Nawada district|Nawada]], [[Aurangabad district, Bihar|Aurangabad]] and [[Jehanabad district|Jehanabad]], all of which had originally been sub-divisions when Gaya district was created.<ref name=MSME /> Aurangabad and Nawada were partitioned from the territory of Gaya in 1976; and Jehanabad in 1988.<ref name='Statoids'>{{cite web | url = http://www.statoids.com/yin.html | title = Districts of India | accessdate = 2011-10-11 | last = Law | first = Gwillim | date = 2011-09-25 | work = Statoids | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111017155710/http://www.statoids.com/yin.html | archivedate = 2011-10-17 }}</ref> Gaya district occupies an area of 4,976&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (1,921 mile<sup>2</sup>).<ref name=MSME />\n\n==Culture==\n===Pilgrimage===\n\nThe city of Gaya is a holy place of [[Hinduism]], with a great number of [[Hindu deities]] represented in the engravings, paintings and carvings of its shrines. Of particular importance are the sites in the city associated with [[Vishnu]], in particular the [[Phalgu|Phalgu River]] and the shrine [[Vishnupad Mandir]], or Vishnupada, which is marked by a large footprint of Lord Vishnu engraved in a basalt block.<ref name='Vidyarthi'/> Gaya is the location at which Rama, with Sita and Lakshmana, offered pind-daan for his father, Dasharatha. Gaya has since remained a site of key importance for the performance of the pind-daan ritual.<ref name=\"R\u00e1may\u00e1n\"/><ref name='pind daan'/>\n\n\nGaya is considered to be one of the most ideal places to perform the shraddh. (A shraddh is the Hindu ritual that one performs to pay homage to one's \u2018ancestors\u2019, especially to one's dead parents). As per Hindu belief system, it is believed that a person goes to hell if he dies in the following circumstances - if he meets an accidental death, if he dies without his consecrations being performed, or if he is killed by a wild animal. But, if \u2018Shraddh rituals\u2019 of that person are performed at \u2018Gaya\u2019 then the soul of such a man will get rid of the tortures of the hell and will go to heaven. Performing \u2018Shraddh rituals\u2019 here is of great importance as it helps one to get rid of \u2018pitra rinna\u2019 i.e. debts towards one's ancestors (male forefathers). \n\nNearby Bodh Gaya (\"Buddha Gaya\"), so named to distinguish it from the Hindu town centre of Gaya, is one of the four holiest sites of Buddhism and the site where the Buddha attained enlightenment.<ref name='UNESCO WHC' /><ref name='Vidyarthi'/>\n\n===World Heritage site at Bodh Gaya===\n\nThe [[Mahabodhi Temple|Mahabodhi Temple Complex at Bodh Gaya]] was listed as a [[World Heritage site]] by the [[World Heritage Committee]] of the [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO)]] at its 26th session, on 26 June 2002.<ref name='UNESCO WHC'/>\n\nThe {{convert|50|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} Mahabodhi Temple central to the complex was first built by the emperor [[Ashoka]] in the 3rd century BCE. The main part of the present structure dates from the 5th\u20136th centuries CE. It is one of the earliest and best-preserved Buddhist temples built entirely of brick dating from the later [[Gupta Empire|Gupta]] period. The [[Bodhi Tree]] (''Ficus religiosa''), the most important of the sacred places within the complex, is reputedly a descendant of the original tree under which Siddh\u0101rtha Gautama attained [[Enlightenment in Buddhism|enlightenment]] and became the [[Buddha]].<ref name='UNESCO WHC'/> Marking this seminal moment, Bodh Gaya is one of the four holiest pilgrimage sites of Buddhism, with [[Lumbini]], [[Sarnath]] and [[Kushinagar]].<ref name='ICCROM'/>\n\nThe various structures on the site have undergone a number of restorations over the centuries. Ongoing maintenance and management is required to protect the complex which, as a major pilgrimage site, is under pressure due to large numbers of visitors.<ref name='ICCROM'>{{cite book |last=Lambah |first=Abha Narain |last2=Dorje |first2=Nangze |editor-last1=Wijesuriya |editor-first1=Gamini |editor-last2=Lee |editor-first2=Sujeong |title=ICCROM-CHA Conservation Forum Series: First ICCROM-CHA International Forum on Conservation Asian Buddhist Heritage: Conserving the Sacred |publisher= ICCROM, International Centre for the Study of the Preservation and Restoration of Cultural Property|date=2017 |pages=103\u2013111 |chapter=Chapter 13: Challenges of managing a living Buddhist site: Mahabodhi Temple, Bodh Gaya, India | isbn=978-92-9077-240-8|url= https://www.iccrom.org/sites/default/files/2017-11/asianbuddhist_web.pdf |access-date=27 September 2018}}</ref> The site is under the responsibility of the state government of Bihar, and is managed by the Bodhgaya Temple Management Committee (BTMC) and Advisory Board under the Bodh Gaya Temple Act, 1949.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bodhgayatemple.com/images/pdf/temple_act.pdf |title= The Bodh Gaya Temple Act, 1949 (Bihar Act of 17 of 1949), (as modified up to the 8th February, 1955) |website= www.bodhgayatemple.com |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nAs Gaya is surrounded by hills on three sides and river on the fourth side, the climate of Gaya is seasonable. Climate is characterised by relatively high temperatures and evenly distributed rainfall throughout the year.  The [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] sub-type for this climate is \"[[Humid subtropical climate|Cwa]]\" (humid subtropical).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=590718&cityname=Gaya%2C+Bihar%2C+India&units= |title=Climate Summary for Gaya, India |publisher=Weatherbase.com |accessdate=2016-01-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323021216/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=590718&cityname=Gaya%2C+Bihar%2C+India&units= |archivedate=23 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gaya, India \n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan high F = 75\n|Feb high F = 80\n|Mar high F = 92\n|Apr high F = 102\n|May high F = 105\n|Jun high F = 101\n|Jul high F = 92\n|Aug high F = 90\n|Sep high F = 91\n|Oct high F = 89\n|Nov high F = 84\n|Dec high F = 80\n|year high F = 90\n|Jan low F = 50\n|Feb low F = 55\n|Mar low F = 64\n|Apr low F = 74\n|May low F = 80\n|Jun low F = 82\n|Jul low F = 79\n|Aug low F = 78\n|Sep low F = 77\n|Oct low F = 71\n|Nov low F = 58\n|Dec low F = 53\n|year low F = 68\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.8\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.8\n|Mar precipitation inch = 0.5\n|Apr precipitation inch = 0.3\n|May precipitation inch = 0.8\n|Jun precipitation inch = 5.4\n|Jul precipitation inch = 12.4\n|Aug precipitation inch = 12.9\n|Sep precipitation inch = 8.1\n|Oct precipitation inch = 2.1\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.4\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.1\n|year precipitation inch = 44.5\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=Weatherbase>\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=590718&cityname=Gaya-Bihar-India\n |publisher   = Weatherbase\n |title       = Weatherbase.com\n |year        = 2013\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20150403090837/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=590718&cityname=Gaya-Bihar-India\n |archivedate = 3 April 2015\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\nRetrieved on 31 July 2016.\n</ref>\n|date=July 2013\n}}\n==Border Covering==\nEast-  Nawada\nWest-  AurangaBad\nNorth- Jehanabad\nSouth- Covering Jharkhand State Border\n==Economy==\nGaya is the second-largest contributor to the [[economy of Bihar]], after Patna. Agriculture is the leading economic activity of the district. The main crops grown are rice, wheat, potatoes, and lentils. Livestock raised include cattle, buffaloes, goats and pigs. Gaya has a large number of household industries, producing [[Incense in India|incense sticks]] (atagarbatti), local sweets [[tilkut]] (made with sesame seed) and lai (made with poppy seed), stone-work, hand weaving, power-loom weaving, textiles and garments, small-scale manufactured goods, and plastic products. Small-scale industries also include agricultural services, metalworking, machinery and equipment production and repair services.<ref name=\"MSME\">{{cite news |last= MSME-Development Institute, Ministry of MSME, Government of India |date=2011 |title= Brief Industrial Profile of Gaya District \u2013 Micro, Small & Medium Enterprises |url=http://dcmsme.gov.in/dips/gaya_bihar.pdf |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref> The main vegetable market in the city is the Kedarnath Market. Commercial activities are located along its main roads; the city also has a large number of informal shops.<ref name=\"Udyog Mitra\">{{cite web |url=https://www.udyogmitrabihar.in/docs/dp/gaya.pdf |title=Bihar \u2013 Economic Profile Gaya |last=Udyog Mitra, Department of Industries |publisher=Government of Bihar|date=2011 |website=www.udyogmitrabihar.in |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref> As Gaya is an important centre of religious tourism, accommodation is widely available.<ref name=\"Geary\">{{cite book |last=Geary | first=David |title=The Rebirth of Bodh Gaya: Buddhism and the Making of a World Heritage Site |publisher= University of Washington Press |date=2017 |page=159 |section=Buddhist Circuits and Spiritual Tourism (in Chapter 5: A Master Plan for World Heritage) |isbn=978-0-295-74238-0 | url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=meA5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=tourist+infrastructure+gaya&source=bl&ots=0z79pQXHFu&sig=fTFqoeWgY7LzEyTiwzCpQn56u3Y&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwju_4PT1dvdAhUFQhoKHbhiAxAQ6AEwB3oECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=tourist%20infrastructure%20gaya&f=false }}</ref> Bodh Gaya's largest hotel is the Maha Bodhi Hotel, Resort & Convention Centre; the Sambodhi Retreat, a resort of Bihar and Jharkhand, is also in the town.\n\nIn January 2015, Gaya was chosen as one of twelve heritage cities to benefit from the Government of India's four-year [[Heritage City Development and Augmentation Yojana]] (HRIDAY) scheme for urban planning, economic growth and heritage conservation projects.<ref>{{cite news |last= HRIDAY National Project Management Unit, National Institute of Urban Affairs, Ministry of Urban Development Government of India |date=21 January 2015 |title= Heritage City Development and Augmentation Yojana |url=https://hridayindia.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/hriday-brochure.pdf |website=www.hridayindia.in |access-date=26 September 2018 }}</ref> The scheme is due to complete in November 2018.{{update after|2018|11|30|date=November 2018}}<ref>{{cite news |last= HRIDAY National Project Management Unit, National Institute of Urban Affairs |title= HRIDAY-Rejuvenating the Soul of Urban India-Heritage City Development and Augmentation Yojana |url= https://hridayindia.in |website=www.hridayindia.in |access-date=26 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Gaya<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/181-gaya.html|title=Gaya City Census 2011 data|work=Census 2011 India|accessdate=7 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507141025/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/181-gaya.html|archivedate=7 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|79.43}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|19.65}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|blue|0.26}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jains]]|pink|0.24}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|1.42}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n\u2020<small>Includes [[Sikh]]s (0.09%), [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (0.02%).</small>\n}}\nIn the 2011 census, the Gaya Urban Agglomeration had a population of 474,093.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | title = Urban Agglomerations/Cities having population 1 lakh and above | work = Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011 | accessdate = 2012-04-16 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111113152754/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | archivedate = 13 November 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The Gaya Urban Agglomeration encompasses the Gaya [[Municipal corporations in India|Municipal Corporation]], Kaler ([[Out Growth]]), and Paharpur ([[Census town#India|Census Town]]).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_4_PR_UAs_1Lakh_and_Above_Appendix.pdf | title = Constituents of urban Agglomerations Having Population 1 Lakh & above | work = Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011 | accessdate = 2012-04-16 | url-status = live | archiveurl = http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160617063229/http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_4_PR_UAs_1Lakh_and_Above_Appendix.pdf | archivedate = 17 June 2016 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> the Gaya Municipal Corporation had a total population of 468,614,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.de/php/india-bihar.php?adm2id=1034 |title=Gaya, District in Bihar - The population development of Gaya|accessdate=2016-07-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914184017/http://www.citypopulation.de/php/india-bihar.php?adm2id=1034 |archivedate=14 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> of whom 247,572 were male and 221,042 were female. The population below 5 years was 59,669. The sex ratio was 986 women to 1000 men. The literacy rate for the population aged 7 and over was 85.74%.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | title = Cities having population 1 lakh and above | work = Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011 | accessdate = 2012-04-16 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120507135928/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | archivedate = 7 May 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nGaya is connected to the rest of India by roads, rail and airways. The [[Grand Chord]] section of the Indian Railways passes through Gaya.\n\n===Local transport===\nThere are many city buses and taxis providing services across the city and Bodh Gaya. [[Tanga (carriage)|Tangas]], [[auto rickshaw]]s, and cycle rickshaws also ply the city and Bodh Gaya. The main bus stands are Government Bus Stand, Sikaria More Bus Stand, Gaurkashni Bus Stand (Manpur), and Delha Bus Stand. Local transport is reliable, and auto rickshaws are available for various destinations in the city. The Gaya\u2013Patna railway line plays a major role in transporting people from the town to the state capital.\n\n===Roadways===\nGaya has a road network providing good connectivity with the state of Bihar and other parts of the country.<ref name=CDP>{{cite web |url= http://urban.bih.nic.in/Docs/CDP/CDP-Gaya.pdf |title= City Development Plan (2010-30) Gaya: Executive Summary |last=Egis India Consulting Engineers Private Limited |publisher= Urban Development and Housing Department Government of Biha |website=www.urban.bih.nic.in |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref> Regular direct bus services run from Gaya to [[Patna]], [[Bhagalpur]], [[Munger]], [[Nalanda]], [[Rajgir]], [[Varanasi]], [[Ranchi]], [[Jamshedpur]], [[Hazaribagh]], [[Durgapur]], [[Asansol]], [[Kolkata]] and [[Dhanbad]]. In 2011, {{abbr|A/C|air-conditioned}} [[Mercedes-Benz]] luxury services were introduced by [[Bihar State Road Transport Corporation]] for [[Muzaffarpur]], [[Patna]], [[Munger]], [[Bhagalpur]], [[Motihari]], [[Hazaribagh]], [[Koderma]], and Ramgarh.\n\nThe [[Grand Trunk Road]] from [[Kolkata]] to [[Delhi]] passes from \"Dobhi\"some {{convert|30|km|abbr=on}} from Gaya. This road, known as [[National Highway 2 (India, old numbering)|National Highway 2]] before 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dorth.gov.in/writereaddata/sublinkimages/finaldoc6143316640.pdf|title=Rationalisation of Numbering Systems of National Highways|publisher=[[Department of Road Transport and Highways]]|accessdate=27 September 2018|location=New Delhi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201124738/http://dorth.gov.in/writereaddata/sublinkimages/finaldoc6143316640.pdf|archive-date=1 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> is now called [[National Highway 19 (India)|National Highway 19]]. It connects Gaya to [[Patna]], [[Ranchi]], [[Jamshedpur]], [[Bokaro Steel City|Bokaro]], [[Rourkela]], [[Durgapur, West Bengal|Durgapur]], [[Kolkata]] (495&nbsp;km), [[Varanasi]] (252&nbsp;km), [[Allahabad]], [[Kanpur]], [[Delhi]], [[Amritsar]], and to the Pakistani cities of [[Lahore]] and [[Peshawar]]. Gaya is connected to Patna (105&nbsp;km) by [[National Highway 22 (India)|National Highway 22]] (formerly NH 83), and to Nawada, Rajgir (78&nbsp;km) and [[Bihar Sharif]] by [[National Highway 120 (India)|NH 120]]. Construction work began in 2014 on the road from Patna to Dobhi via Gaya and Gaya to Bihar Sharif to create a four-lane highway with additional road and bridge infrastructure. Completion of the project, originally due in April 2018, has been delayed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Qadir |first=Abdul |date=25 April 2018 |title=Dobhi-Patna road project delayed |url= https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/dobhi-patna-road-project-delayed/articleshow/63900929.cms |work=The Times of India |location=India |access-date=28 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Railways===\n[[Gaya Junction]] railway station is a [[junction station]] serving the city. Gaya Junction was the only station in Bihar and Jharkhand in the list of 66 stations to be built to international standards drawn up by [[Minister of Railways (India)|Minister of Railways]]  [[Mamata Banerjee]]. Gaya falls under the jurisdiction of the [[Mughalsarai railway division]] of the [[East Central Railway zone]]. The [[Grand Chord]] rail line that connects [[Howrah]] and [[New Delhi]] passes through Gaya. It lies between [[Mughalsarai Junction railway station|Mughalsarai Junction]] on the [[Delhi]] side and [[Dhanbad Junction railway station|Dhanbad Junction]] on the [[Howrah railway station|Howrah]] side. It is located at {{Coord|24|48|13|N|84|59|57|E|}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wikimapia.org/13242471/Gaya-Junction-Rail-Station-ER |title=Gaya Junction |publisher=Wikimapia |accessdate=2011-12-01 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210110843/http://wikimapia.org/13242471/Gaya-Junction-Rail-Station-ER |archivedate=10 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It has an elevation of {{Convert|117|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"train list\">{{cite web|title=Trains at Gaya|url=http://indiarailinfo.com/arrivals/1388|publisher=India Rail Info|accessdate=1 April 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111208132627/http://indiarailinfo.com/arrivals/1388|archivedate=8 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=indiantrains>{{cite web|title=Ghanbad Junction Railway Station Details |url=http://www.indiantrains.org/station-details/?code=GAYA&name=DHANBAD+JN |publisher=indiantrains.org |accessdate=1 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408222802/http://www.indiantrains.org/station-details/?code=GAYA&name=DHANBAD+JN |archivedate=8 April 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Airport===\n{{Main|Gaya Airport}}\nSituated between Gaya (7&nbsp;km) and [[Bodh Gaya]] (11&nbsp;km), [[Gaya Airport]] is the large airport by area, and one of two operating international airports in the states of Bihar and Jharkhand. It is the second-busiest airport in Bihar, after Patna's [[Jay Prakash Narayan Airport]]. Gaya airport mainly operates seasonal flights for Buddhist pilgrims to Bodh Gaya from [[Colombo]], Sri Lanka; [[Bangkok]], Thailand; [[Singapore]], and [[Paro, Bhutan|Paro]], Bhutan.  There are also regular domestic flights to Varanasi, Kolkata and Delhi. The Airports Authority of India has plans to develop Gaya Airport as a stand-by to the [[Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose International Airport]] in Kolkata.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.aai.aero/en/node/74281|title= Gaya Airport |website= www.aai.aero |last=Airports Authority of India |access-date=27 September 2018}}</ref>Gaya Airport also Serves as only place of Bihar from where Haj Pilgrimage take direct flight to Holy City of Makkah And Madina.Gaya International Airport has only Immigration Counter in Bihar.\n\n==Education==\n\nNotable institutions of higher education include:\n\n*[[Indian Institute of Management Bodh Gaya]] 11&nbsp;km from City HEADQUARTER\n*[[Gaya College]] \n*[[Gaya College of Engineering]]\n*[[Magadh University]] 10&nbsp;km from District HEADQUARTER\n*[[Central University of South Bihar]] 14&nbsp;km from City HEADQUARTER\n*[[Anugrah Narayan Magadh Medical College and Hospital]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"census2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|title=UA/Cities 1 lakh and above|publisher=Government of India|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113152754/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|archivedate=13 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[https://gayamahanagar.com Reference in hindi about Gaya] \n{{commons category|Gaya, India}}\n\n* [https://www.tentaran.com/the-significance-of-gaya-shraddh-in-hindu-death-rituals/ Significance of performing shradh in Gaya]\n\n<nowiki/>*{{ppn|g/gayaa.htm|Gaya}}\n* {{Suttas|Gaya|gandhabhaka|sn/sn35/sn35.028.than.html Adittapariyaya Sutta \u2013 The Fire|mn/mn.007.nypo.html#gaya Verse from the Vatthupama Sutta \u2013 The Simile of the Cloth}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Gaya}}\n\n{{Bihar}}\n{{Hindu holy cities}}\n{{Magadh Division}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu pilgrimage sites in India]]\n[[Category:Buddhist pilgrimage sites in India]]\n[[Category:Hindu holy cities]]\n[[Category:Early Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Gautama Buddha]]\n[[Category:Gaya, India| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Gaya\n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = City\n| image_skyline           = Vishnupadh Temple.jpg \n| image_alt               = Vishnupad Temple\n| image_caption           = [[Vishnupad Mandir|Vishnupad Temple]] in Gaya, contains footprints of [[Vishnu|Lord Vishnu]]\n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Location of Gaya in Bihar\n| pushpin_map             = India Bihar#India \n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|24.75|N|85.01|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and union territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Administrative divisions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Divisions of Bihar|Division]]\n| subdivision_type4       = [[List of dis