itle1    = Official\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 823001 - 13\n| area_code               = 91-631\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-BR]]\n| registration_plate      = BR-02\n| website                 = {{URL|www.gaya.bih.nic.in}}, [http://apnagaya.com Apna Gaya Official]\n| footnotes               = \n| demographics1_info1     = [[Angika language|Maithili]], [[Hindi language]]\n| demographics1_title2    = Spoken\n| demographics1_info2     =[[Magadhi]], [[Hindi]], [[Maithili language|Maithili]], [[Urdu]]\n| blank1_name             = Railway Station\n| blank1_info             = [[Gaya Junction]]\n| blank2_name             = Airport\n| blank2_info             = [[Gaya International Airport]]\n}}\n\n'''Gaya''' is of historical significance and is one of the major tourist attractions of the state of [[Bihar]] Southern Part. Gaya is {{convert|100|km|mi}} south of [[Patna]], the capital city of Bihar. It is the state's [[List of cities in Bihar by population|second-largest]] city, with a population of 470,839, and is the headquarters of [[Gaya district]] and [[Magadh division]]. The city is surrounded on three sides by small, rocky hills ([[Mangla Gauri|Mangla-Gauri]], Shringa-Sthan, Ram-Shila, and Brahmayoni), with the [[Phalgu|Phalgu River]] on its fourth (eastern) side.\n\nGaya is sanctified in the [[Jain]], [[Hindu]], and [[Buddhist]] religions. Gaya district is mentioned in the great epics, the ''[[Ramayana]]'' and the ''[[Mahabharata]]''. It is the place where [[Rama]], with [[Sita]] and [[Lakshmana]], came to offer [[Pinda (riceball)|pind-daan]] for their father, Dasharath, and continues to be a major Hindu pilgrimage site for the pind-daan ritual. [[Bodh Gaya]], where [[Buddha]] is said to have attained [[Enlightenment in Buddhism|enlightenment]], and is one of the four holy sites of [[Buddhism]]. The [[Mahabodhi Temple]] complex at Bodh Gaya is a [[World Heritage site]].\n\n==Etymology==\nGaya is one of the best historical sites in India. Gaya is named after the demon ''Gayasur'' (meaning \"the demon Gaya\"). According to [[Vayu Purana]], Gaya was the name of a demon ([[Asura]]) whose body became pious after he performed strict penance and secured blessings from Lord [[Vishnu]].<ref name=MSME /> It was said that the body of Gayasura was transformed into the series of rocky hills that make up the landscape of Gaya.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.harekrsna.com/philosophy/associates/demons/vishnu/gayasur.htm |title=The Hare Krsnas - Battles of Vishnu Avatars - Gayasur |publisher=Harekrsna.com |accessdate=2016-01-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115138/http://www.harekrsna.com/philosophy/associates/demons/vishnu/gayasur.htm |archivedate=4 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Gayasisa1.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Brahmayoni Hill, where Buddha preached the ''[[Fire Sermon|Adittapariyaya Sutta]]'' (the ''Fire Sermon'').]]\n\n===Ancient history===\nAccording to modern scholars, the [[Kikata Kingdom|Kikata kingdom]] from rigvedic period was located at Gaya, Bihar.\n\nGaya is an ancient city, with a Buddhist documented history dating back to the 6th century BCE when the sage [[Gautama Buddha]] attained enlightenment at [[Bodh Gaya]], {{convert|16|km|abbr=on}} from the modern city, and became the [[Buddha (title)|Buddha]].<ref name=\"Nomination\">{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/uploads/nominations/1056rev.pdf |title=World Heritage Scanned Nomination - Site Name: Mahabodhi Temple Complex at Bodh Gaya |last=World Heritage Committee |website=www.whc.unesco.org |date=29 June 2002 |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nEven before this time, Gaya was a place of pilgrimage for people from around the world. The fame of ancient Gaya derived from the account in the ''[[Ramayana]]'' of the  god [[Rama]] coming here to the banks of [[Phalgu|Phalgu River]] (called the [[Niranjana]]), accompanied by his wife and younger brother, to offer [[Pinda (riceball)|pind-daan]] for their father [[Dasharatha]], for the [[moksha]] of his soul.<ref name=\"R\u00e1may\u00e1n\">{{cite book |last=Griffith |first=Ralph T. H. |title=The R\u00e1may\u00e1n of V\u00e1lm\u00edki Translated into English Verse |publisher= London: Tr\u00fcbner & Co.; Benares: E. J. Lazarus and Co |date=1870-1874 |page=761 |url= https://www.gutenberg.org/files/24869/24869-pdf.pdf#page=761}}</ref><ref name='pind daan'>{{cite book |last=Bhalla |first=Prem D |title= Hindu Rites, Rituals, Customs and Traditions: A to Z on the Hindu Way of Life |publisher= Pustak Mahal |date=2006 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MOgAnbOmu08C&pg=PT307&lpg=PT307&dq=pind+daan&source=bl&ots=WQj4gS8wxk&sig=ySbZEo66vvlIQkTtS6WHhg1vNMU&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwijrvecr9ndAhUKL8AKHcHKAIA4HhDoATAGegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=pind%20daan&f=false|pages=314\u2013319 |chapter=Chapter N6-N7: What is the importance of pind daan for the deceased?; What is the purpose of the Shraddh ceremony? |isbn=978-8-122-30902-7 |access-date=28 September 2018 }}</ref> In the ''[[Mahabharata]]'', Gaya is referred to as Gayapuri.\n\nGaya flourished in the [[Maurya Empire]] (321\u2013187 BCE), which ruled from the city of [[Pataliputra]] (adjacent to modern [[Patna]]) over an area that extended beyond the Indian subcontinent. During this period, Gaya witnessed the rise and fall of many dynasties in the [[Magadha]] region, where it occupied an important place in cultural history over some 2,400 years between the 6th century BCE and the 18th century CE.\n\nThe city's cultural significance began with the dynasty founded by Sisunaga, who exercised power over Patna and Gaya around 600 BCE. [[Bimbisara]], fifth king of the dynasty, who lived and ruled around 519 BCE, had projected Gaya to the outer world. Having attained an important place in the history of civilization, the area experienced the influence of Gautama Buddha and Bhagwan Mahavir during the reign of Bimbisara. After a brief period under the [[Nanda Empire|Nanda dynasty]] (345\u2013321 BCE), Gaya and the entire Magadha region came under Mauryan rule. Mauryan Emperor [[Ashoka]] (272\u2013232 BCE) embraced and promoted Buddhism. He visited Gaya, and built the first temple at Bodh Gaya to commemorate the [[Buddha]]'s attainment of supreme enlightenment.<ref name='UNESCO WHC'>{{cite web |url= https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1056 |title= Mahabodhi Temple Complex at Bodh Gaya, Description |website=www.whc.unesco.org |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |access-date=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe period of Hindu revivalism began with the [[Gupta Empire]] during the 4th and 5th centuries CE. [[Samudragupta]] of Magadha brought Gaya into the limelight, making it the capital of Bihar district during the Gupta empire.\n\nIn 750 CE, Gaya became a part of the [[Pala Empire]], under the rule of its founder, [[Gopala]]. It is believed that the present temple of Bodh Gaya was built during the reign of Gopala's son, Dharmapala.\n\nIn the 12th century CE, Gaya was invaded by [[Muhammad Bakhtiyar Khilji]] of the [[Ghaznavid Empire]]. By 1557, it had become part of the [[Mughal Empire]], and remained under its power until the [[Battle of Buxar]] and the beginning of [[British Raj|British rule]] in 1764. Gaya, along with other parts of the country, gained its independence in 1947.\n\n===Modern history===\nAs attested by [[Francis Buchanan-Hamilton]] in the early nineteenth century, the city was divided into two areas: a sacred area in the southern part of the city, called Gaya; and the larger secular area, which may have been known by the Muslim community as Allahabad. During the [[British Raj|British rule]], the commercial and administrative area of the secular zone was formally named Saheb Ganj by British policy reformer [[Thomas Law (1756\u20131834)|Thomas Law]], who was a district officer in Gaya in the late nineteenth century.<ref name='Vidyarthi'>{{cite book |last=Vidyarthi |first=Lalita Prasad |title=The Sacred Complex in Hindu Gaya |publisher=Concept Publishing Company |edition=2nd |date=1978 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=S4FidiusPr0C&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=gaya+priests+district&source=bl&ots=C-SjM5JD0j&sig=dQ7Ocyj2wyAm07DU2yG-d02-WEI&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtwvqyrN3dAhXSxIUKHRE9CMgQ6AEwCHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=gaya%20priests%20district&f=false\n|pages=1\u201329 |chapter=Chapter 1: The Sacred Centres of Gaya |isbn=978-1-234-56789-7 |access-date=28 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Swami Sahajanand Saraswati]], founder of the [[All India Kisan Sabha]] peasant movement in 1936, established an ashram at [[Neyamatpur]], Gaya, which later became the centre of the freedom struggle in [[Bihar]]. Many prominent leaders of the [[Indian National Congress]] visited frequently to meet [[Pandit Yadunandan (Jadunandan) Sharma|Yadunandan (Jadunandan) Sharma]] when he was leader of Kisan Sabha, residing in the ashram set up by Swamiji. Yadunandan Sharma became the leader of the peasants of [[Gaya district]] and second-in-command to Swami Sahajanand Saraswati.\n\nGaya played a significant role in the [[Indian Independence Movement]]. From 26 to 31 December 1922, the 37th session of the [[Indian National Congress]] was held in Gaya<ref>{{cite news |last=Indian National Congress |date=1923 |title=Report of the Thirty-Seventh Indian National Congress held at Gaya on the 26th, 27th, 29th, 30th and 31st December 1922 |url=https://dspace.gipe.ac.in/xmlui/handle/10973/17967https://dspace.gipe.ac.in/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10973/17967/GIPE-038654-Contents.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y |access-date=26 September 2018 }}</ref> under the presidency of [[Chittaranjan Das|Deshbandhu Chittaranjan Das]]. It was attended by prominent leaders and luminaries of the Independence Movement, including [[Mahatma Gandhi|Mohandas K. Gandhi]], [[Rajendra Prasad|Dr. Rajendra Prasad]], [[Anugrah Narayan Sinha|Dr. Anugrah Narayan Sinha]], [[Sardar Patel]], [[Maulana Azad]], [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] and [[Sri Krishna Sinha]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Roy |first=Evelyn |date=1923 |title=Politics in Gaya |format=PDF |url=https://dspace.gipe.ac.in/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10973/17967/GIPE-038654-Contents.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y | work=The Communist International, Organ of the Executive Committee of the Communist International, English Edition |location=London, England |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nGaya is the birthplace of eminent nationalist ''[[Honorary titles of Indian leaders|Bihar Vibhuti]]'', [[Anugrah Narayan Sinha|Dr. Anugrah Narayan Sinha]], Bihar's first [[Deputy Chief Minister of Bihar|deputy Chief Minister]] and Finance Minister. Former Bihar Chief Minister [[Satyendra Narayan Sinha]] also hailed from Gaya. Shri Ishwar Chaudhary, a member of the [[5th Lok Sabha|Fifth]], [[6th Lok Sabha|Sixth]] and [[9th Lok Sabha|Ninth]] [[Lok Sabha]]s from 1971 to 1979 and from 1989 to 1991, represented the Gaya constituency of Bihar.\n\n==Administration==\nUntil 1864, Gaya was a part of the district of Behar and Ramgarh (now in the state of [[Jharkhand]]). It became a district of Bihar in its own right on 3 October 1865.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/gaya-celebrates-154th-establishment-day/articleshow/66059602.cms|title=Gaya celebrates 154th establishment day}}</ref> In May 1981, the Bihar state government created the [[Magadh division]], comprising the district of [[Gaya district|Gaya]], along with [[Nawada district|Nawada]], [[Aurangabad district, Bihar|Aurangabad]] and [[Jehanabad district|Jehanabad]], all of which had originally been sub-divisions when Gaya district was created.<ref name=MSME /> Aurangabad and Nawada were partitioned from the territory of Gaya in 1976; and Jehanabad in 1988.<ref name='Statoids'>{{cite web | url = http://www.statoids.com/yin.html | title = Districts of India | accessdate = 2011-10-11 | last = Law | first = Gwillim | date = 2011-09-25 | work = Statoids | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111017155710/http://www.statoids.com/yin.html | archivedate = 2011-10-17 }}</ref> Gaya district occupies an area of 4,976&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (1,921 mile<sup>2</sup>).<ref name=MSME />\n\n==Culture==\n===Pilgrimage===\n\nThe city of Gaya is a holy place of [[Hinduism]], with a great number of [[Hindu deities]] represented in the engravings, paintings and carvings of its shrines. Of particular importance are the sites in the city associated with [[Vishnu]], in particular the [[Phalgu|Phalgu River]] and the shrine [[Vishnupad Mandir]], or Vishnupada, which is marked by a large footprint of Lord Vishnu engraved in a basalt block.<ref name='Vidyarthi'/> Gaya is the location at which Rama, with Sita and Lakshmana, offered pind-daan for his father, Dasharatha. Gaya has since remained a site of key importance for the performance of the pind-daan ritual.<ref name=\"R\u00e1may\u00e1n\"/><ref name='pind daan'/>\n\n\nGaya is considered to be one of the most ideal places to perform the shraddh. (A shraddh is the Hindu ritual that one performs to pay homage to one's \u2018ancestors\u2019, especially to one's dead parents). As per Hindu belief system, it is believed that a person goes to hell if he dies in the following circumstances - if he meets an accidental death, if he dies without his consecrations being performed, or if he is killed by a wild animal. But, if \u2018Shraddh rituals\u2019 of that person are performed at \u2018Gaya\u2019 then the soul of such a man will get rid of the tortures of the hell and will go to heaven. Performing \u2018Shraddh rituals\u2019 here is of great importance as it helps one to get rid of \u2018pitra rinna\u2019 i.e. debts towards one's ancestors (male forefathers). \n\nNearby Bodh Gaya (\"Buddha Gaya\"), so named to distinguish it from the Hindu town centre of Gaya, is one of the four holiest sites of Buddhism and the site where the Buddha attained enlightenment.<ref name='UNESCO WHC' /><ref name='Vidyarthi'/>\n\n===World Heritage site at Bodh Gaya===\n\nThe [[Mahabodhi Temple|Mahabodhi Temple Complex at Bodh Gaya]] was listed as a [[World Heritage site]] by the [[World Heritage Committee]] of the [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO)]] at its 26th session, on 26 June 2002.<ref name='UNESCO WHC'/>\n\nThe {{convert|50|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} Mahabodhi Temple central to the complex was first built by the emperor [[Ashoka]] in the 3rd century BCE. The main part of the present structure dates from the 5th\u20136th centuries CE. It is one of the earliest and best-preserved Buddhist temples built entirely of brick dating from the later [[Gupta Empire|Gupta]] period. The [[Bodhi Tree]] (''Ficus religiosa''), the most important of the sacred places within the complex, is reputedly a descendant of the original tree under which Siddh\u0101rtha Gautama attained [[Enlightenment in Buddhism|enlightenment]] and became the [[Buddha]].<ref name='UNESCO WHC'/> Marking this seminal moment, Bodh Gaya is one of the four holiest pilgrimage sites of Buddhism, with [[Lumbini]], [[Sarnath]] and [[Kushinagar]].<ref name='ICCROM'/>\n\nThe various structures on the site have undergone a number of restorations over the centuries. Ongoing maintenance and management is required to protect the complex which, as a major pilgrimage site, is under pressure due to large numbers of visitors.<ref name='ICCROM'>{{cite book |last=Lambah |first=Abha Narain |last2=Dorje |first2=Nangze |editor-last1=Wijesuriya |editor-first1=Gamini |editor-last2=Lee |editor-first2=Sujeong |title=ICCROM-CHA Conservation Forum Series: First ICCROM-CHA International Forum on Conservation Asian Buddhist Heritage: Conserving the Sacred |publisher= ICCROM, International Centre for the Study of the Preservation and Restoration of Cultural Property|date=2017 |pages=103\u2013111 |chapter=Chapter 13: Challenges of managing a living Buddhist site: Mahabodhi Temple, Bodh Gaya, India | isbn=978-92-9077-240-8|url= https://www.iccrom.org/sites/default/files/2017-11/asianbuddhist_web.pdf |access-date=27 September 2018}}</ref> The site is under the responsibility of the state government of Bihar, and is managed by the Bodhgaya Temple Management Committee (BTMC) and Advisory Board under the Bodh Gaya Temple Act, 1949.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bodhgayatemple.com/images/pdf/temple_act.pdf |title= The Bodh Gaya Temple Act, 1949 (Bihar Act of 17 of 1949), (as modified up to the 8th February, 1955) |website= www.bodhgayatemple.com |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nAs Gaya is surrounded by hills on three sides and river on the fourth side, the climate of Gaya is seasonable. Climate is characterised by relatively high temperatures and evenly distributed rainfall throughout the year.  The [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] sub-type for this climate is \"[[Humid subtropical climate|Cwa]]\" (humid subtropical).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=590718&cityname=Gaya%2C+Bihar%2C+India&units= |title=Climate Summary for Gaya, India |publisher=Weatherbase.com |accessdate=2016-01-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323021216/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=590718&cityname=Gaya%2C+Bihar%2C+India&units= |archivedate=23 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gaya, India \n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan high F = 75\n|Feb high F = 80\n|Mar high F = 92\n|Apr high F = 102\n|May high F = 105\n|Jun high F = 101\n|Jul high F = 92\n|Aug high F = 90\n|Sep high F = 91\n|Oct high F = 89\n|Nov high F = 84\n|Dec high F = 80\n|year high F = 90\n|Jan low F = 50\n|Feb low F = 55\n|Mar low F = 64\n|Apr low F = 74\n|May low F = 80\n|Jun low F = 82\n|Jul low F = 79\n|Aug low F = 78\n|Sep low F = 77\n|Oct low F = 71\n|Nov low F = 58\n|Dec low F = 53\n|year low F = 68\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.8\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.8\n|Mar precipitation inch = 0.5\n|Apr precipitation inch = 0.3\n|May precipitation inch = 0.8\n|Jun precipitation inch = 5.4\n|Jul precipitation inch = 12.4\n|Aug precipitation inch = 12.9\n|Sep precipitation inch = 8.1\n|Oct precipitation inch = 2.1\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.4\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.1\n|year precipitation inch = 44.5\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=Weatherbase>\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=590718&cityname=Gaya-Bihar-India\n |publisher   = Weatherbase\n |title       = Weatherbase.com\n |year        = 2013\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20150403090837/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=590718&cityname=Gaya-Bihar-India\n |archivedate = 3 April 2015\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\nRetrieved on 31 July 2016.\n</ref>\n|date=July 2013\n}}\n==Border Covering==\nEast-  Nawada\nWest-  AurangaBad\nNorth- Jehanabad\nSouth- Covering Jharkhand State Border\n==Economy==\nGaya is the second-largest contributor to the [[economy of Bihar]], after Patna. Agriculture is the leading economic activity of the district. The main crops grown are rice, wheat, potatoes, and lentils. Livestock raised include cattle, buffaloes, goats and pigs. Gaya has a large number of household industries, producing [[Incense in India|incense sticks]] (atagarbatti), local sweets [[tilkut]] (made with sesame seed) and lai (made with poppy seed), stone-work, hand weaving, power-loom weaving, textiles and garments, small-scale manufactured goods, and plastic products. Small-scale industries also include agricultural services, metalworking, machinery and equipment production and repair services.<ref name=\"MSME\">{{cite news |last= MSME-Development Institute, Ministry of MSME, Government of India |date=2011 |title= Brief Industrial Profile of Gaya District \u2013 Micro, Small & Medium Enterprises |url=http://dcmsme.gov.in/dips/gaya_bihar.pdf |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref> The main vegetable market in the city is the Kedarnath Market. Commercial activities are located along its main roads; the city also has a large number of informal shops.<ref name=\"Udyog Mitra\">{{cite web |url=https://www.udyogmitrabihar.in/docs/dp/gaya.pdf |title=Bihar \u2013 Economic Profile Gaya |last=Udyog Mitra, Department of Industries |publisher=Government of Bihar|date=2011 |website=www.udyogmitrabihar.in |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref> As Gaya is an important centre of religious tourism, accommodation is widely available.<ref name=\"Geary\">{{cite book |last=Geary | first=David |title=The Rebirth of Bodh Gaya: Buddhism and the Making of a World Heritage Site |publisher= University of Washington Press |date=2017 |page=159 |section=Buddhist Circuits and Spiritual Tourism (in Chapter 5: A Master Plan for World Heritage) |isbn=978-0-295-74238-0 | url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=meA5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=tourist+infrastructure+gaya&source=bl&ots=0z79pQXHFu&sig=fTFqoeWgY7LzEyTiwzCpQn56u3Y&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwju_4PT1dvdAhUFQhoKHbhiAxAQ6AEwB3oECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=tourist%20infrastructure%20gaya&f=false }}</ref> Bodh Gaya's largest hotel is the Maha Bodhi Hotel, Resort & Convention Centre; the Sambodhi Retreat, a resort of Bihar and Jharkhand, is also in the town.\n\nIn January 2015, Gaya was chosen as one of twelve heritage cities to benefit from the Government of India's four-year [[Heritage City Development and Augmentation Yojana]] (HRIDAY) scheme for urban planning, economic growth and heritage conservation projects.<ref>{{cite news |last= HRIDAY National Project Management Unit, National Institute of Urban Affairs, Ministry of Urban Development Government of India |date=21 January 2015 |title= Heritage City Development and Augmentation Yojana |url=https://hridayindia.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/hriday-brochure.pdf |website=www.hridayindia.in |access-date=26 September 2018 }}</ref> The scheme is due to complete in November 2018.{{update after|2018|11|30|date=November 2018}}<ref>{{cite news |last= HRIDAY National Project Management Unit, National Institute of Urban Affairs |title= HRIDAY-Rejuvenating the Soul of Urban India-Heritage City Development and Augmentation Yojana |url= https://hridayindia.in |website=www.hridayindia.in |access-date=26 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Gaya<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/181-gaya.html|title=Gaya City Census 2011 data|work=Census 2011 India|accessdate=7 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507141025/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/181-gaya.html|archivedate=7 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|79.43}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|19.65}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|blue|0.26}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jains]]|pink|0.24}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|1.42}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n\u2020<small>Includes [[Sikh]]s (0.09%), [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (0.02%).</small>\n}}\nIn the 2011 census, the Gaya Urban Agglomeration had a population of 474,093.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | title = Urban Agglomerations/Cities having population 1 lakh and above | work = Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011 | accessdate = 2012-04-16 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111113152754/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | archivedate = 13 November 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The Gaya Urban Agglomeration encompasses the Gaya [[Municipal corporations in India|Municipal Corporation]], Kaler ([[Out Growth]]), and Paharpur ([[Census town#India|Census Town]]).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_4_PR_UAs_1Lakh_and_Above_Appendix.pdf | title = Constituents of urban Agglomerations Having Population 1 Lakh & above | work = Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011 | accessdate = 2012-04-16 | url-status = live | archiveurl = http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160617063229/http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_4_PR_UAs_1Lakh_and_Above_Appendix.pdf | archivedate = 17 June 2016 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> the Gaya Municipal Corporation had a total population of 468,614,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.de/php/india-bihar.php?adm2id=1034 |title=Gaya, District in Bihar - The population development of Gaya|accessdate=2016-07-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914184017/http://www.citypopulation.de/php/india-bihar.php?adm2id=1034 |archivedate=14 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> of whom 247,572 were male and 221,042 were female. The population below 5 years was 59,669. The sex ratio was 986 women to 1000 men. The literacy rate for the population aged 7 and over was 85.74%.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | title = Cities having population 1 lakh and above | work = Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011 | accessdate = 2012-04-16 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120507135928/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | archivedate = 7 May 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nGaya is connected to the rest of India by roads, rail and airways. The [[Grand Chord]] section of the Indian Railways passes through Gaya.\n\n===Local transport===\nThere are many city buses and taxis providing services across the city and Bodh Gaya. [[Tanga (carriage)|Tangas]], [[auto rickshaw]]s, and cycle rickshaws also ply the city and Bodh Gaya. The main bus stands are Government Bus Stand, Sikaria More Bus Stand, Gaurkashni Bus Stand (Manpur), and Delha Bus Stand. Local transport is reliable, and auto rickshaws are available for various destinations in the city. The Gaya\u2013Patna railway line plays a major role in transporting people from the town to the state capital.\n\n===Roadways===\nGaya has a road network providing good connectivity with the state of Bihar and other parts of the country.<ref name=CDP>{{cite web |url= http://urban.bih.nic.in/Docs/CDP/CDP-Gaya.pdf |title= City Development Plan (2010-30) Gaya: Executive Summary |last=Egis India Consulting Engineers Private Limited |publisher= Urban Development and Housing Department Government of Biha |website=www.urban.bih.nic.in |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref> Regular direct bus services run from Gaya to [[Patna]], [[Bhagalpur]], [[Munger]], [[Nalanda]], [[Rajgir]], [[Varanasi]], [[Ranchi]], [[Jamshedpur]], [[Hazaribagh]], [[Durgapur]], [[Asansol]], [[Kolkata]] and [[Dhanbad]]. In 2011, {{abbr|A/C|air-conditioned}} [[Mercedes-Benz]] luxury services were introduced by [[Bihar State Road Transport Corporation]] for [[Muzaffarpur]], [[Patna]], [[Munger]], [[Bhagalpur]], [[Motihari]], [[Hazaribagh]], [[Koderma]], and Ramgarh.\n\nThe [[Grand Trunk Road]] from [[Kolkata]] to [[Delhi]] passes from \"Dobhi\"some {{convert|30|km|abbr=on}} from Gaya. This road, known as [[National Highway 2 (India, old numbering)|National Highway 2]] before 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dorth.gov.in/writereaddata/sublinkimages/finaldoc6143316640.pdf|title=Rationalisation of Numbering Systems of National Highways|publisher=[[Department of Road Transport and Highways]]|accessdate=27 September 2018|location=New Delhi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201124738/http://dorth.gov.in/writereaddata/sublinkimages/finaldoc6143316640.pdf|archive-date=1 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> is now called [[National Highway 19 (India)|National Highway 19]]. It connects Gaya to [[Patna]], [[Ranchi]], [[Jamshedpur]], [[Bokaro Steel City|Bokaro]], [[Rourkela]], [[Durgapur, West Bengal|Durgapur]], [[Kolkata]] (495&nbsp;km), [[Varanasi]] (252&nbsp;km), [[Allahabad]], [[Kanpur]], [[Delhi]], [[Amritsar]], and to the Pakistani cities of [[Lahore]] and [[Peshawar]]. Gaya is connected to Patna (105&nbsp;km) by [[National Highway 22 (India)|National Highway 22]] (formerly NH 83), and to Nawada, Rajgir (78&nbsp;km) and [[Bihar Sharif]] by [[National Highway 120 (India)|NH 120]]. Construction work began in 2014 on the road from Patna to Dobhi via Gaya and Gaya to Bihar Sharif to create a four-lane highway with additional road and bridge infrastructure. Completion of the project, originally due in April 2018, has been delayed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Qadir |first=Abdul |date=25 April 2018 |title=Dobhi-Patna road project delayed |url= https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/dobhi-patna-road-project-delayed/articleshow/63900929.cms |work=The Times of India |location=India |access-date=28 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Railways===\n[[Gaya Junction]] railway station is a [[junction station]] serving the city. Gaya Junction was the only station in Bihar and Jharkhand in the list of 66 stations to be built to international standards drawn up by [[Minister of Railways (India)|Minister of Railways]]  [[Mamata Banerjee]]. Gaya falls under the jurisdiction of the [[Mughalsarai railway division]] of the [[East Central Railway zone]]. The [[Grand Chord]] rail line that connects [[Howrah]] and [[New Delhi]] passes through Gaya. It lies between [[Mughalsarai Junction railway station|Mughalsarai Junction]] on the [[Delhi]] side and [[Dhanbad Junction railway station|Dhanbad Junction]] on the [[Howrah railway station|Howrah]] side. It is located at {{Coord|24|48|13|N|84|59|57|E|}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wikimapia.org/13242471/Gaya-Junction-Rail-Station-ER |title=Gaya Junction |publisher=Wikimapia |accessdate=2011-12-01 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210110843/http://wikimapia.org/13242471/Gaya-Junction-Rail-Station-ER |archivedate=10 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It has an elevation of {{Convert|117|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"train list\">{{cite web|title=Trains at Gaya|url=http://indiarailinfo.com/arrivals/1388|publisher=India Rail Info|accessdate=1 April 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111208132627/http://indiarailinfo.com/arrivals/1388|archivedate=8 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=indiantrains>{{cite web|title=Ghanbad Junction Railway Station Details |url=http://www.indiantrains.org/station-details/?code=GAYA&name=DHANBAD+JN |publisher=indiantrains.org |accessdate=1 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408222802/http://www.indiantrains.org/station-details/?code=GAYA&name=DHANBAD+JN |archivedate=8 April 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Airport===\n{{Main|Gaya Airport}}\nSituated between Gaya (7&nbsp;km) and [[Bodh Gaya]] (11&nbsp;km), [[Gaya Airport]] is the large airport by area, and one of two operating international airports in the states of Bihar and Jharkhand. It is the second-busiest airport in Bihar, after Patna's [[Jay Prakash Narayan Airport]]. Gaya airport mainly operates seasonal flights for Buddhist pilgrims to Bodh Gaya from [[Colombo]], Sri Lanka; [[Bangkok]], Thailand; [[Singapore]], and [[Paro, Bhutan|Paro]], Bhutan.  There are also regular domestic flights to Varanasi, Kolkata and Delhi. The Airports Authority of India has plans to develop Gaya Airport as a stand-by to the [[Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose International Airport]] in Kolkata.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.aai.aero/en/node/74281|title= Gaya Airport |website= www.aai.aero |last=Airports Authority of India |access-date=27 September 2018}}</ref>Gaya Airport also Serves as only place of Bihar from where Haj Pilgrimage take direct flight to Holy City of Makkah And Madina.Gaya International Airport has only Immigration Counter in Bihar.\n\n==Education==\n\nNotable institutions of higher education include:\n\n*[[Indian Institute of Management Bodh Gaya]] 11&nbsp;km from City HEADQUARTER\n*[[Gaya College]] \n*[[Gaya College of Engineering]]\n*[[Magadh University]] 10&nbsp;km from District HEADQUARTER\n*[[Central University of South Bihar]] 14&nbsp;km from City HEADQUARTER\n*[[Anugrah Narayan Magadh Medical College and Hospital]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"census2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|title=UA/Cities 1 lakh and above|publisher=Government of India|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113152754/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf|archivedate=13 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[https://gayamahanagar.com Reference in hindi about Gaya] \n{{commons category|Gaya, India}}\n\n* [https://www.tentaran.com/the-significance-of-gaya-shraddh-in-hindu-death-rituals/ Significance of performing shradh in Gaya]\n\n<nowiki/>*{{ppn|g/gayaa.htm|Gaya}}\n* {{Suttas|Gaya|gandhabhaka|sn/sn35/sn35.028.than.html Adittapariyaya Sutta \u2013 The Fire|mn/mn.007.nypo.html#gaya Verse from the Vatthupama Sutta \u2013 The Simile of the Cloth}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Gaya}}\n\n{{Bihar}}\n{{Hindu holy cities}}\n{{Magadh Division}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu pilgrimage sites in India]]\n[[Category:Buddhist pilgrimage sites in India]]\n[[Category:Hindu holy cities]]\n[[Category:Early Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Gautama Buddha]]\n[[Category:Gaya, India| ]]\n", "name_user": "157.43.98.133", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I changed the other name of Gaya)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaya,_India"}
{"title_page": "Disrupted planet", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{short description|planet or related being destroyed by a passing object}}\n[[File:Artist's impression of a white dwarf devouring a minor planet.jpg|thumb|right|250px|<center>Artist concept of a rocky planetary object being vaporized by its parent star</center>]]\nIn [[astronomy]], a '''disrupted planet'''<ref name=\"SN-20171222\">{{cite web |author=Staff |title=Young Star RZ Piscium is 'Eating' Its Own Planets, Astronomers Say |url=http://www.sci-news.com/astronomy/young-star-rz-piscium-eating-planets-05561.html |date=22 December 2017 |work=Sci-News.com |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"IU-20171221\">{{cite web |last=Fryling |first=Kevin |title=IU astronomer's analysis helps discover that a star in the constellation Pisces is a 'planet-eater' |url=https://news.iu.edu/stories/2017/12/iub/21-science-planet-eating-star.html |date=21 December 2017 |work=[[Indiana University]] |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}</ref> is a [[planet]], or [[exoplanet]] or, perhaps on a somewhat smaller scale, a [[moon]] or [[exomoon]], that has been disrupted, or destroyed, by a nearby, or passing, astronomical body or object, such as a [[star]].<ref name=\"SN-20171222\" /><ref name=\"IU-20171221\" /> '''Necroplanetology''' is the related study of such a process.<ref name=\"SA-20200328\">{{cite news |last=Starr |first=Michelle |title=Necroplanetology: The Strangest Field of Astronomy You've Never Heard Of |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/necroplanetology-the-study-of-planets-dismembered-remains |date=28 March 2020 |work=ScienceAlert.com |accessdate=30 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"ARX-20200318\">{{cite arxiv |last1=Duvvuri |first1=Girish M. |last2=Redfield |first2=Seth |last3=Veras |first3=Dimitri |title=Necroplanetology: Simulating the Tidal Disruption of Differentiated Planetary Material Orbiting WD 1145+017 |arxiv=2003.08410 |date=18 March 2020 |arxiv=2003.08410 |accessdate=30 March 2020 }}</ref> Nonetheless, the result of such a disruption may be the production of excessive amounts of related gas, [[Cosmic dust|dust]] and debris,<ref name=\"AJ-20171221\">{{cite journal |last1=Punzi |first1=K. M. |last2=Kastner |first2=J. H. |last3=Melis |first3=C. |last4=Zuckerman |first4=B. |last5=Pilachowski |first5=C. |last6=Gingerich |first6=L. |last7=Knapp |first7=T. |title=Is the Young Star RZ Piscium Consuming Its Own (Planetary) Offspring? |doi=10.3847/1538-3881/aa9524 |date=21 December 2017 |journal=[[The Astronomical Journal]] |volume=155 |pages=33 |number=1 |bibcode=2018AJ....155...33P |arxiv=1712.08962 }}</ref> that may eventually surround the parent star in the form of a [[circumstellar disk]] or [[debris disk]]. As a consequence, the orbiting debris field may be an \"[[KIC 8462852#Circumstellar dust ring|uneven ring of dust]]\", causing erratic light fluctuations in the apparent [[luminosity]] of the parent star, as may have been responsible for the oddly flickering [[light curve]]s associated with the starlight observed from certain [[variable star]]s, such as that from  [[KIC 8462852]], [[RZ Piscium]] and [[WD 1145+017]].<ref name=\"SA-20200328\" /><ref name=\"ARX-20200318\" /> Excessive amounts of [[Infrared|infrared radiation]] may be detected from such stars,<ref name=\"ARX-201090310\">{{Cite journal|last1=Farihi |first1=J. |last2=Jura |first2=M. |last3=Zuckerman |first3=B. |title=Infrared Signatures of Disrupted Minor Planets at White Dwarfs |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=694 |issue=2 |pages=805\u2013819 |date=10 March 2009 |arxiv=0901.0973|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/694/2/805 |bibcode=2009ApJ...694..805F }}</ref> suggestive evidence in itself that dust and debris may be orbiting the stars.<ref name=\"AJ-20171221\" /><ref name=\"NASA-20171004\">{{cite web |last=Landau |first=Elizabeth |title=Mysterious Dimming of Tabby's Star May Be Caused by Dust |url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=6963 |date=4 October 2017 |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"ApJ-20171003\">{{cite journal |author=Meng, Huan Y.A.|display-authors=et al |title=Extinction and the Dimming of KIC 8462852 |date=3 October 2017 |journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]] |volume=847 |number=2 |page=131 |doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aa899c |bibcode=2017ApJ...847..131M |arxiv=1708.07556 }}</ref><ref name=\"PHY-20171005\">{{cite web |last=Tabor |first=Abby |title=The scientific quest to explain Kepler's most enigmatic find |url=https://phys.org/news/2017-10-scientific-quest-kepler-enigmatic.html |date=5 October 2017 |work=[[Phys.org]] |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n===Planets===\nExamples of planets (or their related remnants), considered to have been a disrupted planet, or part of such a planet, include:  [['Oumuamua]]<ref name=\"ARX-2017\">{{Cite journal|last=\u0106uk |first=Matija |arxiv=1712.01823 |title=1I/\u02bbOumuamua as a Tidal Disruption Fragment From a Binary Star System |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=852 |issue=1 |pages=L15 |date=2017 |doi=10.3847/2041-8213/aaa3db |bibcode=2018ApJ...852L..15C }}</ref> and [[WD 1145+017 b]], as well as [[asteroid]]s,<ref name=\"ARX-20060816\">{{cite journal |last=Soter |first=Steven |title=What is a Planet? |date=2006 |journal= The Astronomical Journal|volume=132 |issue=6 |pages=2513\u20132519 |arxiv=astro-ph/0608359 |doi=10.1086/508861|bibcode=2006AJ....132.2513S }}</ref> [[hot Jupiter]]s<ref name=\"MNRAS-20110920\">{{cite journal |last=Nayakshin |first=Sergei |title=Hot Super Earths: disrupted young jupiters? |url=https://academic.oup.com/mnras/article/416/4/2974/976497 |date=20 September 2011 |journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]] |volume=416 |issue=4 |pages=2974\u20132980 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2011.19246.x |accessdate=25 December 2017 |bibcode=2011MNRAS.416.2974N |arxiv=1103.1846 }}</ref> and those that are [[hypothetical planet]]s, like [[Fifth planet (hypothetical)|Fifth planet]], [[Phaeton (hypothetical planet)|Phaeton]], [[Planet V]] and [[Theia (planet)|Theia]].\n\n===Stars===\nExamples of parent stars, considered to have caused a planet to have been disrupted, include: [[EPIC 204278916]], [[KIC 8462852]] (Tabby's Star), [[PDS 110]], [[RZ Piscium]], [[WD 1145+017]] and [[47 Ursae Majoris]].\n[[File:PIA22081-KIC8462852-TabbysStar-UnevenDustRing-Illustration-20171004.png|thumb|center|500px|<center>Artist concept of an \"[[KIC 8462852#Circumstellar dust ring|uneven ring of dust]]\" surrounding [[KIC 8462852]].</center>]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==KIC 8462852 light curve==\n[[KIC 8462852]] is an [[F-type main-sequence star]] exhibiting unusual light fluctuations, including up to a 22% dimming in brightness.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boyajian|first=T. S.|last2=LaCourse|first2=D. M.|last3=Rappaport|first3=S. A.|last4=Fabrycky|first4=D.|last5=Fischer|first5=D. A.|last6=Gandolfi|first6=D.|last7=Kennedy|first7=G. M.|last8=Korhonen|first8=H.|last9=Liu|first9=M. C.|date=2016-01-27|title=Planet Hunters IX. KIC&nbsp;8462852 \u2013 where's the flux?|url=https://academic.oup.com/mnras/article-abstract/457/4/3988/2589003?redirectedFrom=fulltext|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|language=en|volume=457|issue=4|pages=3988\u20134004|doi=10.1093/mnras/stw218|issn=0035-8711|arxiv=1509.03622}}</ref> Several hypotheses have been proposed to explain these irregular changes, but none to date fully explain all aspects of the curve. One explanation is that an \"[[KIC 8462852#Circumstellar dust ring|uneven ring of dust]]\" orbits KIC 8462852.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=6963|title=Mysterious Dimming of Tabby's Star May Be Caused by Dust|website=NASA/JPL|access-date=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boyajian|first=Tabetha S.|last2=Alonso|first2=Roi|last3=Ammerman|first3=Alex|last4=Armstrong|first4=David|last5=Ramos|first5=A. Asensio|last6=Barkaoui|first6=K.|last7=Beatty|first7=Thomas G.|last8=Benkhaldoun|first8=Z.|last9=Benni|first9=Paul|date=2018-01-19|title=The First Post-Kepler Brightness Dips of KIC 8462852|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=853|issue=1|pages=L8|doi=10.3847/2041-8213/aaa405|issn=2041-8213|arxiv=1801.00732}}</ref> However, in September 2019, astronomers reported that the observed dimmings of [[Tabby's Star]] may have been produced by fragments resulting from the disruption of an orphaned [[exomoon]].<ref name=\"PHYS-20190916\">{{cite news |author=Columbia University |title=New observations help explain the dimming of Tabby's Star |url=https://phys.org/news/2019-09-dimming-tabby-star.html |date=16 September 2019 |work=[[Phys.org]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |author-link=Columbia University }}</ref><ref name=\"MNRAS-20190915\">{{cite journal |last1=Marinez |first1=Miquel |last2=Stone |first2=Nicholas C. |last3=Metzger |first3=Brian D. |title=Orphaned Exomoons: Tidal Detachment and Evaporation Following an Exoplanet-Star Collision |date=5 September 2019 |journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]] |doi=10.1093/mnras/stz2464 |arxiv=1906.08788 }}</ref>\n[[File:Consolidated plot of KIC 8462852 dip maxima March 2020 update.png|thumb|center|1200px|<div align=\"center\">Consolidated plot of all known dimmings (1 March 2020)</div>]]\n\n<center><gallery widths=\"150px\">\nFile:KIC 8462852 - gesamte Helligkeitsmessung von Kepler.png|All light curve data \u2212 December 2009 to May 2013, scan days 0066 to 1587 (''Kepler'')\nFile:KIC 8462852 - Helligkeitseinbruch 05. M\u00e4rz 2011.png|5 March 2011 \u2212 day 792 <br /> 15% max dip (''Kepler'')\nFile:KIC 8462852 - Helligkeitseinbruch 28. Februar 2013.png|28 February 2013 \u2212 day 1519 <br /> 22% max dip (''Kepler'')\nFile:KIC 8462852 - Helligkeitseinbruch 17. April 2013.png|17 April 2013 \u2212 day 1568 <br /> 8% max dip (''Kepler'')\nFile:KIC 8462852 Daily Normalized Flux by Bruce Gary, 20170502-20180504.png|One year light curve \u2212<br />[[#2017 light fluctuations|up to 4 May 2018]]<br />([[Hereford Arizona Observatory|HAO]]<ref name=\"BG-20171114-latest\">{{cite web |last=Gary |first=Bruce L. |authorlink=Bruce L. Gary |title=Hereford Arizona Observatory photometry observations of KIC 8462852 |url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts5/ |date=14 November 2017 |work=BruceGary.net |accessdate=24 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"BG-20171004\">{{cite web |last=Gary |first=Bruce L. |authorlink=Bruce L. Gary |title=Hereford Arizona Observatory photometry observations of KIC 8462852 between 2 May and 4 October 2017 |url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts4/ |date=4 October 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004220716/http://www.brucegary.net/ts4/ |archivedate=4 October 2017 |work=BruceGary.net |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}<br>{{small|''\"Note: g'-band and r'-band dip depths (and shapes) may differ, with g'-band being more sensitive to dust cloud scattering due to its shorter wavelength (0.47 vs. 0.62 micron). For a reasonable particle size distribution (e.g., Hanson, 0.2 micron) the extinction cross section ratio would produce a depth at r'-band that is 0.57 x depth at g'-band. If g'-band depth is 0.3 %, for example, depth at r'-band could be 0.17 %. The \"Tabby Team\" measurements ([[:File:KIC 8462852 TS r-prime-band Normalized Flux by TabbyTeam, 20170502-20171004.png|Fig. 3]]) at r'-band are compatible with that small dip depth. Incidentally, none of these shapes resemble exo-comet tail transits (as described by Rappaport et al, 2017 [https://arxiv.org/abs/1708.06069 link]); so the mystery of what's producing these week-timescale dips continues! Actually, long oval shapes are known to produce V-shaped dips (think of rings with a high inclination).\"'' - bg}}</ref><ref name=\"BG-20180101\">{{cite web |last=Gary |first=Bruce L. |authorlink=Bruce L. Gary |title=Hereford Arizona Observatory photometry observations of KIC 8462852 between 2 May and 31 December 2017 |url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts5/ |date=1 January 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102012647/http://www.brucegary.net/ts5/ |archivedate=1 January 2018 |work=BruceGary.net |accessdate=1 January 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"BG-20180504\">{{cite web |last=Gary |first=Bruce L. |authorlink=w:Bruce L. Gary |title=Hereford Arizona Observatory photometry observations of KIC 8462852 between 2 May 2017 and 4 May 2018 |url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts6/ |date=4 May 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505143701/http://www.brucegary.net/ts6/ |archivedate=5 May 2018 |work=BruceGary.net |accessdate=5 May 2018 }}</ref><!---<br>''(<small>[http://www.brucegary.net/HAO/ HAO]=[[Hereford Arizona Observatory|HAO]]</small>)''--->)\nFile:KIC 8462852 October-December 2019 Gary.jpg|Light curve between 10 October 2019 and 11 January 2020 (HAO)<ref name=\"Gary_11Jan20\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts9/|date=11 January 2020|title=KIC 8462852 Hereford Arizona Observatory Photometry Observations #9|first=Bruce|last=Gary|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200405060559/http://www.brucegary.net/ts9/|archive-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n</gallery></center>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Asteroid belt]]\n* [[BD+20\u00b0307]]\n* [[Formation and evolution of the Solar System]]\n* [[Giant-impact hypothesis]]\n* [[Interstellar medium]]\n* [[List of stars that dim oddly]]\n* [[Nebular hypothesis]]\n* [[Planetesimal]]\n* [[Protoplanetary disk]]\n* [[Tidal force]]\n* [[WD 0145+234|WD 0145+234 (star disrupting an exoasteroid)]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|author=Wallace Gary Ernst|title=The Dynamic Planet|url=https://archive.org/details/dynamicplanet0000erns|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/dynamicplanet0000erns/page/18 18]|year=1990|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-07231-1}}\n*  {{cite book|author=Michael M. Woolfson|authorlink=Michael Woolfson|title=The Origin and Evolution of the Solar System|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KantSzMGPSkC&pg=PA316|year=2000|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-4200-3335-9}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://exoplanet.eu/catalog/WD_1145+017_b/ NASA \u2013 WD 1145+017 b] at [[Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia|The Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia]].\n* {{YouTube|gypAjPp6eps|title=Video (13:46) \u2212 \"Tabby's Star\"}}, a presentation by [[Tabetha S. Boyajian]].\n* {{YouTube|id=SVCpBr3fxdE|title=Video (31:00) \u2212 \"Tabby's Star\"}}, a presentation by Issac Arthur.\n* {{YouTube|nf2oc6nMsn4|title=Video (01:00) \u2212 RZ Piscium}}, star with unusual light fluctuations (21 December 2017).\n{{Exoplanet|state=collapsed}}\n{{portal bar|Astronomy|Solar System|Space|Star}}\n\n[[Category:Circumstellar disks|Circumstellar disks]]\n[[Category:Hypothetical astronomical objects]]\n[[Category:Objects with variable star designations|Objects with variable star designations]]\n[[Category:Planetary rings]]\n[[Category:Unsolved problems in astronomy]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{short description|planet or related being destroyed by a passing object}}\n[[File:Artist's impression of a white dwarf devouring a minor planet.jpg|thumb|right|250px|<center>Artist concept of a rocky planetary object being vaporized by its parent star</center>]]\nIn [[astronomy]], a '''disrupted planet'''<ref name=\"SN-20171222\">{{cite web |author=Staff |title=Young Star RZ Piscium is 'Eating' Its Own Planets, Astronomers Say |url=http://www.sci-news.com/astronomy/young-star-rz-piscium-eating-planets-05561.html |date=22 December 2017 |work=Sci-News.com |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"IU-20171221\">{{cite web |last=Fryling |first=Kevin |title=IU astronomer's analysis helps discover that a star in the constellation Pisces is a 'planet-eater' |url=https://news.iu.edu/stories/2017/12/iub/21-science-planet-eating-star.html |date=21 December 2017 |work=[[Indiana University]] |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}</ref> is a [[planet]], or [[exoplanet]] or, perhaps on a somewhat smaller scale, a [[moon]] or [[exomoon]], that has been disrupted, or destroyed, by a nearby, or passing, astronomical body or object, such as a [[star]].<ref name=\"SN-20171222\" /><ref name=\"IU-20171221\" /> '''Necroplanetology''' is the related study of such a process.<ref name=\"SA-20200328\">{{cite news |last=Starr |first=Michelle |title=Necroplanetology: The Strangest Field of Astronomy You've Never Heard Of |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/necroplanetology-the-study-of-planets-dismembered-remains |date=28 March 2020 |work=ScienceAlert.com |accessdate=30 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"ARX-20200318\">{{cite journal |last1=Duvvuri |first1=Girish M. |last2=Redfield |first2=Seth |last3=Veras |first3=Dimitri |title=Necroplanetology: Simulating the Tidal Disruption of Differentiated Planetary Material Orbiting WD 1145+017 |url=https://arxiv.org/abs/2003.08410 |date=18 March 2020 |journal=[[arxiv]] |arxiv=2003.08410v1 |accessdate=30 March 2020 }}</ref> Nonetheless, the result of such a disruption may be the production of excessive amounts of related gas, [[Cosmic dust|dust]] and debris,<ref name=\"AJ-20171221\">{{cite journal |last1=Punzi |first1=K. M. |last2=Kastner |first2=J. H. |last3=Melis |first3=C. |last4=Zuckerman |first4=B. |last5=Pilachowski |first5=C. |last6=Gingerich |first6=L. |last7=Knapp |first7=T. |title=Is the Young Star RZ Piscium Consuming Its Own (Planetary) Offspring? |doi=10.3847/1538-3881/aa9524 |date=21 December 2017 |journal=[[The Astronomical Journal]] |volume=155 |pages=33 |number=1 |bibcode=2018AJ....155...33P |arxiv=1712.08962 }}</ref> that may eventually surround the parent star in the form of a [[circumstellar disk]] or [[debris disk]]. As a consequence, the orbiting debris field may be an \"[[KIC 8462852#Circumstellar dust ring|uneven ring of dust]]\", causing erratic light fluctuations in the apparent [[luminosity]] of the parent star, as may have been responsible for the oddly flickering [[light curve]]s associated with the starlight observed from certain [[variable star]]s, such as that from  [[KIC 8462852]], [[RZ Piscium]] and [[WD 1145+017]].<ref name=\"SA-20200328\" /><ref name=\"ARX-20200318\" /> Excessive amounts of [[Infrared|infrared radiation]] may be detected from such stars,<ref name=\"ARX-201090310\">{{Cite journal|last1=Farihi |first1=J. |last2=Jura |first2=M. |last3=Zuckerman |first3=B. |title=Infrared Signatures of Disrupted Minor Planets at White Dwarfs |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=694 |issue=2 |pages=805\u2013819 |date=10 March 2009 |arxiv=0901.0973|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/694/2/805 |bibcode=2009ApJ...694..805F }}</ref> suggestive evidence in itself that dust and debris may be orbiting the stars.<ref name=\"AJ-20171221\" /><ref name=\"NASA-20171004\">{{cite web |last=Landau |first=Elizabeth |title=Mysterious Dimming of Tabby's Star May Be Caused by Dust |url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=6963 |date=4 October 2017 |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"ApJ-20171003\">{{cite journal |author=Meng, Huan Y.A.|display-authors=et al |title=Extinction and the Dimming of KIC 8462852 |date=3 October 2017 |journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]] |volume=847 |number=2 |page=131 |doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aa899c |bibcode=2017ApJ...847..131M |arxiv=1708.07556 }}</ref><ref name=\"PHY-20171005\">{{cite web |last=Tabor |first=Abby |title=The scientific quest to explain Kepler's most enigmatic find |url=https://phys.org/news/2017-10-scientific-quest-kepler-enigmatic.html |date=5 October 2017 |work=[[Phys.org]] |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n===Planets===\nExamples of planets (or their related remnants), considered to have been a disrupted planet, or part of such a planet, include:  [['Oumuamua]]<ref name=\"ARX-2017\">{{Cite journal|last=\u0106uk |first=Matija |arxiv=1712.01823 |title=1I/\u02bbOumuamua as a Tidal Disruption Fragment From a Binary Star System |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=852 |issue=1 |pages=L15 |date=2017 |doi=10.3847/2041-8213/aaa3db |bibcode=2018ApJ...852L..15C }}</ref> and [[WD 1145+017 b]], as well as [[asteroid]]s,<ref name=\"ARX-20060816\">{{cite journal |last=Soter |first=Steven |title=What is a Planet? |date=2006 |journal= The Astronomical Journal|volume=132 |issue=6 |pages=2513\u20132519 |arxiv=astro-ph/0608359 |doi=10.1086/508861|bibcode=2006AJ....132.2513S }}</ref> [[hot Jupiter]]s<ref name=\"MNRAS-20110920\">{{cite journal |last=Nayakshin |first=Sergei |title=Hot Super Earths: disrupted young jupiters? |url=https://academic.oup.com/mnras/article/416/4/2974/976497 |date=20 September 2011 |journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]] |volume=416 |issue=4 |pages=2974\u20132980 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2011.19246.x |accessdate=25 December 2017 |bibcode=2011MNRAS.416.2974N |arxiv=1103.1846 }}</ref> and those that are [[hypothetical planet]]s, like [[Fifth planet (hypothetical)|Fifth planet]], [[Phaeton (hypothetical planet)|Phaeton]], [[Planet V]] and [[Theia (planet)|Theia]].\n\n===Stars===\nExamples of parent stars, considered to have caused a planet to have been disrupted, include: [[EPIC 204278916]], [[KIC 8462852]] (Tabby's Star), [[PDS 110]], [[RZ Piscium]], [[WD 1145+017]] and [[47 Ursae Majoris]].\n[[File:PIA22081-KIC8462852-TabbysStar-UnevenDustRing-Illustration-20171004.png|thumb|center|500px|<center>Artist concept of an \"[[KIC 8462852#Circumstellar dust ring|uneven ring of dust]]\" surrounding [[KIC 8462852]].</center>]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==KIC 8462852 light curve==\n[[KIC 8462852]] is an [[F-type main-sequence star]] exhibiting unusual light fluctuations, including up to a 22% dimming in brightness.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boyajian|first=T. S.|last2=LaCourse|first2=D. M.|last3=Rappaport|first3=S. A.|last4=Fabrycky|first4=D.|last5=Fischer|first5=D. A.|last6=Gandolfi|first6=D.|last7=Kennedy|first7=G. M.|last8=Korhonen|first8=H.|last9=Liu|first9=M. C.|date=2016-01-27|title=Planet Hunters IX. KIC&nbsp;8462852 \u2013 where's the flux?|url=https://academic.oup.com/mnras/article-abstract/457/4/3988/2589003?redirectedFrom=fulltext|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|language=en|volume=457|issue=4|pages=3988\u20134004|doi=10.1093/mnras/stw218|issn=0035-8711|arxiv=1509.03622}}</ref> Several hypotheses have been proposed to explain these irregular changes, but none to date fully explain all aspects of the curve. One explanation is that an \"[[KIC 8462852#Circumstellar dust ring|uneven ring of dust]]\" orbits KIC 8462852.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=6963|title=Mysterious Dimming of Tabby's Star May Be Caused by Dust|website=NASA/JPL|access-date=2018-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boyajian|first=Tabetha S.|last2=Alonso|first2=Roi|last3=Ammerman|first3=Alex|last4=Armstrong|first4=David|last5=Ramos|first5=A. Asensio|last6=Barkaoui|first6=K.|last7=Beatty|first7=Thomas G.|last8=Benkhaldoun|first8=Z.|last9=Benni|first9=Paul|date=2018-01-19|title=The First Post-Kepler Brightness Dips of KIC 8462852|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=853|issue=1|pages=L8|doi=10.3847/2041-8213/aaa405|issn=2041-8213|arxiv=1801.00732}}</ref> However, in September 2019, astronomers reported that the observed dimmings of [[Tabby's Star]] may have been produced by fragments resulting from the disruption of an orphaned [[exomoon]].<ref name=\"PHYS-20190916\">{{cite news |author=Columbia University |title=New observations help explain the dimming of Tabby's Star |url=https://phys.org/news/2019-09-dimming-tabby-star.html |date=16 September 2019 |work=[[Phys.org]] |accessdate=16 September 2019 |author-link=Columbia University }}</ref><ref name=\"MNRAS-20190915\">{{cite journal |last1=Marinez |first1=Miquel |last2=Stone |first2=Nicholas C. |last3=Metzger |first3=Brian D. |title=Orphaned Exomoons: Tidal Detachment and Evaporation Following an Exoplanet-Star Collision |date=5 September 2019 |journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]] |doi=10.1093/mnras/stz2464 |arxiv=1906.08788 }}</ref>\n[[File:Consolidated plot of KIC 8462852 dip maxima March 2020 update.png|thumb|center|1200px|<div align=\"center\">Consolidated plot of all known dimmings (1 March 2020)</div>]]\n\n<center><gallery widths=\"150px\">\nFile:KIC 8462852 - gesamte Helligkeitsmessung von Kepler.png|All light curve data \u2212 December 2009 to May 2013, scan days 0066 to 1587 (''Kepler'')\nFile:KIC 8462852 - Helligkeitseinbruch 05. M\u00e4rz 2011.png|5 March 2011 \u2212 day 792 <br /> 15% max dip (''Kepler'')\nFile:KIC 8462852 - Helligkeitseinbruch 28. Februar 2013.png|28 February 2013 \u2212 day 1519 <br /> 22% max dip (''Kepler'')\nFile:KIC 8462852 - Helligkeitseinbruch 17. April 2013.png|17 April 2013 \u2212 day 1568 <br /> 8% max dip (''Kepler'')\nFile:KIC 8462852 Daily Normalized Flux by Bruce Gary, 20170502-20180504.png|One year light curve \u2212<br />[[#2017 light fluctuations|up to 4 May 2018]]<br />([[Hereford Arizona Observatory|HAO]]<ref name=\"BG-20171114-latest\">{{cite web |last=Gary |first=Bruce L. |authorlink=Bruce L. Gary |title=Hereford Arizona Observatory photometry observations of KIC 8462852 |url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts5/ |date=14 November 2017 |work=BruceGary.net |accessdate=24 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"BG-20171004\">{{cite web |last=Gary |first=Bruce L. |authorlink=Bruce L. Gary |title=Hereford Arizona Observatory photometry observations of KIC 8462852 between 2 May and 4 October 2017 |url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts4/ |date=4 October 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004220716/http://www.brucegary.net/ts4/ |archivedate=4 October 2017 |work=BruceGary.net |accessdate=23 December 2017 }}<br>{{small|''\"Note: g'-band and r'-band dip depths (and shapes) may differ, with g'-band being more sensitive to dust cloud scattering due to its shorter wavelength (0.47 vs. 0.62 micron). For a reasonable particle size distribution (e.g., Hanson, 0.2 micron) the extinction cross section ratio would produce a depth at r'-band that is 0.57 x depth at g'-band. If g'-band depth is 0.3 %, for example, depth at r'-band could be 0.17 %. The \"Tabby Team\" measurements ([[:File:KIC 8462852 TS r-prime-band Normalized Flux by TabbyTeam, 20170502-20171004.png|Fig. 3]]) at r'-band are compatible with that small dip depth. Incidentally, none of these shapes resemble exo-comet tail transits (as described by Rappaport et al, 2017 [https://arxiv.org/abs/1708.06069 link]); so the mystery of what's producing these week-timescale dips continues! Actually, long oval shapes are known to produce V-shaped dips (think of rings with a high inclination).\"'' - bg}}</ref><ref name=\"BG-20180101\">{{cite web |last=Gary |first=Bruce L. |authorlink=Bruce L. Gary |title=Hereford Arizona Observatory photometry observations of KIC 8462852 between 2 May and 31 December 2017 |url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts5/ |date=1 January 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102012647/http://www.brucegary.net/ts5/ |archivedate=1 January 2018 |work=BruceGary.net |accessdate=1 January 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"BG-20180504\">{{cite web |last=Gary |first=Bruce L. |authorlink=w:Bruce L. Gary |title=Hereford Arizona Observatory photometry observations of KIC 8462852 between 2 May 2017 and 4 May 2018 |url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts6/ |date=4 May 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505143701/http://www.brucegary.net/ts6/ |archivedate=5 May 2018 |work=BruceGary.net |accessdate=5 May 2018 }}</ref><!---<br>''(<small>[http://www.brucegary.net/HAO/ HAO]=[[Hereford Arizona Observatory|HAO]]</small>)''--->)\nFile:KIC 8462852 October-December 2019 Gary.jpg|Light curve between 10 October 2019 and 11 January 2020 (HAO)<ref name=\"Gary_11Jan20\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.brucegary.net/ts9/|date=11 January 2020|title=KIC 8462852 Hereford Arizona Observatory Photometry Observations #9|first=Bruce|last=Gary|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200405060559/http://www.brucegary.net/ts9/|archive-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n</gallery></center>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Asteroid belt]]\n* [[BD+20\u00b0307]]\n* [[Formation and evolution of the Solar System]]\n* [[Giant-impact hypothesis]]\n* [[Interstellar medium]]\n* [[List of stars that dim oddly]]\n* [[Nebular hypothesis]]\n* [[Planetesimal]]\n* [[Protoplanetary disk]]\n* [[Tidal force]]\n* [[WD 0145+234|WD 0145+234 (star disrupting an exoasteroid)]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|author=Wallace Gary Ernst|title=The Dynamic Planet|url=https://archive.org/details/dynamicplanet0000erns|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/dynamicplanet0000erns/page/18 18]|year=1990|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-07231-1}}\n*  {{cite book|author=Michael M. Woolfson|authorlink=Michael Woolfson|title=The Origin and Evolution of the Solar System|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KantSzMGPSkC&pg=PA316|year=2000|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-4200-3335-9}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://exoplanet.eu/catalog/WD_1145+017_b/ NASA \u2013 WD 1145+017 b] at [[Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia|The Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia]].\n* {{YouTube|gypAjPp6eps|title=Video (13:46) \u2212 \"Tabby's Star\"}}, a presentation by [[Tabetha S. Boyajian]].\n* {{YouTube|id=SVCpBr3fxdE|title=Video (31:00) \u2212 \"Tabby's Star\"}}, a presentation by Issac Arthur.\n* {{YouTube|nf2oc6nMsn4|title=Video (01:00) \u2212 RZ Piscium}}, star with unusual light fluctuations (21 December 2017).\n{{Exoplanet|state=collapsed}}\n{{portal bar|Astronomy|Solar System|Space|Star}}\n\n[[Category:Circumstellar disks|Circumstellar disks]]\n[[Category:Hypothetical astronomical objects]]\n[[Category:Objects with variable star designations|Objects with variable star designations]]\n[[Category:Planetary rings]]\n[[Category:Unsolved problems in astronomy]]\n", "name_user": "Headbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Various citation & identifier cleanup, plus AWB genfixes (arxiv version pointless when published)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disrupted_planet"}
{"title_page": "Anarkali", "text_new": "<ref><ref><ref><ref>[[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iQuB8TzZ-ys]]</ref></ref></ref></ref>{{other uses}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=June 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2010}}\n{{Weasel|date=March 2012}}\n{{fiction|date=August 2013}}\n{{confusing|date=March 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Prince Salim (the future Jahangir) and his legendary illicit love.jpg|thumb|[[Jahangir]] and Anarkali.]]\n[[File:Tomb of Anar Kali Lahore.jpg|thumb|The possible [[Tomb of Anarkali]], in the Pakistani city of [[Lahore]].]]\n'''Anarkali''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0627\u0646\u0627\u0631\u06a9\u0644\u06cc}}}}) (pomegranate blossom), born as '''Sharif un-Nissa''',<ref>{{cite book |last1=Glover |first1=William |title=Making Lahore Modern, Constructing and Imagining a Colonial City |date=January 2007 |publisher=Univ Of Minnesota Press |isbn=978-0816650224}}</ref> and also known as Nadira Begum, was a [[courtesan]] from [[Lahore]] (in modern-day [[Pakistan]]). According to one of the stories, Anarkali had an illicit relationship with the [[Mughal Empire|Crown Prince]] [[Jahangir]] and the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal Emperor]] [[Akbar]] had her enclosed in a wall where she died. There is no historic proof of Anarakali's existence although her character often appears in movies, books and fictionalized versions of history.\n\nAnarkali was first mentioned in the journal of an English tourist and trader, [[William Finch (merchant)|William Finch]], after he visited the [[Mughal Empire]] on 24 August, 1608.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://beta.dawn.com/news/694833/legend-anarkali-myth-mystery-and-history |title=Legend: Anarkali: myth, mystery and history |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> The story was also written by Indian writer [[Abdul Halim Sharar]] and on the first page of his book, he clearly mentions it to be a work of fiction. Nevertheless, Anarkali's story has been adapted into literature, art and cinema.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nShe is depicted in the Bollywood movie, [[Mughal-e-Azam]], which is set during the [[Mughal era|Mughal]] period. According to legend, Anarkali was ordered to be buried alive between two walls by [[Mughal Empire|Mughal Emperor]] [[Akbar]] for having an illicit relationship with the Crown-Prince Salim, later to become Mughal Emperor [[Jahangir]]. \n\nThere is disagreement among scholars concerning the authenticity of Anarkali's story. There are many supporting and opposing views such as the ones mentioned below.\n\nThe earliest Western stories about the love affair between Salim and Anarkali were written by two British travellers, William Finch and Edward Terry. William Finch reached Lahore in February 1611 (only 11 years after the supposed death of Anarkali), to sell [[Indigo dye|indigo]] he had purchased at [[Bayana]] on behalf of the [[East India Company]]. His account, written in early 17th-century English, gives the following information.\n\nAnarkali had an affair with Prince Salim (Jahangir). Upon notice of the affair, King Akbar ordered her to be enclosed within a wall of his palace, where she died. The King Jahangir, as a token of his love, ordered a magnificent tomb of stone to be built in the midst of a walled four-square garden surrounded by a gate. The body of the tomb, the emperor willed to be wrought in gold.\n\nEdward Terry, who visited a few years after William Finch, wrote that Akbar had threatened to disinherit Jahangir for his liaison with Anarkali, the emperor\u2019s most beloved wife. But on his death-bed, Akbar repealed it.\n\nBasing his analysis on the above two accounts, [[Abraham Eraly]], the author of ''The Last Spring: The Lives and Times of the Great Mughals'', suspects that there \"seems to have been an [[Oedipal complex|oedipal]] conflict between Akbar and Salim.\" He also considers it probable that the legendary Anarkali was none other than the mother of Prince Daniyal. {{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nEraly supports his hypothesis by quoting an incident recorded by Abul Fazl, Akbar's court-historian. According to the historian, Salim was beaten up one evening by guards of Akbar's royal harem. The story goes that a mad man wandered into Akbar\u2019s harem because of the carelessness of the guards. Abul Fazl writes that Salim caught the man but was himself mistaken for the intruder. The emperor arrived upon the scene and was about to strike with his sword when he recognised Salim. It is likely that the intruder was none other than Prince Salim and that the story of the mad man was concocted to put a veil on the prince's indecency.\n\nBut the accounts of the British travellers, and consequently the presumption of Eraly, is unlikely in light of the fact that Prince Daniyal's mother died in 1596, which does not match the dates inscribed on the sarcophagus.\n\nAnother scholar, Muhammed Baqir, the author of ''Lahore Past and Present'' opines that Anarkali was originally the name of the garden in which the tomb was situated. However, with the passage of time, the tomb itself came to be named as that of Anarkali\u2019s. This garden is mentioned by Dara Shikoh, the grandson of Jahangir, in his work, ''Sakinat al-Auliya'', as one of the places where the saint, Mian Mir, used to sit. Dara also mentions the existence of a tomb in the garden but he does not give it any name.\n\nMuhammed Baqir believes that the so-called tomb of Anarkali actually belonged to a lady named or entitled Sahib-i Jamal, another wife of Salim, the mother of the prince\u2019s second son, Sultan Parvez, and a daughter of the noble Zain Khan Koka. This conclusion is also partially faulty. The mother of Sultan Parviz was not a daughter of Zain Khan Koka but the daughter of Khawaja Hasan, the paternal uncle of Zain Khan. Of course, subsequently, the daughter of Zain Khan was also married to Salim on 18 June 1596.\n\nIt is recorded in Akbar Nama that Jahangir \"became violently enamoured of the daughter of Zain Khan Koka. H.M. (Akbar) was displeased at the impropriety, but he saw that his heart was immoderately affected, he, of necessity, gave his consent.\" The translator of Akbar Nama, H. Beveridge, opines that Akbar objected to the marriage, because the Prince was already married \"to Zain Khan\u2019s niece\" (actually the daughter of paternal uncle of Zain Khan, and hence his sister). Akbar objected to marrying near relations. But we do not know the date of death of either of the two wives of Jahangir.\n\nNoted art historian [[Ram Nath|R. Nath]] argues that Jahangir had no wife on record bearing the name or title Anarkali to whom the emperor could have built a tomb and dedicated a couplet with a suffix ''[[Majnun]]''. He writes: \"[it is] absolutely improbable that the grand Mughal emperor would address his married wife as ''yar'', designate himself as ''majnun'' and aspire to see her face once again. Had he not seen her enough? Obviously she was not his married wife but only his beloved, to whom he would take the liberty to be romantic and a little poetic too, and it appears to be a case of an unsuccessful romance of a disappointed lover... The prince could not save her, though it is on record that he was so unhappy with his father in this year 1599 that he defied his orders and revolted. It may be recalled that Mehrunissa (later Nurjahan Begum) was also married to Sher Afgan the same year and the young Prince was so dejected and disturbed on the failure of his two romances and annihilation of his tender feelings of love that he went as far as to defy Akbar.\" {{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nAlthough there are many views over the death of Anarkali, the most prominent are:\n\n1. Anarkali or \"Sharrafunnisa\", although cemented behind the wall by the order of Akbar, was released by the emperor on the request of Anarkali's mother, \"Jillo Bai\". Emperor Akbar had promised Anarkali's mother one wish in her life. Thereby, Anarkali escaped through a secret route to the outskirts of Delhi and then went to Lahore and lived there until her death.\n\nThere exists a tomb of Anarkali in Lahore. It was in Lahore that Prince Salim set eyes upon Anarkali (\"Pomegranate Blossom\"). She was Emperor Akbar's favorite dancing girl and, legend has it, that he was furious when he learned of her affair with the prince. As punishment, he had Anarkali entombed outside the fort. Whether this story is fact or fiction, a modest tomb does stand in Lahore which is believed to have been built by the lovesick prince in 1615. The gravestone in the tomb for Anarkali bears a tragic inscription:\n<poem>\nCould I behold the face of my beloved once more,\nI would thank God until the day of resurrection.</poem>\n\nThe tomb was converted into a church during British occupation and now serves as an archive (with a collection of old prints) within the compound of the Government Record Office.\nOn the lower Mall Road, inside the grounds of the Punjab Secretariat, lies the tomb of Anarkali. The tomb is accessible to the public. \n\n2. The second view is that Anarkali, after the death of Akbar, was recalled by Salim (Jahangir) after which they married. She was given a new identity, Nur Jahan.\n\nHer father came to the sub-continent during the time of the Mughal emperor, Akbar, and entered into his service. He rose rapidly through the ranks on merit. In 1607, Nur Jahan was brought to the court as a royal ward. She was beautiful and highly intelligent and attracted Jahangir's attention.\n\nA good deal of fiction has gathered around this remarkable woman, obscuring her personality and role in the social and political life of the period. It is wrongly and widely believed that Jahangir murdered Sher Afghan, Nur Jahan's first husband, because he wanted to marry Nur Jahan. In reality, Sher Afghan died in a skirmish with Jahangir's foster brother, Qutbuddin Koka, in 1607. The conqueror of the world, Jahangir, fell in love with Nur Jahan and married her in 1611. He gave her the title of Nur Mehal, \"Light of the Palace\", and later, Nur Jahan, \"Light of the World\".\n\nAfter marriage, Nur Jahan won Jahangir's complete confidence. She carefully attended to the affairs of the state. Her father and brother became ministers and together they dominated the courts. A number of historians believe that Nur Jahan became the real power behind the throne and practically the sovereign of the Mughal Empire. For many years she wielded the imperial powers. She even gave audiences at her palace and her name was placed on the coinage.\n\nThe decision to marry her daughter, Ladli Begum (from her first husband), to Shah Jahan's younger brother, Shahryar, caused Shah Jahan's rebellion. There are rumors that she had previously formed a junta supporting Shah Jahan's right to the throne along with her father Ghias Beg and her brother Abul Hasan (later Asaf Khan), who was also Shah Jahan's father-in-law. However, when Shah Jahan refused to marry Ladli Begum in spite of Nur Jahan's command, she married her daughter off to Shahryar, who was more compliant than his brother. Emperor Jahangir was captured by rebels in 1626 while he was on his way to Kashmir. Nur Jahan intervened to get her husband released. Jahangir was rescued but died on 28 October 1627.\n\nNur Jehan had a magnificent tomb erected over the grave of her husband. She retired from the world and lived a quiet and lonely life for 16 years after the death of Jahangir. She died in 1645 and is buried beside Jahangir at Shahdra, Lahore.\n\n== Film Portrayals ==\n\nAnarkali has been the subject of a number of Indian, Bangladeshi and Pakistani books, plays and films. The earliest and most celebrated historical play about her, ''Anarkali'', was written by [[Imtiaz Ali Taj]] in Urdu and performed in 1922. The play was made into a film, ''Loves of a Mughal Prince'', released in India in 1928 and starred Taj as Akbar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0256895/ |title=Loves of a Moghul Prince |publisher= |via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> [[Bina Rai]] portrayed Anarkali in [[Anarkali (1953 film)|''Anarkali'']], a 1953 Indian film. In Pakistan, another film, also entitled ''Anarkali'', was released in 1958 with [[Noor Jehan]] in the lead role.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0233210/ \"Anarkali (1958)\" imdb]; based on the Imtiaz Ali Taj play/script as adapted by [[Hakim Ahmad Shuja]] for his son [[Anwar Kamal Pasha]]'s production/direction</ref> Later, in 1960, [[K. Asif]]'s landmark film ''[[Mughal-e-Azam]]'' was released in India with actress [[Madhubala]] in the role of Anarkali and [[Dilip Kumar]] as Prince Salim. In 1955, Akkineni Nageswara Rao and Anjali Devi starred in Anarkali[ [[Anarkali (1955 film)]]]. In 1979, Telugu superstar [[N.T.Rama Rao]] directed and acted in the film [[Akbar Salim Anarkali]], featuring himself as Akbar, [[Nandamuri Balakrishna]] as Salim and [[Unni Mary|Deepa]] as Anarkali. [[Iman Ali]] portrayed Anarkali in [[Shoaib Mansoor]]'s short music video series on the theme ''[[Ishq]]'' (love) in 2003. In the 2013 [[Ekta Kapoor]]'s TV Series ''[[Jodha Akbar]]'', she was portrayed by [[Heena Parmar]] while [[Saniya Touqeer]] played young Anarkali.\n\nA daily soap was aired on Colors TV titled \"Dastan-e-Mohabbat...Salim Anarkali\", where Prince Salim is enacted by [[Shaheer Sheikh]] and his beloved Anarkali by [[Sonarika Bhadoria]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tomb of Anarkali]]\n* [[Anarkali Bazaar]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\nhttps://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/tomb_anarkali.html\n{{Commons category|Anarkali}}\n\n\n[[Category:Indian legends]]\n[[Category:Indian literature]]\n[[Category:Indian folklore]]\n[[Category:Women of the Mughal Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=June 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2010}}\n{{Weasel|date=March 2012}}\n{{fiction|date=August 2013}}\n{{confusing|date=March 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Prince Salim (the future Jahangir) and his legendary illicit love.jpg|thumb|[[Jahangir]] and Anarkali.]]\n[[File:Tomb of Anar Kali Lahore.jpg|thumb|The possible [[Tomb of Anarkali]], in the Pakistani city of [[Lahore]].]]\n'''Anarkali''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0627\u0646\u0627\u0631\u06a9\u0644\u06cc}}}}) (pomegranate blossom), born as '''Sharif un-Nissa''',<ref>{{cite book |last1=Glover |first1=William |title=Making Lahore Modern, Constructing and Imagining a Colonial City |date=January 2007 |publisher=Univ Of Minnesota Press |isbn=978-0816650224}}</ref> and also known as Nadira Begum, was a [[courtesan]] from [[Lahore]] (in modern-day [[Pakistan]]). According to one of the stories, Anarkali had an illicit relationship with the [[Mughal Empire|Crown Prince]] [[Jahangir]] and the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal Emperor]] [[Akbar]] had her enclosed in a wall where she died. There is no historic proof of Anarakali's existence although her character often appears in movies, books and fictionalized versions of history.\n\nAnarkali was first mentioned in the journal of an English tourist and trader, [[William Finch (merchant)|William Finch]], after he visited the [[Mughal Empire]] on 24 August, 1608.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://beta.dawn.com/news/694833/legend-anarkali-myth-mystery-and-history |title=Legend: Anarkali: myth, mystery and history |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> The story was also written by Indian writer [[Abdul Halim Sharar]] and on the first page of his book, he clearly mentions it to be a work of fiction. Nevertheless, Anarkali's story has been adapted into literature, art and cinema.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nShe is depicted in the Bollywood movie, [[Mughal-e-Azam]], which is set during the [[Mughal era|Mughal]] period. According to legend, Anarkali was ordered to be buried alive between two walls by [[Mughal Empire|Mughal Emperor]] [[Akbar]] for having an illicit relationship with the Crown-Prince Salim, later to become Mughal Emperor [[Jahangir]]. \n\nThere is disagreement among scholars concerning the authenticity of Anarkali's story. There are many supporting and opposing views such as the ones mentioned below.\n\nThe earliest Western stories about the love affair between Salim and Anarkali were written by two British travellers, William Finch and Edward Terry. William Finch reached Lahore in February 1611 (only 11 years after the supposed death of Anarkali), to sell [[Indigo dye|indigo]] he had purchased at [[Bayana]] on behalf of the [[East India Company]]. His account, written in early 17th-century English, gives the following information.\n\nAnarkali had an affair with Prince Salim (Jahangir). Upon notice of the affair, King Akbar ordered her to be enclosed within a wall of his palace, where she died. The King Jahangir, as a token of his love, ordered a magnificent tomb of stone to be built in the midst of a walled four-square garden surrounded by a gate. The body of the tomb, the emperor willed to be wrought in gold.\n\nEdward Terry, who visited a few years after William Finch, wrote that Akbar had threatened to disinherit Jahangir for his liaison with Anarkali, the emperor\u2019s most beloved wife. But on his death-bed, Akbar repealed it.\n\nBasing his analysis on the above two accounts, [[Abraham Eraly]], the author of ''The Last Spring: The Lives and Times of the Great Mughals'', suspects that there \"seems to have been an [[Oedipal complex|oedipal]] conflict between Akbar and Salim.\" He also considers it probable that the legendary Anarkali was none other than the mother of Prince Daniyal. {{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nEraly supports his hypothesis by quoting an incident recorded by Abul Fazl, Akbar's court-historian. According to the historian, Salim was beaten up one evening by guards of Akbar's royal harem. The story goes that a mad man wandered into Akbar\u2019s harem because of the carelessness of the guards. Abul Fazl writes that Salim caught the man but was himself mistaken for the intruder. The emperor arrived upon the scene and was about to strike with his sword when he recognised Salim. It is likely that the intruder was none other than Prince Salim and that the story of the mad man was concocted to put a veil on the prince's indecency.\n\nBut the accounts of the British travellers, and consequently the presumption of Eraly, is unlikely in light of the fact that Prince Daniyal's mother died in 1596, which does not match the dates inscribed on the sarcophagus.\n\nAnother scholar, Muhammed Baqir, the author of ''Lahore Past and Present'' opines that Anarkali was originally the name of the garden in which the tomb was situated. However, with the passage of time, the tomb itself came to be named as that of Anarkali\u2019s. This garden is mentioned by Dara Shikoh, the grandson of Jahangir, in his work, ''Sakinat al-Auliya'', as one of the places where the saint, Mian Mir, used to sit. Dara also mentions the existence of a tomb in the garden but he does not give it any name.\n\nMuhammed Baqir believes that the so-called tomb of Anarkali actually belonged to a lady named or entitled Sahib-i Jamal, another wife of Salim, the mother of the prince\u2019s second son, Sultan Parvez, and a daughter of the noble Zain Khan Koka. This conclusion is also partially faulty. The mother of Sultan Parviz was not a daughter of Zain Khan Koka but the daughter of Khawaja Hasan, the paternal uncle of Zain Khan. Of course, subsequently, the daughter of Zain Khan was also married to Salim on 18 June 1596.\n\nIt is recorded in Akbar Nama that Jahangir \"became violently enamoured of the daughter of Zain Khan Koka. H.M. (Akbar) was displeased at the impropriety, but he saw that his heart was immoderately affected, he, of necessity, gave his consent.\" The translator of Akbar Nama, H. Beveridge, opines that Akbar objected to the marriage, because the Prince was already married \"to Zain Khan\u2019s niece\" (actually the daughter of paternal uncle of Zain Khan, and hence his sister). Akbar objected to marrying near relations. But we do not know the date of death of either of the two wives of Jahangir.\n\nNoted art historian [[Ram Nath|R. Nath]] argues that Jahangir had no wife on record bearing the name or title Anarkali to whom the emperor could have built a tomb and dedicated a couplet with a suffix ''[[Majnun]]''. He writes: \"[it is] absolutely improbable that the grand Mughal emperor would address his married wife as ''yar'', designate himself as ''majnun'' and aspire to see her face once again. Had he not seen her enough? Obviously she was not his married wife but only his beloved, to whom he would take the liberty to be romantic and a little poetic too, and it appears to be a case of an unsuccessful romance of a disappointed lover... The prince could not save her, though it is on record that he was so unhappy with his father in this year 1599 that he defied his orders and revolted. It may be recalled that Mehrunissa (later Nurjahan Begum) was also married to Sher Afgan the same year and the young Prince was so dejected and disturbed on the failure of his two romances and annihilation of his tender feelings of love that he went as far as to defy Akbar.\" {{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nAlthough there are many views over the death of Anarkali, the most prominent are:\n\n1. Anarkali or \"Sharrafunnisa\", although cemented behind the wall by the order of Akbar, was released by the emperor on the request of Anarkali's mother, \"Jillo Bai\". Emperor Akbar had promised Anarkali's mother one wish in her life. Thereby, Anarkali escaped through a secret route to the outskirts of Delhi and then went to Lahore and lived there until her death.\n\nThere exists a tomb of Anarkali in Lahore. It was in Lahore that Prince Salim set eyes upon Anarkali (\"Pomegranate Blossom\"). She was Emperor Akbar's favorite dancing girl and, legend has it, that he was furious when he learned of her affair with the prince. As punishment, he had Anarkali entombed outside the fort. Whether this story is fact or fiction, a modest tomb does stand in Lahore which is believed to have been built by the lovesick prince in 1615. The gravestone in the tomb for Anarkali bears a tragic inscription:\n<poem>\nCould I behold the face of my beloved once more,\nI would thank God until the day of resurrection.</poem>\n\nThe tomb was converted into a church during British occupation and now serves as an archive (with a collection of old prints) within the compound of the Government Record Office.\nOn the lower Mall Road, inside the grounds of the Punjab Secretariat, lies the tomb of Anarkali. The tomb is accessible to the public. \n\n2. The second view is that Anarkali, after the death of Akbar, was recalled by Salim (Jahangir) after which they married. She was given a new identity, Nur Jahan.\n\nHer father came to the sub-continent during the time of the Mughal emperor, Akbar, and entered into his service. He rose rapidly through the ranks on merit. In 1607, Nur Jahan was brought to the court as a royal ward. She was beautiful and highly intelligent and attracted Jahangir's attention.\n\nA good deal of fiction has gathered around this remarkable woman, obscuring her personality and role in the social and political life of the period. It is wrongly and widely believed that Jahangir murdered Sher Afghan, Nur Jahan's first husband, because he wanted to marry Nur Jahan. In reality, Sher Afghan died in a skirmish with Jahangir's foster brother, Qutbuddin Koka, in 1607. The conqueror of the world, Jahangir, fell in love with Nur Jahan and married her in 1611. He gave her the title of Nur Mehal, \"Light of the Palace\", and later, Nur Jahan, \"Light of the World\".\n\nAfter marriage, Nur Jahan won Jahangir's complete confidence. She carefully attended to the affairs of the state. Her father and brother became ministers and together they dominated the courts. A number of historians believe that Nur Jahan became the real power behind the throne and practically the sovereign of the Mughal Empire. For many years she wielded the imperial powers. She even gave audiences at her palace and her name was placed on the coinage.\n\nThe decision to marry her daughter, Ladli Begum (from her first husband), to Shah Jahan's younger brother, Shahryar, caused Shah Jahan's rebellion. There are rumors that she had previously formed a junta supporting Shah Jahan's right to the throne along with her father Ghias Beg and her brother Abul Hasan (later Asaf Khan), who was also Shah Jahan's father-in-law. However, when Shah Jahan refused to marry Ladli Begum in spite of Nur Jahan's command, she married her daughter off to Shahryar, who was more compliant than his brother. Emperor Jahangir was captured by rebels in 1626 while he was on his way to Kashmir. Nur Jahan intervened to get her husband released. Jahangir was rescued but died on 28 October 1627.\n\nNur Jehan had a magnificent tomb erected over the grave of her husband. She retired from the world and lived a quiet and lonely life for 16 years after the death of Jahangir. She died in 1645 and is buried beside Jahangir at Shahdra, Lahore.\n\n== Film Portrayals ==\n\nAnarkali has been the subject of a number of Indian, Bangladeshi and Pakistani books, plays and films. The earliest and most celebrated historical play about her, ''Anarkali'', was written by [[Imtiaz Ali Taj]] in Urdu and performed in 1922. The play was made into a film, ''Loves of a Mughal Prince'', released in India in 1928 and starred Taj as Akbar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0256895/ |title=Loves of a Moghul Prince |publisher= |via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> [[Bina Rai]] portrayed Anarkali in [[Anarkali (1953 film)|''Anarkali'']], a 1953 Indian film. In Pakistan, another film, also entitled ''Anarkali'', was released in 1958 with [[Noor Jehan]] in the lead role.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0233210/ \"Anarkali (1958)\" imdb]; based on the Imtiaz Ali Taj play/script as adapted by [[Hakim Ahmad Shuja]] for his son [[Anwar Kamal Pasha]]'s production/direction</ref> Later, in 1960, [[K. Asif]]'s landmark film ''[[Mughal-e-Azam]]'' was released in India with actress [[Madhubala]] in the role of Anarkali and [[Dilip Kumar]] as Prince Salim. In 1955, Akkineni Nageswara Rao and Anjali Devi starred in Anarkali[ [[Anarkali (1955 film)]]]. In 1979, Telugu superstar [[N.T.Rama Rao]] directed and acted in the film [[Akbar Salim Anarkali]], featuring himself as Akbar, [[Nandamuri Balakrishna]] as Salim and [[Unni Mary|Deepa]] as Anarkali. [[Iman Ali]] portrayed Anarkali in [[Shoaib Mansoor]]'s short music video series on the theme ''[[Ishq]]'' (love) in 2003. In the 2013 [[Ekta Kapoor]]'s TV Series ''[[Jodha Akbar]]'', she was portrayed by [[Heena Parmar]] while [[Saniya Touqeer]] played young Anarkali.\n\nA daily soap was aired on Colors TV titled \"Dastan-e-Mohabbat...Salim Anarkali\", where Prince Salim is enacted by [[Shaheer Sheikh]] and his beloved Anarkali by [[Sonarika Bhadoria]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tomb of Anarkali]]\n* [[Anarkali Bazaar]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\nhttps://sites.ualberta.ca/~rnoor/tomb_anarkali.html\n{{Commons category|Anarkali}}\n\n\n[[Category:Indian legends]]\n[[Category:Indian literature]]\n[[Category:Indian folklore]]\n[[Category:Women of the Mughal Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Zunair Khan", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anarkali"}
{"title_page": "Data stream mining", "text_new": "'''Data Stream Mining''' is the process of extracting knowledge structures from continuous, rapid data records. A [[data stream]] is an ordered sequence of instances that in many applications of data stream mining can be read only once or a small number of times using limited computing and storage capabilities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Medhat|first=Mohamed|last2=Zaslavsky|last3=Krishnaswamy|date=2005-06-01|title=Mining data streams|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/1083784.1083789|journal=ACM SIGMOD Record|language=EN|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1145/1083784.1083789|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn many data stream mining applications, the goal is to predict the class or value of new instances in the data stream given some knowledge about the class membership or values of previous instances in the data stream.\nMachine learning techniques can be used to learn this prediction task from labeled examples in an automated fashion.\nOften, concepts from the field of [[incremental learning]] are applied to cope with structural changes, [[online Machine Learning|on-line learning]] and real-time demands. \nIn many applications, especially operating within non-stationary environments, the distribution underlying the instances or the rules underlying their labeling may change over time, i.e. the goal of the prediction, the class to be predicted or the target value to be predicted, may change over time.<ref>{{Citation|last=Lemaire|first=Vincent|title=A Survey on Supervised Classification on Data Streams|date=2015|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-17551-5_4|work=Business Intelligence: 4th European Summer School, eBISS 2014, Berlin, Germany, July 6\u201311, 2014, Tutorial Lectures|pages=88\u2013125|editor-last=Zim\u00e1nyi|editor-first=Esteban|series=Lecture Notes in Business Information Processing|publisher=Springer International Publishing|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-17551-5_4|isbn=978-3-319-17551-5|access-date=2020-04-04|last2=Salperwyck|first2=Christophe|last3=Bondu|first3=Alexis|editor2-last=Kutsche|editor2-first=Ralf-Detlef}}</ref> This problem is referred to as [[concept drift]]. Detecting [[concept drift]] is a central issue to data stream mining.<ref>{{cite arxiv|last=Webb|first=Geoffrey I.|last2=Lee|first2=Loong Kuan|last3=Petitjean|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|last4=Goethals|first4=Bart|date=2017-04-02|title=Understanding Concept Drift|arxiv=1704.00362}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gama|first=Jo\u00e3o|last2=\u017dliobait\u0117|last3=Bifet|last4=Pechenizkiy|last5=Bouchachia|date=2014-03-01|title=A survey on concept drift adaptation|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/2523813|journal=ACM Computing Surveys (CSUR)|language=EN|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1145/2523813|via=}}</ref> Other challenges<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gomes|first=Heitor Murilo|last2=Read|last3=Bifet|last4=Barddal|last5=Gama|date=2019-11-26|title=Machine learning for streaming data|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3373464.3373470|journal=ACM SIGKDD Explorations Newsletter|language=EN|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1145/3373464.3373470|via=}}</ref> that arise when applying machine learning to streaming data include: partially and delayed labeled data,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grzenda|first=Maciej|last2=Gomes|first2=Heitor Murilo|last3=Bifet|first3=Albert|date=2019-11-16|title=Delayed labelling evaluation for data streams|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s10618-019-00654-y|journal=Data Mining and Knowledge Discovery|language=en|doi=10.1007/s10618-019-00654-y|issn=1573-756X}}</ref> recovery from concept drifts,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gomes|first=Heitor M.|last2=Bifet|first2=Albert|last3=Read|first3=Jesse|last4=Barddal|first4=Jean Paul|last5=Enembreck|first5=Fabr\u00edcio|last6=Pfharinger|first6=Bernhard|last7=Holmes|first7=Geoff|last8=Abdessalem|first8=Talel|date=2017-10-01|title=Adaptive random forests for evolving data stream classification|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s10994-017-5642-8|journal=Machine Learning|language=en|volume=106|issue=9|pages=1469\u20131495|doi=10.1007/s10994-017-5642-8|issn=1573-0565}}</ref> temporal dependencies.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u017dliobait\u0117|first=Indr\u0117|last2=Bifet|first2=Albert|last3=Read|first3=Jesse|last4=Pfahringer|first4=Bernhard|last5=Holmes|first5=Geoff|date=2015-03-01|title=Evaluation methods and decision theory for classification of streaming data with temporal dependence|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s10994-014-5441-4|journal=Machine Learning|language=en|volume=98|issue=3|pages=455\u2013482|doi=10.1007/s10994-014-5441-4|issn=1573-0565}}</ref>\n\nExamples of data streams include computer network traffic, phone conversations, ATM transactions, web searches, and sensor data.\nData stream mining can be considered a subfield of [[data mining]], [[machine learning]], and [[knowledge discovery]].\n\n==Software for data stream mining==\n* [[MOA (Massive Online Analysis)]]: free open-source software specific for mining data streams with concept drift. It has several machine learning algorithms ([[Statistical classification|classification]], [[Regression analysis|regression]], [[data clustering|clustering]], outlier detection and recommender systems).  Also, it contains a prequential evaluation method, the EDDM concept drift methods, a reader of ARFF real datasets, and artificial stream generators as SEA concepts, STAGGER, [[rotating hyperplane]], random tree, and [[random radius based functions]]. MOA supports bi-directional interaction with [[Weka (machine learning)]].\n* [[RapidMiner]]: commercial software for knowledge discovery, data mining, and machine learning also featuring data stream mining, learning time-varying concepts, and tracking drifting concept (if used in combination with its data stream mining plugin (formerly: Concept Drift plugin))\n*[https://scikit-multiflow.github.io scikit-multiflow]: A machine learning framework for multi-output/multi-label and stream data implemented in Python.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Montiel|first=Jacob|last2=Read|first2=Jesse|last3=Bifet|first3=Albert|last4=Abdessalem|first4=Talel|date=2018|title=Scikit-Multiflow: A Multi-output Streaming Framework|url=http://jmlr.org/papers/v19/18-251.html|journal=Journal of Machine Learning Research|volume=19|issue=72|pages=1\u20135|issn=1533-7928}}</ref> scikit-multiflow contains stream generators, stream learning methods for single-target and multi-target, concept drift detectors, evaluation and visualization methods.\n\n==Events==\n* [http://www.liaad.up.pt/udm/ International Workshop on Ubiquitous Data Mining] held in conjunction with the [http://ijcai13.org/ International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence (IJCAI) ] in Beijing, China, August 3\u20135, 2013.\n* [http://www.liaad.up.pt/~iwkduds/ International Workshop on Knowledge Discovery from Ubiquitous Data Streams] held in conjunction with the [http://ameblo.jp/kkonkatsu/ 18th European Conference on Machine Learning (ECML) and the 11th European Conference on Principles and Practice of Knowledge Discovery in Databases (PKDD)] in Warsaw, Poland, in September 2007.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070312173756/http://www.niaad.liacc.up.pt/~jgama/SAC07/ ACM Symposium on Applied Computing Data Streams Track] held in conjunction with the [http://www.acm.org/conferences/sac/sac2007/ 2007 ACM Symposium on Applied Computing (SAC-2007)] in [[Seoul]], [[Korea]], in March 2007.\n* [http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~mgaber/iwmesd/ IEEE International Workshop on Mining Evolving and Streaming Data (IWMESD 2006)] to be held in conjunction with the [http://www.comp.hkbu.edu.hk/~wii06/icdm/ 2006 IEEE International Conference on Data Mining (ICDM-2006)] in [[Hong Kong]] in December 2006.\n* [http://www.machine-learning.eu/iwkdds-2006/ Fourth International Workshop on Knowledge Discovery from Data Streams (IWKDDS)] to be held in conjunction with the [http://www.ecmlpkdd2006.org/ 17th European Conference on Machine Learning (ECML) and the 10th European Conference on Principles and Practice of Knowledge Discovery in Databases (PKDD) (ECML/PKDD-2006)] in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]], in September 2006.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Concept drift]]\n* [[Data Mining]]\n* [[Sequence mining]]\n* [[Streaming Algorithm]]\n* [[Stream processing]]\n* [[Wireless sensor network]]\n* [[Lambda architecture]]\n\n==Books==\n* {{cite book |first1= Albert |last1= Bifet |first2= Ricard |last2= Gavald\u00e0 |first3= Geoff |last3= Holmes |first4= Bernhard |last4= Pfahringer |title= Machine Learning for Data Streams with Practical Examples in MOA |publisher= MIT Press |date= 2018 |url= https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/machine-learning-data-streams |isbn= 9780262037792 |pages= 288 |series=  Adaptive Computation and Machine Learning }}\n* {{cite book |editor-first1= Jo\u00e3o |editor-last1= Gama |editor-first2= Mohamed Medhat |editor-last2= Gaber |title= Learning from Data Streams: Processing Techniques in Sensor Networks |url= https://www.springer.com/us/book/9783540736783 |isbn= 9783540736783 |doi= 10.1007/3-540-73679-4 |publisher= Springer |date= 2007 |pages= 244 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-first1= Auroop R. |editor-last1= Ganguly |editor-first2= Jo\u00e3o |editor-last2= Gama |editor-first3= Olufemi A. |editor-last3= Omitaomu |editor-first4= Mohamed M. |editor-last4= Gaber |editor-first5= Ranga R. |editor-last5= Vatsavai |title= Knowledge Discovery from Sensor Data |publisher= CRC Press |date= 2008 |url= https://www.crcpress.com/Knowledge-Discovery-from-Sensor-Data/Ganguly-Gama-Omitaomu-Gaber-Vatsavai/p/book/9781420082326 |isbn= 9781420082326 |pages= 215 |series= Industrial Innovation }}\n* {{cite book |first= Jo\u00e3o |last= Gama |title= Knowledge Discovery from Data Streams |publisher= Chapman and Hall |date= 2010 |url= https://www.crcpress.com/Knowledge-Discovery-from-Data-Streams/Gama/p/book/9781439826119 |isbn= 9781439826119 |pages= 255 |series= Data Mining and Knowledge Discovery }}\n* {{cite book |first= Edwin |last= Lughofer |title= Evolving Fuzzy Systems - Methodologies, Advanced Concepts and Applications |publisher= Springer |location= Heidelberg |date= 2011 |url= https://www.springer.com/us/book/9783642180866 |isbn= 9783642180866 |doi= 10.1007/978-3-642-18087-3 |pages= 456 |volume= 266 |series= Studies in Fuzziness and Soft Computing  }} \n* {{cite book |editor-first1= Moamar |editor-last1= Sayed-Mouchaweh |editor-first2= Edwin |editor-last2= Lughofer |title= Learning in Non-Stationary Environments: Methods and Applications |publisher= Springer |location= New York |date= 2012 |url= https://www.springer.com/us/book/9781441980199 |isbn= 9781441980199 |doi= 10.1007/978-1-4419-8020-5 |pages= 440 |citeseerx= 10.1.1.709.437 }}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Data Stream Mining}}\n[[Category:Data mining]]\n[[Category:Business intelligence]]\n", "text_old": "'''Data Stream Mining''' is the process of extracting knowledge structures from continuous, rapid data records. A [[data stream]] is an ordered sequence of instances that in many applications of data stream mining can be read only once or a small number of times using limited computing and storage capabilities<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Medhat|first=Mohamed|last2=Zaslavsky|last3=Krishnaswamy|date=2005-06-01|title=Mining data streams|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/1083784.1083789|journal=ACM SIGMOD Record|language=EN|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1145/1083784.1083789|via=}}</ref>.\n\nIn many data stream mining applications, the goal is to predict the class or value of new instances in the data stream given some knowledge about the class membership or values of previous instances in the data stream.\nMachine learning techniques can be used to learn this prediction task from labeled examples in an automated fashion.\nOften, concepts from the field of [[incremental learning]] are applied to cope with structural changes, [[online Machine Learning|on-line learning]] and real-time demands. \nIn many applications, especially operating within non-stationary environments, the distribution underlying the instances or the rules underlying their labeling may change over time, i.e. the goal of the prediction, the class to be predicted or the target value to be predicted, may change over time<ref>{{Citation|last=Lemaire|first=Vincent|title=A Survey on Supervised Classification on Data Streams|date=2015|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-17551-5_4|work=Business Intelligence: 4th European Summer School, eBISS 2014, Berlin, Germany, July 6-11, 2014, Tutorial Lectures|pages=88\u2013125|editor-last=Zim\u00e1nyi|editor-first=Esteban|series=Lecture Notes in Business Information Processing|publisher=Springer International Publishing|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-17551-5_4|isbn=978-3-319-17551-5|access-date=2020-04-04|last2=Salperwyck|first2=Christophe|last3=Bondu|first3=Alexis|editor2-last=Kutsche|editor2-first=Ralf-Detlef}}</ref>. This problem is referred to as [[concept drift]]. Detecting [[concept drift]] is a central issue to data stream mining <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Webb|first=Geoffrey I.|last2=Lee|first2=Loong Kuan|last3=Petitjean|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|last4=Goethals|first4=Bart|date=2017-04-02|title=Understanding Concept Drift|url=http://arxiv.org/abs/1704.00362|journal=arXiv:1704.00362 [cs]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gama|first=Jo\u00e3o|last2=\u017dliobait\u0117|last3=Bifet|last4=Pechenizkiy|last5=Bouchachia|date=2014-03-01|title=A survey on concept drift adaptation|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/2523813|journal=ACM Computing Surveys (CSUR)|language=EN|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1145/2523813|via=}}</ref>. Other challenges<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gomes|first=Heitor Murilo|last2=Read|last3=Bifet|last4=Barddal|last5=Gama|date=2019-11-26|title=Machine learning for streaming data|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3373464.3373470|journal=ACM SIGKDD Explorations Newsletter|language=EN|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1145/3373464.3373470|via=}}</ref> that arise when applying machine learning to streaming data include: partially and delayed labeled data<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grzenda|first=Maciej|last2=Gomes|first2=Heitor Murilo|last3=Bifet|first3=Albert|date=2019-11-16|title=Delayed labelling evaluation for data streams|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s10618-019-00654-y|journal=Data Mining and Knowledge Discovery|language=en|doi=10.1007/s10618-019-00654-y|issn=1573-756X}}</ref>, recovery from concept drifts<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gomes|first=Heitor M.|last2=Bifet|first2=Albert|last3=Read|first3=Jesse|last4=Barddal|first4=Jean Paul|last5=Enembreck|first5=Fabr\u00edcio|last6=Pfharinger|first6=Bernhard|last7=Holmes|first7=Geoff|last8=Abdessalem|first8=Talel|date=2017-10-01|title=Adaptive random forests for evolving data stream classification|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s10994-017-5642-8|journal=Machine Learning|language=en|volume=106|issue=9|pages=1469\u20131495|doi=10.1007/s10994-017-5642-8|issn=1573-0565}}</ref>, temporal dependencies<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u017dliobait\u0117|first=Indr\u0117|last2=Bifet|first2=Albert|last3=Read|first3=Jesse|last4=Pfahringer|first4=Bernhard|last5=Holmes|first5=Geoff|date=2015-03-01|title=Evaluation methods and decision theory for classification of streaming data with temporal dependence|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s10994-014-5441-4|journal=Machine Learning|language=en|volume=98|issue=3|pages=455\u2013482|doi=10.1007/s10994-014-5441-4|issn=1573-0565}}</ref>. \n\nExamples of data streams include computer network traffic, phone conversations, ATM transactions, web searches, and sensor data.\nData stream mining can be considered a subfield of [[data mining]], [[machine learning]], and [[knowledge discovery]].\n\n==Software for data stream mining==\n* [[MOA (Massive Online Analysis)]]: free open-source software specific for mining data streams with concept drift. It has several machine learning algorithms ([[Statistical classification|classification]], [[Regression analysis|regression]], [[data clustering|clustering]], outlier detection and recommender systems).  Also, it contains a prequential evaluation method, the EDDM concept drift methods, a reader of ARFF real datasets, and artificial stream generators as SEA concepts, STAGGER, [[rotating hyperplane]], random tree, and [[random radius based functions]]. MOA supports bi-directional interaction with [[Weka (machine learning)]].\n* [[RapidMiner]]: commercial software for knowledge discovery, data mining, and machine learning also featuring data stream mining, learning time-varying concepts, and tracking drifting concept (if used in combination with its data stream mining plugin (formerly: Concept Drift plugin))\n*[https://scikit-multiflow.github.io scikit-multiflow]: A machine learning framework for multi-output/multi-label and stream data implemented in Python<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Montiel|first=Jacob|last2=Read|first2=Jesse|last3=Bifet|first3=Albert|last4=Abdessalem|first4=Talel|date=2018|title=Scikit-Multiflow: A Multi-output Streaming Framework|url=http://jmlr.org/papers/v19/18-251.html|journal=Journal of Machine Learning Research|volume=19|issue=72|pages=1\u20135|issn=1533-7928}}</ref>. scikit-multiflow contains stream generators, stream learning methods for single-target and multi-target, concept drift detectors, evaluation and visualization methods.\n\n==Events==\n* [http://www.liaad.up.pt/udm/ International Workshop on Ubiquitous Data Mining] held in conjunction with the [http://ijcai13.org/ International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence (IJCAI) ] in Beijing, China, August 3\u20135, 2013.\n* [http://www.liaad.up.pt/~iwkduds/ International Workshop on Knowledge Discovery from Ubiquitous Data Streams] held in conjunction with the [http://ameblo.jp/kkonkatsu/ 18th European Conference on Machine Learning (ECML) and the 11th European Conference on Principles and Practice of Knowledge Discovery in Databases (PKDD)] in Warsaw, Poland, in September 2007.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070312173756/http://www.niaad.liacc.up.pt/~jgama/SAC07/ ACM Symposium on Applied Computing Data Streams Track] held in conjunction with the [http://www.acm.org/conferences/sac/sac2007/ 2007 ACM Symposium on Applied Computing (SAC-2007)] in [[Seoul]], [[Korea]], in March 2007.\n* [http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~mgaber/iwmesd/ IEEE International Workshop on Mining Evolving and Streaming Data (IWMESD 2006)] to be held in conjunction with the [http://www.comp.hkbu.edu.hk/~wii06/icdm/ 2006 IEEE International Conference on Data Mining (ICDM-2006)] in [[Hong Kong]] in December 2006.\n* [http://www.machine-learning.eu/iwkdds-2006/ Fourth International Workshop on Knowledge Discovery from Data Streams (IWKDDS)] to be held in conjunction with the [http://www.ecmlpkdd2006.org/ 17th European Conference on Machine Learning (ECML) and the 10th European Conference on Principles and Practice of Knowledge Discovery in Databases (PKDD) (ECML/PKDD-2006)] in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]], in September 2006.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Concept drift]]\n* [[Data Mining]]\n* [[Sequence mining]]\n* [[Streaming Algorithm]]\n* [[Stream processing]]\n* [[Wireless sensor network]]\n* [[Lambda architecture]]\n\n==Books==\n* {{cite book |first1= Albert |last1= Bifet |first2= Ricard |last2= Gavald\u00e0 |first3= Geoff |last3= Holmes |first4= Bernhard |last4= Pfahringer |title= Machine Learning for Data Streams with Practical Examples in MOA |publisher= MIT Press |date= 2018 |url= https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/machine-learning-data-streams |isbn= 9780262037792 |pages= 288 |series=  Adaptive Computation and Machine Learning }}\n* {{cite book |editor-first1= Jo\u00e3o |editor-last1= Gama |editor-first2= Mohamed Medhat |editor-last2= Gaber |title= Learning from Data Streams: Processing Techniques in Sensor Networks |url= https://www.springer.com/us/book/9783540736783 |isbn= 9783540736783 |doi= 10.1007/3-540-73679-4 |publisher= Springer |date= 2007 |pages= 244 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-first1= Auroop R. |editor-last1= Ganguly |editor-first2= Jo\u00e3o |editor-last2= Gama |editor-first3= Olufemi A. |editor-last3= Omitaomu |editor-first4= Mohamed M. |editor-last4= Gaber |editor-first5= Ranga R. |editor-last5= Vatsavai |title= Knowledge Discovery from Sensor Data |publisher= CRC Press |date= 2008 |url= https://www.crcpress.com/Knowledge-Discovery-from-Sensor-Data/Ganguly-Gama-Omitaomu-Gaber-Vatsavai/p/book/9781420082326 |isbn= 9781420082326 |pages= 215 |series= Industrial Innovation }}\n* {{cite book |first= Jo\u00e3o |last= Gama |title= Knowledge Discovery from Data Streams |publisher= Chapman and Hall |date= 2010 |url= https://www.crcpress.com/Knowledge-Discovery-from-Data-Streams/Gama/p/book/9781439826119 |isbn= 9781439826119 |pages= 255 |series= Data Mining and Knowledge Discovery }}\n* {{cite book |first= Edwin |last= Lughofer |title= Evolving Fuzzy Systems - Methodologies, Advanced Concepts and Applications |publisher= Springer |location= Heidelberg |date= 2011 |url= https://www.springer.com/us/book/9783642180866 |isbn= 9783642180866 |doi= 10.1007/978-3-642-18087-3 |pages= 456 |volume= 266 |series= Studies in Fuzziness and Soft Computing  }} \n* {{cite book |editor-first1= Moamar |editor-last1= Sayed-Mouchaweh |editor-first2= Edwin |editor-last2= Lughofer |title= Learning in Non-Stationary Environments: Methods and Applications |publisher= Springer |location= New York |date= 2012 |url= https://www.springer.com/us/book/9781441980199 |isbn= 9781441980199 |doi= 10.1007/978-1-4419-8020-5 |pages= 440 |citeseerx= 10.1.1.709.437 }}\n\n==References==\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Data Stream Mining}}\n[[Category:Data mining]]\n[[Category:Business intelligence]]\n<references />\n", "name_user": "Headbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "Various citation & identifier cleanup, plus AWB genfixes (arxiv version pointless when published)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_stream_mining"}
{"title_page": "Atomic electron transition", "text_new": "{{About||the TV series|Quantum Leap|the sculpture|The Quantum Leap}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n'''Atomic electron transition''' is a change of an [[electron]] from one [[energy level]] to another within an [[atom]]<ref>Schombert, James. [http://abyss.uoregon.edu/~js/cosmo/lectures/lec08.html \"Quantum physics\"] University of Oregon Department of Physics</ref> or [[artificial atom]].<ref>{{Cite journal |arxiv = 1009.2969|bibcode = 2011PhRvL.106k0502V|title = Observation of Quantum Jumps in a Superconducting Artificial Atom|journal = Physical Review Letters|volume = 106|issue = 11|pages = 110502|last1 = Vijay|first1 = R|last2 = Slichter|first2 = D. H|last3 = Siddiqi|first3 = I|year = 2011|doi = 10.1103/PhysRevLett.106.110502|pmid = 21469850}}</ref> It appears discontinuous as the electron \"jumps\" from one [[energy level]] to another, typically in a few [[nanosecond]]s or less. It is also known as an '''electronic (de-)excitation''' or '''atomic transition''' or '''quantum jump'''.\n\nElectron transitions cause the emission or absorption of [[electromagnetic radiation]] in the form of quantized units called [[photon]]s. Their statistics are [[Poisson distribution|Poissonian]], and the time between jumps is [[Exponential distribution|exponentially distributed]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mpq.mpg.de/Theorygroup/CIRAC/wiki/images/8/86/Samuel.pdf |last=Del\u00e9glise |first=S. |title=Observing the quantum jumps of light |access-date=September 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107043403/http://www.mpq.mpg.de/Theorygroup/CIRAC/wiki/images/8/86/Samuel.pdf |archive-date=November 7, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The damping time constant (which ranges from [[nanosecond]]s to a few seconds) relates to the natural, pressure, and field [[Spectral line#Line broadening and shift|broadening of spectral lines]]. The larger the energy separation of the states between which the electron jumps, the shorter the [[wavelength]] of the photon emitted.\n\nThe observability of quantum jumps was predicted by [[Hans Dehmelt]] in 1975, and they were first observed using [[Quadrupole ion trap|trapped ions]] of [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] at [[NIST]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Itano|first1=W. M.|last2=Bergquist|first2=J. C.|last3=Wineland|first3=D. J.|title=Early observations of macroscopic quantum jumps in single atoms|journal=International Journal of Mass Spectrometry|date=2015|volume=377|page=403|doi=10.1016/j.ijms.2014.07.005|url=http://tf.boulder.nist.gov/general/pdf/2723.pdf|bibcode = 2015IJMSp.377..403I }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 it was demonstrated in an experiment with a superconducting [[artificial atom]] consisting of two strongly-hybridized [[Transmon|transmon qubits]] placed inside a readout resonator cavity at 15 mK, that the evolution of some jumps is continuous, coherent, [[determinism|deterministic]], and reversible.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Minev |first1=Z. K. |last2=Mundhada |first2=S. O. |last3=Shankar |first3=S. |last4=Reinhold |first4=P. |last5=Guti\u00e9rrez-J\u00e1uregui |first5=R. |last6=Schoelkopf |first6=R. J.. |last7=Mirrahimi |first7=M. |last8=Carmichael |first8=H. J. |last9=Devoret |first9=M. H. |title=To catch and reverse a quantum jump mid-flight |journal=Nature |date=3 June 2019 |volume=570 |issue=7760 |pages=200\u2013204 |doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1287-z |pmid=31160725 |arxiv=1803.00545 }}</ref> On the other hand other quantum jumps are inherently unpredictable ie. nondeterministic.<ref>{{cite arxiv|last=Snizhko|first=Kyrylo|last2=Kumar|first2=Parveen|last3=Romito|first3=Alessandro|date=2020-03-23|title=The Quantum Zeno effect appears in stages|arxiv=2003.10476}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Burst noise]]\n* [[Ensemble interpretation]]\n* [[Fluorescence]]\n* [[Glowing pickle demonstration]]\n* [[Molecular electronic transition]] for molecules\n* [[Phosphorescence]]\n* [[Spontaneous emission]]\n* [[Stimulated emission]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary|quantum leap}}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://www.psiquadrat.de/downloads/schroedinger52_jumps1.pdf |title=Are there quantum jumps? Part I |journal=The British Journal for the Philosophy of Science |volume=3 |issue=10 |date=August 1952 |pages=109&ndash;123 |first=Erwin |last=Schr\u00f6dinger |authorlink=Erwin Schr\u00f6dinger |doi=10.1093/bjps/iii.10.109}}  [http://www.psiquadrat.de/downloads/schroedinger52_jumps2.pdf Part 2]\n* [http://www.rzuser.uni-heidelberg.de/~as3/no-quantum-jumps.pdf \"There are no quantum jumps, nor are there particles!\"] by H. D. Zeh, ''Physics Letters'' '''A172''', 189 (1993).\n* {{cite news\n | last = Gleick\n | first = James\n | title =Physicists Finally Get To See the Quantum Jump\n | newspaper =The New York Times\n | date = October 21, 1986\n | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/21/science/physicists-finally-get-to-see-quantum-jump-with-own-eyes.html\n | accessdate =2013-08-23}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Ball |first1=Philip |title=Quantum Leaps, Long Assumed to Be Instantaneous, Take Time |url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/quantum-leaps-long-assumed-to-be-instantaneous-take-time-20190605 |website=Quanta Magazine |accessdate=6 June 2019 |date=5 June 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atomic Electron Transition}}\n[[Category:Quantum mechanics]]\n[[Category:Atomic physics]]\n[[Category:Electron states]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the TV series|Quantum Leap|the sculpture|The Quantum Leap}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n'''Atomic electron transition''' is a change of an [[electron]] from one [[energy level]] to another within an [[atom]]<ref>Schombert, James. [http://abyss.uoregon.edu/~js/cosmo/lectures/lec08.html \"Quantum physics\"] University of Oregon Department of Physics</ref> or [[artificial atom]].<ref>{{Cite journal |arxiv = 1009.2969|bibcode = 2011PhRvL.106k0502V|title = Observation of Quantum Jumps in a Superconducting Artificial Atom|journal = Physical Review Letters|volume = 106|issue = 11|pages = 110502|last1 = Vijay|first1 = R|last2 = Slichter|first2 = D. H|last3 = Siddiqi|first3 = I|year = 2011|doi = 10.1103/PhysRevLett.106.110502|pmid = 21469850}}</ref> It appears discontinuous as the electron \"jumps\" from one [[energy level]] to another, typically in a few [[nanosecond]]s or less. It is also known as an '''electronic (de-)excitation''' or '''atomic transition''' or '''quantum jump'''.\n\nElectron transitions cause the emission or absorption of [[electromagnetic radiation]] in the form of quantized units called [[photon]]s. Their statistics are [[Poisson distribution|Poissonian]], and the time between jumps is [[Exponential distribution|exponentially distributed]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mpq.mpg.de/Theorygroup/CIRAC/wiki/images/8/86/Samuel.pdf |last=Del\u00e9glise |first=S. |title=Observing the quantum jumps of light |access-date=September 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107043403/http://www.mpq.mpg.de/Theorygroup/CIRAC/wiki/images/8/86/Samuel.pdf |archive-date=November 7, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The damping time constant (which ranges from [[nanosecond]]s to a few seconds) relates to the natural, pressure, and field [[Spectral line#Line broadening and shift|broadening of spectral lines]]. The larger the energy separation of the states between which the electron jumps, the shorter the [[wavelength]] of the photon emitted.\n\nThe observability of quantum jumps was predicted by [[Hans Dehmelt]] in 1975, and they were first observed using [[Quadrupole ion trap|trapped ions]] of [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] at [[NIST]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Itano|first1=W. M.|last2=Bergquist|first2=J. C.|last3=Wineland|first3=D. J.|title=Early observations of macroscopic quantum jumps in single atoms|journal=International Journal of Mass Spectrometry|date=2015|volume=377|page=403|doi=10.1016/j.ijms.2014.07.005|url=http://tf.boulder.nist.gov/general/pdf/2723.pdf|bibcode = 2015IJMSp.377..403I }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 it was demonstrated in an experiment with a superconducting [[artificial atom]] consisting of two strongly-hybridized [[Transmon|transmon qubits]] placed inside a readout resonator cavity at 15 mK, that the evolution of some jumps is continuous, coherent, [[determinism|deterministic]], and reversible.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Minev |first1=Z. K. |last2=Mundhada |first2=S. O. |last3=Shankar |first3=S. |last4=Reinhold |first4=P. |last5=Guti\u00e9rrez-J\u00e1uregui |first5=R. |last6=Schoelkopf |first6=R. J.. |last7=Mirrahimi |first7=M. |last8=Carmichael |first8=H. J. |last9=Devoret |first9=M. H. |title=To catch and reverse a quantum jump mid-flight |journal=Nature |date=3 June 2019 |volume=570 |issue=7760 |pages=200\u2013204 |doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1287-z |pmid=31160725 |arxiv=1803.00545 }}</ref> On the other hand other quantum jumps are inherently unpredictable ie. nondeterministic.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Snizhko|first=Kyrylo|last2=Kumar|first2=Parveen|last3=Romito|first3=Alessandro|date=2020-03-23|title=The Quantum Zeno effect appears in stages|url=http://arxiv.org/abs/2003.10476|journal=arXiv:2003.10476 [cond-mat, physics:quant-ph]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Burst noise]]\n* [[Ensemble interpretation]]\n* [[Fluorescence]]\n* [[Glowing pickle demonstration]]\n* [[Molecular electronic transition]] for molecules\n* [[Phosphorescence]]\n* [[Spontaneous emission]]\n* [[Stimulated emission]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary|quantum leap}}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://www.psiquadrat.de/downloads/schroedinger52_jumps1.pdf |title=Are there quantum jumps? Part I |journal=The British Journal for the Philosophy of Science |volume=3 |issue=10 |date=August 1952 |pages=109&ndash;123 |first=Erwin |last=Schr\u00f6dinger |authorlink=Erwin Schr\u00f6dinger |doi=10.1093/bjps/iii.10.109}}  [http://www.psiquadrat.de/downloads/schroedinger52_jumps2.pdf Part 2]\n* [http://www.rzuser.uni-heidelberg.de/~as3/no-quantum-jumps.pdf \"There are no quantum jumps, nor are there particles!\"] by H. D. Zeh, ''Physics Letters'' '''A172''', 189 (1993).\n* {{cite news\n | last = Gleick\n | first = James\n | title =Physicists Finally Get To See the Quantum Jump\n | newspaper =The New York Times\n | date = October 21, 1986\n | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/21/science/physicists-finally-get-to-see-quantum-jump-with-own-eyes.html\n | accessdate =2013-08-23}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Ball |first1=Philip |title=Quantum Leaps, Long Assumed to Be Instantaneous, Take Time |url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/quantum-leaps-long-assumed-to-be-instantaneous-take-time-20190605 |website=Quanta Magazine |accessdate=6 June 2019 |date=5 June 2019}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atomic Electron Transition}}\n[[Category:Quantum mechanics]]\n[[Category:Atomic physics]]\n[[Category:Electron states]]\n", "name_user": "Headbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "Various citation & identifier cleanup, plus AWB genfixes (arxiv version pointless when published)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_electron_transition"}
{"title_page": "Active matter", "text_new": "[[File:The flock of starlings acting as a swarm. - geograph.org.uk - 124593.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|A flock of [[common starling|starling]]s acting as a [[swarm]]]]\n'''Active matter''' is composed of large numbers of active \"agents\", each of which consumes [[energy]] in order to move or to exert mechanical forces.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Mechanics and Statistics of Active Matter|journal=Annual Review of Condensed Matter Physics |date=2010-01-01 |pages=323\u2013345 |volume=1 |issue=1 |doi=10.1146/annurev-conmatphys-070909-104101 |first=Sriram|last=Ramaswamy|authorlink=Sriram Ramaswamy|arxiv = 1004.1933 |bibcode = 2010ARCMP...1..323R }}</ref><ref name=\"Marchetti2012\">{{cite journal | last1=Marchetti | first1=M. C. | last2=Joanny | first2=J.F. | last3=Ramaswamy | first3=S. | last4=Liverpool | first4=T. B. | last5=Prost | first5=J. | last6=Rao | first6=M. | last7=Adita Simha | first7=R. | year=2012 | title=Hydrodynamics of soft active matter | journal=[[Reviews of Modern Physics]] | volume=85 | issue=3 | pages=1143\u20131189 | arxiv=1207.2929| doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.85.1143 | bibcode=2013RvMP...85.1143M}}</ref> Such systems are intrinsically out of [[Thermodynamic equilibrium|thermal equilibrium]]. Unlike thermal systems relaxing towards equilibrium and systems with boundary conditions imposing steady currents, active matter systems break [[T-symmetry|time reversal symmetry]] because energy is being continually dissipated by the individual constituents.<ref>{{cite arxiv |last1=Berthier |first1=Ludovic |last2=Kurchan |first2=Jorge |title=Lectures on non-equilibrium active systems |date=7 June 2019 |arxiv=1906.04039}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cates |first1=Michael E. |last2=Tailleur |first2=Julien |title=Motility-Induced Phase Separation |journal=Annual Review of Condensed Matter Physics |date=January 2, 2015 |volume=6 |pages=219\u2013244 |doi=10.1146/annurev-conmatphys-031214-014710 |url=https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev-conmatphys-031214-014710}}</ref> Most examples of active matter are biological in origin and span all the scales of the living, from bacteria and self-organising [[Biopolymer|bio-polymers]] such as [[microtubule]]s and [[actin]] (both of which are part of the [[cytoskeleton]] of living cells), to schools of fish and flocks of birds. However, a great deal of current experimental work is devoted to synthetic systems such as artificial [[self-propelled particles]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bricard |first1=Antoine |last2=Caussin |first2=Jean-Baptiste |last3=Desreumaux |first3=Nicolas |last4=Dauchot |first4=Olivier |last5=Bartolo |first5=Denis |title=Emergence of macroscopic directed motion in populations of motile colloids |journal=Nature |date=6 November 2013 |volume=503 |issue=7474 |pages=95\u201398 |doi=10.1038/nature12673 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nature12673}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Theurkauff |first1=I. |last2=Cottin-Bizonne |first2=C. |last3=Palacci |first3=J. |last4=Ybert |first4=C. |last5=Bocquet |first5=L. |title=Dynamic Clustering in Active Colloidal Suspensions with Chemical Signaling |journal=Physical Review Letters |date=26 June 2012 |volume=108 |issue=26 |page=268303 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.268303 |url=https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.268303}}</ref> Active matter is a relatively new material classification in [[soft matter physics|soft matter]]:  the most extensively studied model, the [[Vicsek model]], dates from 1995.<ref name=\"Vicsek1995\">{{cite journal | last1=Vicsek | first1=T. |authorlink1=Tam\u00e1s Vicsek| last2=Czirok | first2=A. | last3=Ben-Jacob | first3=E. | last4=Cohen | first4=I. | last5=Shochet | first5=O. | year=1995 | title=Novel type of phase transition in a system of self-driven particles | journal=[[Physical Review Letters]] | volume=75 | pages=1226\u20131229 | arxiv=cond-mat/0611743| doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.75.1226 | issue=6 | bibcode=1995PhRvL..75.1226V | pmid=10060237}}</ref>\n\nResearch in active matter combines analytical techniques, numerical simulations and experiments. Notable analytical approaches include [[Fluid dynamics|hydrodynamics]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |title=Hydrodynamics and phases of flocks |journal=Annals of Physics |date=2005-07-01 |pages=170\u2013244 |volume=318 |series=Special Issue |issue=1 |doi=10.1016/j.aop.2005.04.011 |first=John |last=Toner|first2=Yuhai|last2=Tu|first3=Sriram|last3=Ramaswamy|bibcode = 2005AnPhy.318..170T |url=http://eprints.iisc.ac.in/3397/1/A89.pdf }}</ref> [[kinetic theory of gases|kinetic theory]], and non-equilibrium [[statistical physics]]. Numerical studies mainly involve [[Self-propelled particles|self-propelled-particles]] models,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Novel Type of Phase Transition in a System of Self-Driven Particles|journal=Physical Review Letters|date=1995-08-07|pages=1226\u20131229|volume=75|issue=6|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.75.1226|first=Tam\u00e1s|last=Vicsek|first2=Andr\u00e1s|last2=Czir\u00f3k|first3=Eshel|last3=Ben-Jacob|first4=Inon|last4=Cohen|first5=Ofer|last5=Shochet|pmid=10060237|arxiv = cond-mat/0611743 |bibcode = 1995PhRvL..75.1226V }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Collective motion of self-propelled particles interacting without cohesion|journal=Physical Review E|date=2008-04-18|pages=046113|volume=77|issue=4|doi=10.1103/PhysRevE.77.046113|pmid=18517696|first=Hugues|last=Chat\u00e9|first2=Francesco|last2=Ginelli|first3=Guillaume|last3=Gr\u00e9goire|first4=Franck|last4=Raynaud|arxiv = 0712.2062 |bibcode = 2008PhRvE..77d6113C }}</ref> making use of [[Agent-based model|agent-based]] models such as [[molecular dynamics]] algorithms as well as computational studies of hydrodynamic equations of [[active fluid]]s.<ref name=\":0\" /> Experiments on biological systems extend over a wide range of scales, including animal groups (e.g., bird flocks,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Interaction ruling animal collective behavior depends on topological rather than metric distance: Evidence from a field study|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|date=2008-01-29|issn=0027-8424|pmc=2234121|pmid=18227508|pages=1232\u20131237|volume=105|issue=4|doi=10.1073/pnas.0711437105|first=M.|last=Ballerini|first2=N.|last2=Cabibbo|first3=R.|last3=Candelier|first4=A.|last4=Cavagna|first5=E.|last5=Cisbani|first6=I.|last6=Giardina|first7=V.|last7=Lecomte|first8=A.|last8=Orlandi|first9=G.|last9=Parisi|arxiv = 0709.1916 |bibcode = 2008PNAS..105.1232B }}</ref> mammalian herds, fish schools and insect swarms<ref>{{Cite journal|title=From Disorder to Order in Marching Locusts|journal=Science|date=2006-06-02|issn=0036-8075|pmid=16741126|pages=1402\u20131406|volume=312|issue=5778|doi=10.1126/science.1125142|first=J.|last=Buhl|first2=D. J. T.|last2=Sumpter|first3=I. D.|last3=Couzin|first4=J. J.|last4=Hale|first5=E.|last5=Despland|first6=E. R.|last6=Miller|first7=S. J.|last7=Simpson|bibcode = 2006Sci...312.1402B }}</ref>), bacterial colonies, cellular tissues (e.g. epithelial tissue layers,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Physical forces during collective cell migration|journal=Nature Physics|date=2009-06-01|issn=1745-2473|pages=426\u2013430|volume=5|issue=6|doi=10.1038/nphys1269|first=Xavier|last=Trepat|first2=Michael R.|last2=Wasserman|first3=Thomas E.|last3=Angelini|first4=Emil|last4=Millet|first5=David A.|last5=Weitz|first6=James P.|last6=Butler|first7=Jeffrey J.|last7=Fredberg|bibcode = 2009NatPh...5..426T }}</ref> cancer growth and embryogenesis), [[cytoskeleton]] components (e.g., ''in vitro'' motility assays, actin-myosin networks and molecular-motor driven filaments<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Topology and dynamics of active nematic vesicles|journal=Science|date=2014-09-05|issn=0036-8075|pmc=4401068|pmid=25190790|pages=1135\u20131139|volume=345|issue=6201|doi=10.1126/science.1254784|first=Felix C.|last=Keber|first2=Etienne|last2=Loiseau|first3=Tim|last3=Sanchez|first4=Stephen J.|last4=DeCamp|first5=Luca|last5=Giomi|first6=Mark J.|last6=Bowick|first7=M. Cristina|last7=Marchetti|first8=Zvonimir|last8=Dogic|first9=Andreas R.|last9=Bausch|arxiv = 1409.1836 |bibcode = 2014Sci...345.1135K }}</ref>). Experiments on synthetic systems include self-propelled colloids (e.g., phoretically propelled particles<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Living Crystals of Light-Activated Colloidal Surfers|journal=Science|date=2013-02-22|issn=0036-8075|pmid=23371555|pages=936\u2013940|volume=339|issue=6122|doi=10.1126/science.1230020|first=Jeremie|last=Palacci|first2=Stefano|last2=Sacanna|first3=Asher Preska|last3=Steinberg|first4=David J.|last4=Pine|first5=Paul M.|last5=Chaikin|bibcode = 2013Sci...339..936P }}</ref>), driven granular matter (e.g. vibrated monolayers<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Collective Motion of Vibrated Polar Disks|journal=Physical Review Letters|date=2010-08-23|pages=098001|volume=105|issue=9|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.105.098001|pmid=20868196|first=Julien|last=Deseigne|first2=Olivier|last2=Dauchot|first3=Hugues|last3=Chat\u00e9|bibcode=2010PhRvL.105i8001D|arxiv = 1004.1499 }}</ref>), swarming robots and Quinke rotators.\n\n'''Concepts in Active matter'''\n* Active gels\n** Dense active matter\n* [[Collective motion]]\n** [[Collective animal behavior]]\n** [[Collective cell migration]]\n* Motility induced phase separation\n* [[Shoaling and schooling|Schooling]], [[Flocking (behavior)|flocking]] and [[Swarm behaviour|swarming]]\n* [[Collective motion]]\n* Active [[Stress (mechanics)|stress]] \n* [[Disordered hyperuniformity]]\n\n'''Active matter systems'''\n* [[Biological tissue]]s\n** Subcellular and cell mechanics\n* [[Crowd simulation|Crowd behaviour]]\n* [[Self-propelled particles]] and [[colloid]]s\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|32em}}\n\n{{swarming}}\n\n[[Category:Soft matter]]\n[[Category:Crowds]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:The flock of starlings acting as a swarm. - geograph.org.uk - 124593.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|A flock of [[common starling|starling]]s acting as a [[swarm]]]]\n'''Active matter''' is composed of large numbers of active \"agents\", each of which consumes [[energy]] in order to move or to exert mechanical forces.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Mechanics and Statistics of Active Matter|journal=Annual Review of Condensed Matter Physics |date=2010-01-01 |pages=323\u2013345 |volume=1 |issue=1 |doi=10.1146/annurev-conmatphys-070909-104101 |first=Sriram|last=Ramaswamy|authorlink=Sriram Ramaswamy|arxiv = 1004.1933 |bibcode = 2010ARCMP...1..323R }}</ref><ref name=\"Marchetti2012\">{{cite journal | last1=Marchetti | first1=M. C. | last2=Joanny | first2=J.F. | last3=Ramaswamy | first3=S. | last4=Liverpool | first4=T. B. | last5=Prost | first5=J. | last6=Rao | first6=M. | last7=Adita Simha | first7=R. | year=2012 | title=Hydrodynamics of soft active matter | journal=[[Reviews of Modern Physics]] | volume=85 | issue=3 | pages=1143\u20131189 | arxiv=1207.2929| doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.85.1143 | bibcode=2013RvMP...85.1143M}}</ref> Such systems are intrinsically out of [[Thermodynamic equilibrium|thermal equilibrium]]. Unlike thermal systems relaxing towards equilibrium and systems with boundary conditions imposing steady currents, active matter systems break [[T-symmetry|time reversal symmetry]] because energy is being continually dissipated by the individual constituents.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Berthier |first1=Ludovic |last2=Kurchan |first2=Jorge |title=Lectures on non-equilibrium active systems |journal=arXiv:1906.04039 |date=7 June 2019 |url=https://arxiv.org/abs/1906.04039}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cates |first1=Michael E. |last2=Tailleur |first2=Julien |title=Motility-Induced Phase Separation |journal=Annual Review of Condensed Matter Physics |date=January 2, 2015 |volume=6 |pages=219-244 |doi=10.1146/annurev-conmatphys-031214-014710 |url=https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev-conmatphys-031214-014710}}</ref> Most examples of active matter are biological in origin and span all the scales of the living, from bacteria and self-organising [[Biopolymer|bio-polymers]] such as [[microtubule]]s and [[actin]] (both of which are part of the [[cytoskeleton]] of living cells), to schools of fish and flocks of birds. However, a great deal of current experimental work is devoted to synthetic systems such as artificial [[self-propelled particles]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bricard |first1=Antoine |last2=Caussin |first2=Jean-Baptiste |last3=Desreumaux |first3=Nicolas |last4=Dauchot |first4=Olivier |last5=Bartolo |first5=Denis |title=Emergence of macroscopic directed motion in populations of motile colloids |journal=Nature |date=6 November 2013 |volume=503 |issue=7474 |pages=95-98 |doi=10.1038/nature12673 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nature12673}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Theurkauff |first1=I. |last2=Cottin-Bizonne |first2=C. |last3=Palacci |first3=J. |last4=Ybert |first4=C. |last5=Bocquet |first5=L. |title=Dynamic Clustering in Active Colloidal Suspensions with Chemical Signaling |journal=Physical Review Letters |date=26 June 2012 |volume=108 |issue=26 |page=268303 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.268303 |url=https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.268303}}</ref> Active matter is a relatively new material classification in [[soft matter physics|soft matter]]:  the most extensively studied model, the [[Vicsek model]], dates from 1995.<ref name=\"Vicsek1995\">{{cite journal | last1=Vicsek | first1=T. |authorlink1=Tam\u00e1s Vicsek| last2=Czirok | first2=A. | last3=Ben-Jacob | first3=E. | last4=Cohen | first4=I. | last5=Shochet | first5=O. | year=1995 | title=Novel type of phase transition in a system of self-driven particles | journal=[[Physical Review Letters]] | volume=75 | pages=1226\u20131229 | arxiv=cond-mat/0611743| doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.75.1226 | issue=6 | bibcode=1995PhRvL..75.1226V | pmid=10060237}}</ref>\n\nResearch in active matter combines analytical techniques, numerical simulations and experiments. Notable analytical approaches include [[Fluid dynamics|hydrodynamics]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |title=Hydrodynamics and phases of flocks |journal=Annals of Physics |date=2005-07-01 |pages=170\u2013244 |volume=318 |series=Special Issue |issue=1 |doi=10.1016/j.aop.2005.04.011 |first=John |last=Toner|first2=Yuhai|last2=Tu|first3=Sriram|last3=Ramaswamy|bibcode = 2005AnPhy.318..170T |url=http://eprints.iisc.ac.in/3397/1/A89.pdf }}</ref> [[kinetic theory of gases|kinetic theory]], and non-equilibrium [[statistical physics]]. Numerical studies mainly involve [[Self-propelled particles|self-propelled-particles]] models,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Novel Type of Phase Transition in a System of Self-Driven Particles|journal=Physical Review Letters|date=1995-08-07|pages=1226\u20131229|volume=75|issue=6|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.75.1226|first=Tam\u00e1s|last=Vicsek|first2=Andr\u00e1s|last2=Czir\u00f3k|first3=Eshel|last3=Ben-Jacob|first4=Inon|last4=Cohen|first5=Ofer|last5=Shochet|pmid=10060237|arxiv = cond-mat/0611743 |bibcode = 1995PhRvL..75.1226V }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Collective motion of self-propelled particles interacting without cohesion|journal=Physical Review E|date=2008-04-18|pages=046113|volume=77|issue=4|doi=10.1103/PhysRevE.77.046113|pmid=18517696|first=Hugues|last=Chat\u00e9|first2=Francesco|last2=Ginelli|first3=Guillaume|last3=Gr\u00e9goire|first4=Franck|last4=Raynaud|arxiv = 0712.2062 |bibcode = 2008PhRvE..77d6113C }}</ref> making use of [[Agent-based model|agent-based]] models such as [[molecular dynamics]] algorithms as well as computational studies of hydrodynamic equations of [[active fluid]]s.<ref name=\":0\" /> Experiments on biological systems extend over a wide range of scales, including animal groups (e.g., bird flocks,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Interaction ruling animal collective behavior depends on topological rather than metric distance: Evidence from a field study|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|date=2008-01-29|issn=0027-8424|pmc=2234121|pmid=18227508|pages=1232\u20131237|volume=105|issue=4|doi=10.1073/pnas.0711437105|first=M.|last=Ballerini|first2=N.|last2=Cabibbo|first3=R.|last3=Candelier|first4=A.|last4=Cavagna|first5=E.|last5=Cisbani|first6=I.|last6=Giardina|first7=V.|last7=Lecomte|first8=A.|last8=Orlandi|first9=G.|last9=Parisi|arxiv = 0709.1916 |bibcode = 2008PNAS..105.1232B }}</ref> mammalian herds, fish schools and insect swarms<ref>{{Cite journal|title=From Disorder to Order in Marching Locusts|journal=Science|date=2006-06-02|issn=0036-8075|pmid=16741126|pages=1402\u20131406|volume=312|issue=5778|doi=10.1126/science.1125142|first=J.|last=Buhl|first2=D. J. T.|last2=Sumpter|first3=I. D.|last3=Couzin|first4=J. J.|last4=Hale|first5=E.|last5=Despland|first6=E. R.|last6=Miller|first7=S. J.|last7=Simpson|bibcode = 2006Sci...312.1402B }}</ref>), bacterial colonies, cellular tissues (e.g. epithelial tissue layers,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Physical forces during collective cell migration|journal=Nature Physics|date=2009-06-01|issn=1745-2473|pages=426\u2013430|volume=5|issue=6|doi=10.1038/nphys1269|first=Xavier|last=Trepat|first2=Michael R.|last2=Wasserman|first3=Thomas E.|last3=Angelini|first4=Emil|last4=Millet|first5=David A.|last5=Weitz|first6=James P.|last6=Butler|first7=Jeffrey J.|last7=Fredberg|bibcode = 2009NatPh...5..426T }}</ref> cancer growth and embryogenesis), [[cytoskeleton]] components (e.g., ''in vitro'' motility assays, actin-myosin networks and molecular-motor driven filaments<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Topology and dynamics of active nematic vesicles|journal=Science|date=2014-09-05|issn=0036-8075|pmc=4401068|pmid=25190790|pages=1135\u20131139|volume=345|issue=6201|doi=10.1126/science.1254784|first=Felix C.|last=Keber|first2=Etienne|last2=Loiseau|first3=Tim|last3=Sanchez|first4=Stephen J.|last4=DeCamp|first5=Luca|last5=Giomi|first6=Mark J.|last6=Bowick|first7=M. Cristina|last7=Marchetti|first8=Zvonimir|last8=Dogic|first9=Andreas R.|last9=Bausch|arxiv = 1409.1836 |bibcode = 2014Sci...345.1135K }}</ref>). Experiments on synthetic systems include self-propelled colloids (e.g., phoretically propelled particles<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Living Crystals of Light-Activated Colloidal Surfers|journal=Science|date=2013-02-22|issn=0036-8075|pmid=23371555|pages=936\u2013940|volume=339|issue=6122|doi=10.1126/science.1230020|first=Jeremie|last=Palacci|first2=Stefano|last2=Sacanna|first3=Asher Preska|last3=Steinberg|first4=David J.|last4=Pine|first5=Paul M.|last5=Chaikin|bibcode = 2013Sci...339..936P }}</ref>), driven granular matter (e.g. vibrated monolayers<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Collective Motion of Vibrated Polar Disks|journal=Physical Review Letters|date=2010-08-23|pages=098001|volume=105|issue=9|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.105.098001|pmid=20868196|first=Julien|last=Deseigne|first2=Olivier|last2=Dauchot|first3=Hugues|last3=Chat\u00e9|bibcode=2010PhRvL.105i8001D|arxiv = 1004.1499 }}</ref>), swarming robots and Quinke rotators.\n\n'''Concepts in Active matter'''\n* Active gels\n** Dense active matter\n* [[Collective motion]]\n** [[Collective animal behavior]]\n** [[Collective cell migration]]\n* Motility induced phase separation\n* [[Shoaling and schooling|Schooling]], [[Flocking (behavior)|flocking]] and [[Swarm behaviour|swarming]]\n* [[Collective motion]]\n* Active [[Stress_(mechanics)|stress]] \n* [[Disordered hyperuniformity]]\n\n\n'''Active matter systems'''\n* [[Biological tissue]]s\n** Subcellular and cell mechanics\n* [[Crowd simulation|Crowd behaviour]]\n* [[Self-propelled particles]] and [[colloid]]s\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|32em}}\n\n{{swarming}}\n\n[[Category:Soft matter]]\n[[Category:Crowds]]\n", "name_user": "Headbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Various citation & identifier cleanup, plus AWB genfixes (arxiv version pointless when published)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Active_matter"}
{"title_page": "Son o se hacen", "text_new": "'''''Son o se hacen''''' is a 1997 Argentine comedy television series. It stars [[Julieta Ortega]], [[Rodrigo de la Serna|Rodrigo De la Serna]], [[Carolina Fal]], [[Walter Quiroz]], and [[Iv\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez (actor)|Iv\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez]]. It was one of the first Argentine television series to explore the topic of [[sexual diversity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmaffinity.com/es/film954946.html|title=Son o se hacen|publisher=Film Affinity|accessdate=21 August 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Argentine comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1997 Argentine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1997 Argentine television series endings]]\n[[Category:Argentine LGBT-related television shows]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-tv-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''''Son o se hacen''''' is a 1997 Argentine comedy television series. It stars [[Julieta Ortega]], [[Rodrigo De la Serna]], [[Carolina Fal]], [[Walter Quiroz]], and [[Iv\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez (actor)|Iv\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez]]. It was one of the first Argentine television series to explore the topic of [[sexual diversity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmaffinity.com/es/film954946.html|title=Son o se hacen|publisher=Film Affinity|accessdate=21 August 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Argentine comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1997 Argentine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1997 Argentine television series endings]]\n[[Category:Argentine LGBT-related television shows]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-tv-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Flo19", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated link to actor's wikipedia page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Son_o_se_hacen"}
{"title_page": "Karel Teige", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Karel Teige\n| image        = 1925_Toyen_och_Karel_Teige.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = Teige with [[Toyen]] in 1925\n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1900|12|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Prague]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1951|10|1|1900|12|13|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| occupation   = Publicist, literary critic\n| nationality  = [[Czechs|Czech]]\n| period       = \n| genre        = \n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = Josef Teige (father)\n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n}}\n\n'''Karel Teige''' (13 December 1900  \u2013 1 October 1951) was a Czech [[Modernism|modernist]] [[avant-garde]] artist, writer, critic and one of the most important figures of the 1920s and 1930s  movement. He was a member of the ''[[Dev\u011btsil]]'' (Butterbur) movement in the 1920s and also worked as an editor and graphic designer for Dev\u011btsil's monthly magazine ''ReD'' (''Revue Dev\u011btsilu''). One of his major works on architecture theory is ''The Minimum Dwelling'' (1932).<ref>[https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/minimum-dwelling The Minimum Dwelling]. mitpress.mit.edu.</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nTeige was born in [[Prague]]. With evidently endless energy, he introduced modern art to [[Prague]]. ''Dev\u011btsil''-sponsored exhibitions and events brought international avant-garde figures like [[Le Corbusier]], [[Man Ray]], [[Paul Klee]], [[Vladimir Mayakovsky]], and [[Walter Gropius]], among many others, to lecture and perform in Prague. Teige interpreted their work, sometimes literally, for the Czech audience. In his 1935 Prague lecture, [[Andr\u00e9 Breton]] paid tribute to his \"perfect intellectual fellowship\" with Teige and [[V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nezval|Nezval]]: \"Constantly interpreted by Teige in the most lively way, made to undergo an all-powerful lyric thrust by Nezval, Surrealism can flatter itself that it has blossomed in Prague as it has in Paris.\" <ref>\"Surrealist situation of the object\" in {{cite book | last=Breton |first=Andr\u00e9 | title=Manifestoes of Surrealism | url=https://archive.org/details/manifestoesofsur0000bret | url-access=registration | publisher=University of Michigan Press | year=1972| isbn=0-472-06182-8}}, p256</ref>\n\nAlthough not an architect, Teige was an articulate and knowledgeable architecture critic, an active participant in [[Congr\u00e8s International d'Architecture Moderne|CIAM]], and friends with [[Hannes Meyer]], the second director of the [[Bauhaus]]. \nFrom 1929 to 1930 he gave guest lectures at the Bauhaus in [[Dessau]] <ref>Dluhosch, Eric (ed.); Svacha, Rostislav (ed.) (1999) ''Karel Teige / 1900-1951: L\u2019enfant terrible of the Czech modernist avant-garde''. Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</ref>\n\nTeige and Meyer both believed in a scientific, [[Functionalism (architecture)|functionalist]] approach to architecture, grounded in [[Marxism|Marxist]] principles. In 1929 he famously criticized Le Corbusier's [[Mundaneum]] project (planned for [[Geneva]] but never built) on the grounds that Corbusier had departed from rational functionalism, and was on his way to becoming a mere stylist. Teige believed that 'the only aim and scope of modern architecture is the scientific solution of exact tasks of rational construction.'\n\nAfter welcoming the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] army as liberators, Teige was silenced by the [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|Communist]] government in 1948. In 1951 he died in Prague of a heart attack, said to be a result of a ferocious Soviet press campaign against him as a '[[Trotskyite|Trotskyism]] degenerate,' his papers were destroyed by the secret police, and his published work was suppressed for decades.\n\n== Writings ==\n\u0634\u0633\u06cc\u0633\u06cc\n===Original versions===\n\n==== Studies ====\n* ''Stavba a b\u00e1se\u0148'' (1927)\n* ''Sv\u011bt, kter\u00fd se sm\u011bje'' (1928)\n* ''Sv\u011bt, kter\u00fd von\u00ed'' (1930)\n* ''Surrealismus proti proudu'' (1938)\n* ''Jarmark um\u011bn\u00ed'' (1964)\n\n====Scientific writings====\n* ''Archipenko'' (1923)\n* ''Jan Zrzav\u00fd'' (1923)\n* ''Soudob\u00e1 mezin\u00e1rodn\u00ed architektura'' (1928)\n* ''Sov\u011btsk\u00e1 kultura'' (1928)\n* ''Modern\u00ed architektura v \u010ceskoslovensku'' (1930. Translated to English and published as ''Modern Architecture in Czechoslovakia and Other Writings'' in 2000)\n* ''Nejmen\u0161\u00ed byt'' (1932. Translated to English and published as ''The Minimum Dwelling'' in 2002)\n* ''Zahradn\u00ed m\u011bsta nezam\u011bstnan\u00fdch'' (1933)\n* ''Architektura prav\u00e1 a lev\u00e1'' (1934)\n* ''V\u00fdvoj sov\u011btsk\u00e9 architektury'' (1936)\n* ''Vladim\u00edr Majakovskij'' (1936)\n* ''\u0160tyrsk\u00fd a Toyen'' (1938 with [[V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nezval]])\n* ''Modern\u00ed fotografie v \u010ceskoslovensku'' (1947)\n* ''Sociologie architektury'' (date unknown)\n* ''Fenomenologie modern\u00edho um\u011bn\u00ed'' (unfinished work, ''The Phenomenology of Modern Art''. Two parts of this work were published posthumously as ''V\u00fdvojov\u00e9 prom\u011bny v um\u011bn\u00ed'' (''Developmental Changes in Art'') in 1966.)\n\n===English Editions===\n*''Modern Architecture in Czechoslovakia and Other Writings'' (Texts & Documents), J P Getty Trust Pubn, 2000, {{ISBN|0-89236-596-X}}\n*''The Minimum Dwelling'', MIT Press, 2002, {{ISBN|0-262-20136-4}}\n\n==Secondary literature==\n*''Karel Teige. L'Enfant Terrible of the Czech Modernist Avant-Garde'', ed. by Eric Dluhosch and Rostislav Sv\u00e1cha, MIT Press, 1999, {{ISBN|0-262-04170-7}} -  includes 4 Essays of Teige \n*Esther Levinger: \"A life in nature - Karel Teige's journey from Poetism to Surrealism\" In: ''Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Kunstgeschichte'', vol. 67.2004, 3, pp.&nbsp;401\u2013420 \n*Peter A. Zusi: \"The Style of the Present: Karel Teige on Constructivism and Poetism\" in: ''Representations'', 88. Fall 2004, pp.&nbsp;102\u2013124\n*''Prager Architektur und die europ\u00e4ische Moderne'', ed. by Tom\u00e1\u0161 Valena and Ulrich Winko, Berlin: Mann, 2006\n*Radu-Alexandra R\u0103u\u0163\u0103: \"Shifting meanings of modernism: parallels and contrasts between Karel Teige and [[Cezar L\u0103z\u0103rescu]]\" in:\t''The journal of architecture'', Royal Institute of British Architects. - Bd. 14.2009, 1, S. 27-44\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090727162116/http://www.ce-review.org/00/7/hearld7.html On Teige's erotic surrealist photomontages]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020315141836/http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/exhibits/teige/ Dreams and Disillusion] Karel Teige and the Czech Avant-Garde\n* [https://www.fostinum.org/czech-photomontage.html Fostinum: Czech Photomontage] Numerous examples of Karel Teige's work\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teige, Karel}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Prague]]\n[[Category:Czech artists]]\n[[Category:Czech photographers]]\n[[Category:Bauhaus teachers]]\n[[Category:Czech journalists]]\n[[Category:Czech translators]]\n[[Category:Czech literary critics]]\n[[Category:Czech surrealist writers]]\n[[Category:Czech surrealist artists]]\n[[Category:Surrealist poets]]\n[[Category:Czech communists]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak communists]]\n[[Category:20th-century translators]]\n[[Category:Writers from Prague]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Karel Teige\n| image        = 1925_Toyen_och_Karel_Teige.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = Teige with [[Toyen]] in 1925\n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1900|12|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Prague]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1951|10|1|1900|12|13|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| occupation   = Publicist, literary critic\n| nationality  = [[Czechs|Czech]]\n| period       = \n| genre        = \n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = Josef Teige (father)\n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n}}\n\n'''Karel Teige''' (13 December 1900  \u2013 1 October 1951) was a Czech [[Modernism|modernist]] [[avant-garde]] artist, writer, critic and one of the most important figures of the 1920s and 1930s  movement. He was a member of the ''[[Dev\u011btsil]]'' (Butterbur) movement in the 1920s and also worked as an editor and graphic designer for Dev\u011btsil's monthly magazine ''ReD'' (''Revue Dev\u011btsilu''). One of his major works on architecture theory is ''The Minimum Dwelling'' (1932).<ref>[https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/minimum-dwelling The Minimum Dwelling]. mitpress.mit.edu.</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nTeige was born in [[Prague]]. With evidently endless energy, he introduced modern art to [[Prague]]. ''Dev\u011btsil''-sponsored exhibitions and events brought international avant-garde figures like [[Le Corbusier]], [[Man Ray]], [[Paul Klee]], [[Vladimir Mayakovsky]], and [[Walter Gropius]], among many others, to lecture and perform in Prague. Teige interpreted their work, sometimes literally, for the Czech audience. In his 1935 Prague lecture, [[Andr\u00e9 Breton]] paid tribute to his \"perfect intellectual fellowship\" with Teige and [[V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nezval|Nezval]]: \"Constantly interpreted by Teige in the most lively way, made to undergo an all-powerful lyric thrust by Nezval, Surrealism can flatter itself that it has blossomed in Prague as it has in Paris.\" <ref>\"Surrealist situation of the object\" in {{cite book | last=Breton |first=Andr\u00e9 | title=Manifestoes of Surrealism | url=https://archive.org/details/manifestoesofsur0000bret | url-access=registration | publisher=University of Michigan Press | year=1972| isbn=0-472-06182-8}}, p256</ref>\n\nAlthough not an architect, Teige was an articulate and knowledgeable architecture critic, an active participant in [[Congr\u00e8s International d'Architecture Moderne|CIAM]], and friends with [[Hannes Meyer]], the second director of the [[Bauhaus]]. \nFrom 1929 to 1930 he gave guest lectures at the Bauhaus in [[Dessau]] <ref>Dluhosch, Eric (ed.); Svacha, Rostislav (ed.) (1999) ''Karel Teige / 1900-1951: L\u2019enfant terrible of the Czech modernist avant-garde''. Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</ref>\n\nTeige and Meyer both believed in a scientific, [[Functionalism (architecture)|functionalist]] approach to architecture, grounded in [[Marxism|Marxist]] principles. In 1929 he famously criticized Le Corbusier's [[Mundaneum]] project (planned for [[Geneva]] but never built) on the grounds that Corbusier had departed from rational functionalism, and was on his way to becoming a mere stylist. Teige believed that 'the only aim and scope of modern architecture is the scientific solution of exact tasks of rational construction.'\n\nAfter welcoming the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] army as liberators, Teige was silenced by the [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|Communist]] government in 1948. In 1951 he died in Prague of a heart attack, said to be a result of a ferocious Soviet press campaign against him as a '[[Trotskyite|Trotskyism]] degenerate,' his papers were destroyed by the secret police, and his published work was suppressed for decades.\n\n== Writings ==\n\n===Original versions===\n\n==== Studies ====\n* ''Stavba a b\u00e1se\u0148'' (1927)\n* ''Sv\u011bt, kter\u00fd se sm\u011bje'' (1928)\n* ''Sv\u011bt, kter\u00fd von\u00ed'' (1930)\n* ''Surrealismus proti proudu'' (1938)\n* ''Jarmark um\u011bn\u00ed'' (1964)\n\n====Scientific writings====\n* ''Archipenko'' (1923)\n* ''Jan Zrzav\u00fd'' (1923)\n* ''Soudob\u00e1 mezin\u00e1rodn\u00ed architektura'' (1928)\n* ''Sov\u011btsk\u00e1 kultura'' (1928)\n* ''Modern\u00ed architektura v \u010ceskoslovensku'' (1930. Translated to English and published as ''Modern Architecture in Czechoslovakia and Other Writings'' in 2000)\n* ''Nejmen\u0161\u00ed byt'' (1932. Translated to English and published as ''The Minimum Dwelling'' in 2002)\n* ''Zahradn\u00ed m\u011bsta nezam\u011bstnan\u00fdch'' (1933)\n* ''Architektura prav\u00e1 a lev\u00e1'' (1934)\n* ''V\u00fdvoj sov\u011btsk\u00e9 architektury'' (1936)\n* ''Vladim\u00edr Majakovskij'' (1936)\n* ''\u0160tyrsk\u00fd a Toyen'' (1938 with [[V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nezval]])\n* ''Modern\u00ed fotografie v \u010ceskoslovensku'' (1947)\n* ''Sociologie architektury'' (date unknown)\n* ''Fenomenologie modern\u00edho um\u011bn\u00ed'' (unfinished work, ''The Phenomenology of Modern Art''. Two parts of this work were published posthumously as ''V\u00fdvojov\u00e9 prom\u011bny v um\u011bn\u00ed'' (''Developmental Changes in Art'') in 1966.)\n\n===English Editions===\n*''Modern Architecture in Czechoslovakia and Other Writings'' (Texts & Documents), J P Getty Trust Pubn, 2000, {{ISBN|0-89236-596-X}}\n*''The Minimum Dwelling'', MIT Press, 2002, {{ISBN|0-262-20136-4}}\n\n==Secondary literature==\n*''Karel Teige. L'Enfant Terrible of the Czech Modernist Avant-Garde'', ed. by Eric Dluhosch and Rostislav Sv\u00e1cha, MIT Press, 1999, {{ISBN|0-262-04170-7}} -  includes 4 Essays of Teige \n*Esther Levinger: \"A life in nature - Karel Teige's journey from Poetism to Surrealism\" In: ''Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Kunstgeschichte'', vol. 67.2004, 3, pp.&nbsp;401\u2013420 \n*Peter A. Zusi: \"The Style of the Present: Karel Teige on Constructivism and Poetism\" in: ''Representations'', 88. Fall 2004, pp.&nbsp;102\u2013124\n*''Prager Architektur und die europ\u00e4ische Moderne'', ed. by Tom\u00e1\u0161 Valena and Ulrich Winko, Berlin: Mann, 2006\n*Radu-Alexandra R\u0103u\u0163\u0103: \"Shifting meanings of modernism: parallels and contrasts between Karel Teige and [[Cezar L\u0103z\u0103rescu]]\" in:\t''The journal of architecture'', Royal Institute of British Architects. - Bd. 14.2009, 1, S. 27-44\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090727162116/http://www.ce-review.org/00/7/hearld7.html On Teige's erotic surrealist photomontages]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020315141836/http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/exhibits/teige/ Dreams and Disillusion] Karel Teige and the Czech Avant-Garde\n* [https://www.fostinum.org/czech-photomontage.html Fostinum: Czech Photomontage] Numerous examples of Karel Teige's work\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teige, Karel}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Prague]]\n[[Category:Czech artists]]\n[[Category:Czech photographers]]\n[[Category:Bauhaus teachers]]\n[[Category:Czech journalists]]\n[[Category:Czech translators]]\n[[Category:Czech literary critics]]\n[[Category:Czech surrealist writers]]\n[[Category:Czech surrealist artists]]\n[[Category:Surrealist poets]]\n[[Category:Czech communists]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak communists]]\n[[Category:20th-century translators]]\n[[Category:Writers from Prague]]\n", "name_user": "62.102.137.188", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eWritings)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karel_Teige"}
{"title_page": "Cunard Building (New York City)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Cunard Building{{!}}Cunard Building, Liverpool}}\n{{short description|Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Cunard Building\n| image = File:Bowling Green-Battery Pk 01 - Cunard.jpg\n| image_size =\n| image_caption =\n| former_names =\n| alternate_names = Standard & Poors Building\n| status = Complete\n| building_type = Office\n| architectural_style = [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Neo-Renaissance]]\n| classification =\n| location = 25 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]<br />[[Financial District, Manhattan]], New York\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|42|21|N|74|00|51|W|display=inline,title}}\n| groundbreaking_date =\n| start_date = 1920\n| stop_date =\n| topped_out_date =\n| completion_date = 1921\n| opened_date = May 2, 1921\n| inauguration_date =\n| client = [[Cunard Line]]\n| owner =\n| height = {{convert|254.74|ft|m}}\n| material =\n| size =\n| floor_count = 22 (+1 basement)\n| floor_area =\n| elevator_count =\n| architect = [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris III]]\n| architecture_firm = [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]]\n| embedded = {{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = NYC\n| designation1_date = September 19, 1995\n| designation1_number = 1928 (exterior), 1929 (interior)\n}}\n| references = <ref name=\"emporis\" />\n}}\nThe '''Cunard Building''', also known as the '''Standard & Poors Building''', is a 22-story office building located at 25 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]], adjacent to [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green Park]] in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. The Cunard Building was designed in the [[Renaissance architecture|Italian Renaissance]] style by [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris]], in conjunction with consultants [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]].\n\nThe Cunard Building's main facade, on Broadway, is made of limestone and consists of three horizontal sections. The design employs [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] and open \"light courts\" as mandated by the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]]. The structure was designed around an irregular street grid and is located directly above a [[New York City Subway|subway]] line that crosses the building site diagonally. The first floor interior contains an elaborately decorated lobby, as well as a similarly opulent Great Hall, which extends {{Convert|185|ft||abbr=}} with a {{Convert|65|ft|m|abbr=|-tall|adj=mid}} dome. The remaining floors contain various offices and school spaces.\n\nThe Cunard Building was erected for the New York City office of the [[Cunard Line]], a British-American steamship line; construction started in 1920 and the building was completed the next year. Upon completion, the Cunard Building was almost fully leased to tenants of various industries. The Twenty-five Broadway Corporation, a Cunard Line affiliate, owned the building until the 1960s. The Great Hall was vacated after the Cunard Line moved out in 1968; the [[United States Postal Service]] occupied the Great Hall from 1974 until 2000, and [[Cipriani S.A.]] started using the space in 2014. The upper floors continued to host offices and various educational facilities.\n\nUpon completion, the Cunard Building's exterior and interior designs received critical acclaim. The Cunard Building's facade and principal first-floor interior spaces were designated as [[List of New York City Landmarks|landmarks]] by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1995.\n\n== Description ==\nThe Cunard Building is a 22-story building,<ref name=\"emporis\" /> bounded by the [[Bowling Green Offices Building]] (11 Broadway) to the south, Broadway to the east, [[Greenwich Street]] to the west, and Morris Street to the north.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/02/20/archives/cunard-to-have-big-building-here-10000000-structure-of-26-stories.html|title=Cunard To Have Big Building Here; $10,000,000 Structure of 26 Stories Going Up on Site of Old Stevens House.|last=|first=|date=February 20, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune-Cunard-1919\" /> It is located across from [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green Park]] to the southeast, and [[26 Broadway]] and the ''[[Charging Bull]]'' sculpture to the east.<ref name=\"lpc95\" /> While 25 Broadway is considered to be its primary address, it is also known as 13\u201327 Broadway, 13\u201339 Greenwich Street, and 1\u20139 Morris Street.<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web |url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/115358/standard-poors-building-new-york-city-ny-usa |title=Standard & Poors Building |website=Emporis |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"lpc95\" /> The Cunard Building has a [[frontage]] of {{Convert|203|ft||abbr=}} along Broadway, {{Convert|231|ft||abbr=}} along Greenwich Street, and {{Convert|248|ft||abbr=}} along Morris Street.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=61}}</ref> Due to the irregular street grid of the area, none of its corners are at right angles.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=October 1919|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.c2640733&view=1up&seq=260|journal=Architectural Review|volume=26|pages=113\u2013114|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43286591/|title=$20,000,000 Office Building Projects of Cunard and Munson Lines Completed|date=May 1, 1921|work=New-York Tribune|access-date=January 30, 2020|page=37|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nThe Cunard Building was largely designed by [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris]].<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /> The [[massing]] and [[facade]] were devised by [[Carr\u00e8re and Hastings]], while exterior detail was created by Rochette & Parzini.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=5}}</ref> The structure was laid out so that ancillary structures such as smoke stacks, penthouses, and storage tanks could not be seen from the side. Its location near ferry slips, the [[New York City Subway]], elevated [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|Interborough Rapid Transit]] lines, and the [[Hudson & Manhattan Railroad]]'s [[Hudson Terminal]] made the Cunard Building desirable to tenants.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> In the 1970s, the Cunard Building became known as the Standard & Poors Building, after its tenant [[Standard & Poor's]],<ref name=\"Oser 1977\" /> though the name also came to refer to nearby structures.{{efn|The Standard & Poor's Building may refer to [[65 Broadway]]<ref>{{cite aia5|page=22}}</ref> or [[55 Water Street]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Standard & Poor's, Given Subsidies, Is to Stay in New York | website=The New York Times | date=April 25, 1997 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/25/nyregion/standard-poor-s-given-subsidies-is-to-stay-in-new-york.html | access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Form ===\n[[File:Bowling Green NYC Feb 2020 78 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Eastern facade seen from across Broadway]]\nAt the time of the Cunard Building's construction, large buildings in New York City were being erected in a \"C\" or \"H\" shape to maximize illumination of the interior space.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> Additionally, the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]] necessitated the inclusion of [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] on buildings in New York City that were above a certain height.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/26/nyregion/new-yorks-first-zoning-resolution-which-brought-order-to-a-chaotic-building-boom-turns-100.html|title=Zoning Arrived 100 Years Ago. It Changed New York City Forever.|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=July 25, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Cunard Building was the first large structure built in the city after the end of [[World War I]], and set an example for compliance to the 1916 law.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\nThe building is H-shaped, with \"light courts\" facing north toward Morris Street and south toward the Bowling Green Building.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The \"light courts\" are located above the base. The placement of these courts allowed light to enter the Great Hall, located on the first floor.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> Because of the presence of large intersections on either side of the building (Bowling Green to the east and the intersection of Greenwich Street and [[Trinity Place]] to the west), the required setback under the 1916 zoning law was minimal.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> According to Morris, the irregular street grid of the neighborhood made it difficult to determine the orientation of the building; he finally decided on its current alignment since, at the time, it would have been possible to see the [[North River (Hudson River)]] to the south.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Morris|1920|p=1}}</ref>\n\n=== Foundation ===\nThe New York City Subway's [[BMT Broadway Line]] (now the {{NYCS trains|Broadway south day}}) crosses diagonally underneath the Cunard Building from northwest to southeast. Two additional subway lines, the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Lexington south}}) and the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Broadway-Seventh South Ferry}}), run adjacent to the western and eastern boundaries of the building, respectively.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\">{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=21}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.mta.info/document/2461|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Bowling Green (4)(5)|date=2018|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref> The Lexington Avenue Line's [[Bowling Green station]] is located directly under the building's boundary, while the Broadway Line's [[Whitehall Street station]] is located one block south.<ref name=\":0\" /> Because of the confluence of subway tunnels in the area, the Cunard Building's foundation was built around the subway.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\" /><ref name=\"AR p. 22\">{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=22}}</ref>\n\nDuring construction, the engineers considered and rejected an idea for placing the Cunard Building's [[girder]]s on the roof of the Broadway Line tunnel, since that would have resulted in vibrations every time a subway train passed by.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\" /> Furthermore, the subway tunnel was designed to support the weight of several small buildings and might not have been able to support one large building.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=17\u201318}}</ref> Instead, engineers decided to place the building's foundation columns on either side of the subway tunnel, and then erect girders for the building above the tunnel's roof. The foundation columns were placed as close to the subway tunnel as possible, in order to reduce the length of the trusses, which would have had to carry heavy loads. All of the foundation columns were sunk to the depth of the rock underneath.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\" />\n\nA [[cofferdam]] was then built on the eastern border of the site, and on part of the northern border. The rock surface underneath the building site was closer to the ground on the western side of the lot, requiring extensive excavation. On the eastern side of the lot, the rock surface sloped below the elevation of the subway tunnel. A {{Convert|6|ft|m|-thick|abbr=|adj=mid}} wall was built on the southern boundary of the Cunard lot, of which a {{Convert|2|ft||adj=on}} width was located under the Bowling Green Offices Building. The wall served several purposes: it closed the cofferdam, underpinned the subway, and provided support for the columns on the southern side of the Cunard Building.<ref name=\"AR p. 22\" />\n\n=== Facade ===\n\n==== Broadway elevation ====\n[[File:Bowling Green-Battery Pk 03 - Cunard.jpg|thumb|left|Center arches at the base|alt=]]\nThe facade at the Broadway [[Elevation (architecture)|elevation]] is made of [[Indiana Limestone]], making Cunard Building part of a masonry \"canyon\" on lower Broadway.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> It is divided into three horizontal sections on the western and eastern facades. The outermost portions of these facades consist of pavilions that project outward, while the central pavilion is set back {{Convert|5|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 4\">{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> The projecting \"side pavilions\" rise to the maximum height allowed under the 1916 law.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" /> On the Broadway facade, the side pavilions are {{Convert|50|ft||abbr=}} wide, while the central pavilion is about {{Convert|103|ft||abbr=}} wide.<ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" />\n\nThe Broadway facade contains decorative elements that signify the area's historic connections with the maritime industry, including \"nautically-inspired sculpted elements\", decorative [[Keystone (architecture)|keystones]] above the first-floor arches, decorative ship-themed [[roundel]]s above the third-floor loggia, and carvings of seahorses with their riders above the pavilions' setbacks.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 62\" />\n\nWithin the four-story base, the central section is recessed slightly. The first floor contains five double-height arches, set within [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] masonry, facing east toward Broadway.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> The center three arches, within the recessed central pavilion, lead to the Great Hall; the southernmost arch leads to the elevator lobby for the office space above; and the northernmost arch led to a banking area on the north side of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> All the arches contain doors and windows with bronze frames.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> The third and fourth floors contain an Ionic-style [[loggia]] structure supported by [[Italianate architecture|Tuscan-style]] column pairs. Above the base, the facade is mostly composed of smooth limestone, except for rustication around the fifth story windows. The columns of windows around the central pavilion, which is recessed further, are also set within a rusticated facade. The outer pavilions are set back beyond the 18th story to comply with the 1916 Zoning Resolution. The central pavilion contains a loggia between the 19th and 21st stories, also supported by Tuscan-style column pairs, and includes a [[mansard roof]] above the 22nd story. The roofs of the outer pavilions, above the 22nd story, are flat.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\n==== Other elevations ====\n{{multiple image\n|total_width=450\n|image1=Cunard Building side Feb 2020 02.jpg\n|caption1=Morris Street facade, looking up at the light court, which is faced mostly in brick. The section at far left, closest to Broadway, is faced with limestone\n|image2=Cunard Building rear Feb 2020 2.jpg\n|caption2=Greenwich Street facade, with the triple-height window recessed at an angle. Below is the full-height basement, faced with granite\n}}\nOn Morris Street, the first and second stories are faced with limestone, while the basement is faced with a [[Water table (architecture)|water table]] made of granite. Above the second story is a light court. The facade of the eastern wing (facing Broadway) is limestone, while the rest of the Morris Street facade is made of tan brick. There are also numerous glazed doors with bronze frames, as well as glazed paneled windows with metal frames. The remaining windows on Morris Street are [[sash window]]s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\nOn Greenwich Street, the basement is faced with granite and the remaining stories are faced with tan brick. The basement contains service doors, a garage door, and metal window openings. Above the garage door is a large triple-height arched window on the first through third floors, with balconies on the second and third floors; the window is recessed at an angle. The remaining windows on Greenwich Street are sash windows. There is a [[cornice]] of stone above the 22nd floor. The southernmost section of the Greenwich Street facade only goes to the third floor<!-- four stories high, including basement --> to allow light to enter the light court within the southern side of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> The gray brick at both Morris and Greenwich Streets was designed to \"harmoniz[e] closely with the limestone\".<ref name=\"AB p. 62\" />\n\nThe south elevation consists of a brick facade with sash windows. The light court faces south toward the Bowling Green Offices Building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\n=== Interior ===\nAt opening, the Cunard Building featured over {{convert|700,000|ft2||abbr=}} of space, of which {{Convert|500,000|ft2||abbr=}} was made available for tenants when it opened. A basement in the building contained a safe-deposit vault.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /> The structure also included a fireproof internal structure.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 2, 1919|title=Unusual Features Mark Plans of New Cunard Building|url=https://rerecord.library.columbia.edu/pdf_files/ldpd_7031148_064_32.pdf|journal=The Real Estate Record: Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide|volume=104|pages=141|via=[[Columbia University|columbia.edu]]|number=5}}</ref> According to data collected by ''[[The Real Deal (magazine)|The Real Deal]]'' magazine, the precise floor area of the Cunard Building is {{convert|809,401|ft2}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=25 Broadway \u2013 TRD Research | website=The Real Deal | date=March 13, 2019 | url=https://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/property/25-broadway/ | access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe building also contained 36 elevators: 33 for passengers and 3 for freight.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 3\">{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> Of the passenger elevators, 28 were \"high-speed\" elevators for general use and the remaining 5 were private cabs.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Twenty of the \"high-speed\" elevators were local and express elevators, accessible from the elevator lobby at the southern end of the Broadway facade. The other eight were located at the building's northwest corner, near Greenwich and Morris Streets.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" />\n\n==== Lobby and Great Hall ====\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| total_width = 250\n| image1 = Cunard Building 02.JPG\n| caption1 = Lobby\n| image2 = Cunard 6.jpg\n| caption2 = Great Hall\n}}\n\nThe main entrance is from Broadway, through the three center arches, each of which contains a small entrance vestibule inside. The vestibules and the two outer arches all lead to the building's main lobby.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 12\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> The lobby contains a ceiling of five [[groin vault]]s, each of which correspond to one of the arches on the Broadway facade. The floors are made of [[travertine]] with [[marble]] trim and contain maritime-themed bronze medallions.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> The walls are also made of travertine; there is a fireplace on the southern wall and a roll-down gate and doors on the northern wall.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> A passageway runs along the western wall of the lobby, connecting the northern four bays to the Great Hall to the west.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 12\" /> The building's original owners had decided against putting \"miscellaneous minor business adventures\" in the lobby, such as newsstands, shoe-shine stands, and cigar shops.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/>\n\nThe Great Hall, extending {{Convert|185|ft||abbr=}} from east to west,<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /> was described as \"the largest of its kind\" within the United States when completed, and was compared to the waiting rooms of railroad terminals.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> It includes three separate vaults. The central vault is {{Convert|65|ft||abbr=}} tall with a diameter of {{Convert|70|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> There are large arched windows or \"luminary squares\" at the ends of its diagonal axes, under which are Ionic columns.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 63\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=63}}</ref> Flanking the main dome are two spaces with rectangular [[rib vault]]s, which extend the hall to the west and east.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 63\" /> There are additional arched openings through the west and east walls of the Great Hall: the former leads to a window facing Greenwich Street, while the latter leads to the lobby.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> As built, the hall was overlooked by wrought-iron balconies on the east wall, designed by [[Samuel Yellin]].<ref name=\"AB p. 63\" /> The features are reminiscent of [[Thermae|Roman bathhouses]] and the treatment of the artwork resembles that at the [[Villa Madama]]'s loggia in Italy.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\nThe north side of the Cunard Building's first floor contained a banking area, which had a private elevator to the fourth floor and a basement-level bank vault.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> This was initially occupied by a branch of the [[Mechanics and Metals National Bank]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-MM-1921\"/>\n\nThe first floor contains numerous elaborate works of art.<ref name=\"nycland\">{{cite nycland|page=10}}</ref> The lobby ceiling was painted by [[Ezra Winter]] and sculpted by [[C. Paul Jennewein|Carl Jennewein]], and contains decorations of marine animals and children.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"nycland\" /> The lobby's end bays also contain [[bas-relief]]s carved by Jennewein.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> Wrought-iron screens topped by [[lunette]] grilles, designed by [[Samuel Yellin]], separate the passageway from both the lobby to the east and the Great Hall to the west.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> The ceiling of the Great Hall contains maritime-themed frescoes, which Winter painted using the [[fresco-secco]] method,<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=13}}</ref> which depicted maritime activity.<ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=16}}</ref> [[Barry Faulkner]] painted murals of maps into the walls of the Great Hall's niches.<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref name=\"nycland\" /> The [[pendentive]]s of the Great Hall's dome include depictions of oceanic explorers [[Leif Erikson]], [[Christopher Columbus]], [[Sebastian Cabot (explorer)|Sebastian Cabot]], and [[Francis Drake]].<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=6}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> On the Great Hall's floor is a marble compass surrounded by a bronze frieze, designed by [[John Gregory (sculptor)|John Gregory]] as an \"allegory of the sea\".<ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=7}}</ref>\n\n==== Upper stories ====\nEach of the office floors consisted of about {{Convert|48,000|ft2||abbr=}} of space,<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> though the actual rentable space on each floor ranged from {{convert|20,000|to|30,000|ft2}}.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Because of the \"H\" shaped design, all offices had access to windows.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" />\n\nThe upper four floors were later converted for use by the [[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]], which utilizes a side entrance at 1 Morris Street. The school space contains a cafeteria; 30 classrooms; a library; a 400-seat auditorium; and a {{convert|40,000|ft2|adj=on}} athletic complex with a gym, swimming pool, and rock climbing wall.<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20100920/downtown/claremont-prep-opens-new-40-million-school-downtown|title=Claremont Prep Opens New $40 Million School Downtown|last=Shapiro|first=Julie|date=September 20, 2010|website=DNAinfo New York|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Context ===\nThe site of the Cunard Building was occupied by Dutch houses after the colony of [[New Amsterdam]] was founded in the 17th century.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/iconographyofma_02stok#page/220/mode/2up|title=The iconography of Manhattan Island, 1498\u20131909|last=Phelps Stokes|first=I.N.|date=1916|volume=2|pages=220\u2013222|access-date=January 28, 2020|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 1846, the future site of the Cunard Building became a hotel and restaurant operated by Joseph and Lorenzo Delmonico. This later became a hotel called the Stevens House which was popular among shipping and mercantile industry figures.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=2}}</ref> By the 1900s and 1910s, the Stevens House name applied to two 5-story buildings at the corner of Broadway and Morris Street.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /> According to a 1910 photograph, the buildings on 13-27 Broadway were largely commercial and included a restaurant, art publishers, the [[Anchor Line (steamship company)|Anchor Line]] steamship company, hatters, and Stevens House.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/bothsidesofbroad00dele|title=Both sides of Broadway, from Bowling Green to Central Park, New York City.|last=De Leeuw|first=Rudolph M.|date=1910|publisher=De Leeuw Riehl publishing company|others=Columbia University Libraries|isbn=|location=|pages=42|oclc=7536624}}</ref> Meanwhile, the lots facing Greenwich and Morris Streets contained [[Manhattan Railway Company]]'s lost-property building and former vice president [[Aaron Burr]]'s old house.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\">{{cite book | title=Architecture and Building | publisher=W.T. Comstock Company | issue=v. 52 | year=1920 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nCznAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PR54 | access-date=February 5, 2020 | pages=4\u20135}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" />\n\nThe [[Cunard Line]], for whom the Cunard Building was constructed, was one of the preeminent British transatlantic [[steamship]] companies of the 19th century. Its New York City office, which opened in 1846, had always been situated in or around Bowling Green.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> After moving several times, the Cunard Line sought \"an adequate and permanent American headquarters\" by the 1910s.<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /> Benjamin Wistar Morris started planning for a new office building for the Cunard Line by August 1917, before the site had even been purchased. His preliminary plans called for a grandiose ticket lobby for Cunard's ticket offices and a smaller elevator lobby for tenants of the upper floors. Despite subsequent modifications to the draft, the two separate lobbies remained in the final plan.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The individual lots comprising the future Cunard Building were then purchased by the Irons & Todd real-estate firm, which then formed the Todd, Irons & Robertson, Inc. construction company. Irons & Todd eventually hoped to turn over the land to the Twenty-Five Broadway Corporation, a subsidiary headed by an official for the Cunard Line.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" />\n\n=== Construction ===\n[[File:Pilot lore; from sail to steam (1922) (14779091221).jpg|thumb|1922 view from [[Whitehall Street]] to the south]]\nPlans for the Cunard Building were announced in February 1918. At the time, the building was supposed to be 26 stories and cost $10\u201315 million.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"Tribune-Cunard-1919\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43161159/|title=Cunard Line Will Build Skyscraper At Bowling Green: Home of Aaron Burr, Stevens House and Other Landmarks Bought|last=|first=|date=February 20, 1918|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live|page=13|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> One ''New York Times'' writer lamented that the plans would involve the destruction of the Stevens House, described as \"the last quaint landmark standing as an interesting connecting link between\" historic and modern New York City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/03/03/archives/passing-of-the-stevens-house.html|title=Passing of the Stevens House|date=March 3, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Due to World War I, further planning was delayed until June 1919 when Morris was authorized to create \"working drawings, specifications and contracts\".<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /> The demolition of the Stevens House began in July 1919, at which point the Cunard Building's final plans were publicized, showing that it was to comprise only 21 stories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1919/07/20/archives/monumental-broadway-building-for-cunard-steamship-company-a.html|title=Monumental Broadway Building For Cunard Steamship Company; A Structure of Twenty Stories, Representing an Investment of $10,000,000, to be Elected on Site of Old Stevens House on Lower Broadway, Facing Bowling Green|date=July 20, 1919|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Several details were revised in the final plans; for instance, a colonnade on the Broadway facade was replaced with arches.<ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" /> The [[New York City Department of Buildings]] received the blueprints for the Cunard Building in August 1919 and approved the project the next January, allowing construction to begin right afterward.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\nConstruction was hindered by the presence of [[New York City Subway|subway]] lines directly underneath the building site, as well as the irregular plot shape and \"unknowable\" costs.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /> During construction, the underground BMT Broadway Line was carried on a concrete bed held by [[quicksand]] above the bottom of the Cunard Building's excavation site, in order to dampen the noise. The presence of the subways, combined with the fact that the Cunard site had been assembled from numerous separate plots, made construction more difficult.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Morris|1920|pp=2\u20133}}</ref><ref name=\"AR p. 22\" /> In one construction incident in February 1920, rock blasts from the building's excavation resulted in several subway passengers being injured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/02/19/archives/six-hurt-in-subway-as-blast-hits-train-rocks-from-cunard-building.html|title=Six Hurt In Subway As Blast Hits Train; Rocks from Cunard Building Excavation Bombard B.R.T. Passengers Near Whitehall.|date=February 19, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The designs of the interior artworks were devised off-site and then transferred to a studio within the Cunard Building.<ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=9\u201310}}</ref> The paintings were then installed within the building in four months; the artists used scaffolds to paint the ceilings while the foundations were still being built beneath them.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\nThe Cunard Building opened in May 1921<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> at a total cost of $15 million.<ref name=\"The Nautical Gazette 1921 p. 434\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mqk5AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA434|title=The Nautical Gazette|year=1921|page=434|access-date=January 29, 2020|issue=v. 100}}</ref> Despite increasing material costs at the end of World War I, the project had been completed on time, within 3% of its original budget.<ref name=\"AB p. 62\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=62}}</ref> The Cunard Building was one of several structures built on the lower section of Broadway in the early 20th century that would be affiliated with the maritime trade.<ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|pp=4, 8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/10/03/archives/lower-new-yorks-building-activity-recent-broadway-purchase-by.html|title=Lower New York's Building Activity; Recent Broadway Purchase by Harriman Interests, Near the New Cunard Structure an Object Lesson of Recent Trade Expansion|date=October 3, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Usage ===\nAt opening, the Great Hall was the home of Cunard and Anchor Lines, which occupied the Great Hall, first three stories, basement, and top floors.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> The remaining floors housed numerous other tenants,<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/05/01/archives/new-cunard-building-imposing-office-structure-at-25-broadway-opens.html|title=New Cunard Building; Imposing Office Structure at 25 Broadway Opens Its Doors Tomorrow--Striking Architectural Features|date=May 1, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> including [[Atlas Portland Cement Company]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/02/10/archives/5000000-involved-in-two-big-leases-times-square-corner-leased-by.html|title=$5,000,000 Involved in Two Big Leases|date=February 10, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Anaconda Copper]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43288262/|title=Pay $4,200,000 For Space in Steamship Row|date=November 4, 1920|work=New-York Tribune|access-date=January 30, 2020|page=20|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> [[Merchant Shipbuilding Corporation]], [[Consolidated Steel Corporation]], [[International Motor Truck Company]], and Atlantic, Gulf & West Indies Steamship Lines.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> A branch of the [[Mechanics and Metals National Bank]] was located at the first floor, within the retail space on the northeast corner.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-MM-1921\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/05/16/archives/bank-branch-moved-mechanics-and-metals-opens-an-office-in-the.html|title=Bank Branch Moved; Mechanics and Metals Opens an Office in the Cunard Building.|date=May 16, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Even before the Cunard Building's official opening, it was almost fully leased, with only {{Convert|24,000|ft2|m2|abbr=}} remaining unused by April 1921.<ref name=\"The Nautical Gazette 1921 p. 434\" /> Factors in the Cunard Building's near-complete occupancy included relatively low rents, the inclusion of 21-year leases, the timely completion of the project, and a shortage of available office space in the Financial District.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> In later years, other industries moved into the Cunard Building as well, such as attorneys, railroad and steamship companies, shipbuilding companies, brokers, engineers, and raw materials companies.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> These included the [[New York Central Railroad]], which moved into the building in 1946.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/04/10/archives/ny-central-in-lease-takes-floor-in-25-broadway-for-foreign-freight.html|title=N.Y. Central in Lease; Takes Floor in 25 Broadway for Foreign Freight and Marine|date=April 10, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe building's owners were given a loan of $8 million in 1930,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/10/archives/lends-8000000-at-4-on-the-cunard-building.html|title=Lends $8,000,000 at 4 % On the Cunard Building|date=October 10, 1931|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and another $2.82 million in 1944.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1282862777/D445EE0D35DD4530PQ|title=Loan of $2,820,000 For Cunard Building|date=April 18, 1944|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|page=28|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1944/04/11/archives/2820000-loan-placed-on-the-cunard-building.html|title=$2,820,000 Loan Placed On the Cunard Building|date=April 11, 1944|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In subsequent years, the assessed taxes for the Cunard Building was reduced multiple times. The New York Supreme Court gave the building's owners tax reprieves in 1946,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/01/01/archives/cunard-building-gets-assessment-reduction.html|title=Cunard Building Gets Assessment Reduction|date=January 1, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> 1948,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/03/31/archives/cunard-building-valuations-cut.html|title=Cunard Building Valuations Cut|date=March 31, 1948|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and 1950.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/04/22/archives/court-cuts-valuations-lowers-assessments-on-hotel-lincoln-and.html|title=Court Cuts Valuation; Lowers Assessments on Hotel Lincoln and Cunard Building|date=April 22, 1950|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 1955, the owners completed a $3 million project to add air conditioning to the Cunard Building, one of the largest such retrofits in an existing structure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1323294095/D445EE0D35DD4530PQ|title=Space in Cunard Building Cooled at $3,000,000 Cost|date=August 14, 1955|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|page=3C|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/08/21/archives/cunard-building-aircooled.html|title=Cunard Building Air-Cooled|date=August 21, 1955|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAshforth, Todd & Company purchased the building in 1962.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/11/09/archives/25-broadway-building-is-sold-by-cunard-line.html|title=25 Broadway Building Is Sold by Cunard Line|date=November 9, 1962|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Cunard Line continued to operate the ticket hall until 1968, when it moved to [[555 Fifth Avenue]];<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> the vacant space was then leased by brokerage company Francis I. duPont Co.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/12/19/archives/news-of-realty-cunard-tenancy-francis-i-dupont-leases-space-at-25.html|title=News of Realty: Cunard Tenancy; Francis I. duPont Leases Space at 25 Broadway|date=December 19, 1968|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was sold again in 1971, this time to the Cementation Company of America, a subsidiary of [[Trafalgar House (company)|Trafalgar House Investment Group]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/07/01/archives/trafalgar-house-reveals-576million-cunard-bid.html|title=Trafalgar House Reveals $57.6\u2010Million Cunard Bid|date=July 1, 1971|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Initially, the owners had difficulty finding tenants for the Great Hall due to its vast size.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/119455656/F536749CA6244088PQ|title=Tenant Hunted for Cunard Building's 'Great Hall'|date=October 1, 1972|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service]] leased the Great Hall in 1974, intending to relocate its post office from the nearby [[Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House]] two years later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/09/16/archives/cunard-will-lease-its-great-hall-to-postal-service-move-planned-in.html|title=Cunard Will Lease Its Great Hall to Postal Service|last=Horsley|first=Carter B.|date=September 16, 1974|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By 1977, the USPS had moved into the Great Hall, and [[Standard & Poor's]] had signed a 20-year lease for space at the Cunard Building.<ref name=\"Oser 1977\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/12/07/archives/about-real-estate-gradual-changes-for-the-old-cunard-building.html|title=About Real Estate|last=Oser|first=Alan S.|date=December 7, 1977|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was sold to Zev W. Wolfson for $15 million by 1979.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/10/10/archives/real-estate-a-foreign-interest-in-manhattan.html|title=Real Estate|date=1979-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[City College of New York]]'s Center For Worker Education was established on the seventh floor of the Cunard Building in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccny.cuny.edu/news/%E2%80%9C-realm%E2%80%9D-opens-ccnys-sixth-annual-taffny-film-festival|title='The Realm' opens CCNY's sixth annual TAFFNY film festival|last=|first=|date=June 11, 2019|website=www.ccny.cuny.edu|publisher=The City College of New York|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Elizabeth Berger Plaza 78 - L\u00e9man Manhattan.jpg|alt=L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School sign|thumb|[[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]] sign outside the Morris Street entrance]]\n\nIn 1995, the exterior and the first floor interior of the Cunard Building, along with several other buildings on Bowling Green,{{efn|Namely [[26 Broadway]]; the [[Bowling Green Offices Building]]; and the [[International Mercantile Marine Company Building]]<ref name=\"Dunlap 1995\" />}} were formally designated as New York City landmarks.<ref name=\"Dunlap 1995\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/15/realestate/bringing-downtown-back-up.html|title=Bringing Downtown Back Up|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=1995-10-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{efn|The interior designation included the entrance vestibules and lobby, the passage to the Great Hall, and the Hall up to the height of its rotunda.<ref name=\"lpc95\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=1}}</ref>}} Two years later, S&P vacated its spaces at the Cunard Building, as well as at [[26 Broadway]] directly to the east, when the company started leasing space at nearby [[55 Water Street]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Oser|first=Alan S.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/03/realestate/downtown-is-looking-up.html|title=Downtown Is Looking Up|date=August 3, 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The post office closed in 2000.<ref>{{cite web | last=Geier | first=Stephanie | title=A Look Inside the Opulent Cunard Building in NYC | website=Untapped New York | date=December 4, 2015 | url=https://untappedcities.com/2015/12/04/a-look-inside-the-opulent-cunard-building-in-nyc/ | access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Afterward, the Great Hall went unused again for over a decade. ''The New York Times'' cited the hall's landmark status as a factor in the difficulty of leasing the space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/23/realestate/commercial/the-tricky-task-of-renovating-a-buildings-landmark-interior.html|title=The Tricky Task of Renovating a Building Without Altering Its Landmark Insides|last=Hughes|first=C. J.|date=November 22, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The doors were locked, barring visitors from entering the Great Hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/nyregion/so-you-think-you-can-see-a-landmark.html|title=So, You Think You Can See a Landmark?|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=2006-01-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During the mid-2000s, the [[Sports Museum of America]] considered opening within the Great Hall,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2004/11/02/sports-hall-switches-sides-founder-crosses-bway-to-keep-national-museum-in-play/|title=Sports Hall Switches Sides \u2013 Founder Crosses B'way To Keep National Museum In Play|last=Cuozzo|first=Steve|date=2004-11-02|website=New York Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pennington|first=Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/13/sports/ncaafootball/sports-museum-and-heisman-find-place-in-lower-manhattan.html|title=Sports Museum and Heisman Find Place in Lower Manhattan|date=2005-04-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> but the museum ultimately opened in 2008 at 26 Broadway.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/12/arts/artsspecial/12sport.html|title=Luring Sports Fans of All Seasons to Lower Manhattan|date=2008-03-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2014, the Great Hall was leased to [[Cipriani S.A.]] for the operation of an event venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribecacitizen.com/2014/01/09/cipriani-is-adding-another-grand-space-to-its-empire/|title=Cipriani Is Adding Another Grand Space to Its Empire|date=January 9, 2014|website=Tribeca Citizen|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/02/16/lower-broadway-finally-blossoming-after-years-of-neglect/|title=Lower Broadway finally blossoming after years of neglect|last=Cuozzo|first=Steve|date=February 17, 2015|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe upper floors remained in use by multiple tenants, including school and college campuses. In 2002, [[Deloitte]] leased three floors of the Cunard Building after its previous offices at the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] were destroyed in the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/27/business/commercial-real-estate-deloitte-picks-light-flexibility-and-link-to-history.html|title=Commercial Real Estate; Deloitte Picks Light, Flexibility and Link to History|last=McDowell|first=Edwin|date=2002-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]] moved to the Cunard Building in 2010,<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/05/nyregion/05claremont.html|title=Claremont Prep Is Sold to For-Profit Firm|last=Anderson|first=Jenny|date=April 4, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 30, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{efn|At the time of the purchase, it was known as the Claremont Preparatory School;<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\" /> the name was changed to L\u00e9man in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/08/31/in-private-school-world-a-rush-to-be-international/|title=In Private School World, a Rush to Be 'International'|last=Anderson|first=Jenny|date=2011-08-31|website=City Room|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>}} occupying the top four floors for its middle and high school campuses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/10/07/take-a-look-inside-manhattans-first-and-only-boarding-school/|title=Inside Manhattan's first & only boarding school|last=Ridley|first=Jane|date=October 7, 2014|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> [[Relay Graduate School of Education]], a private graduate school for teachers, moved into the building in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/25/education-nonprofit-moves-into-historical-cunard-building/|title=Education nonprofit moves into historical Cunard Building|last=Weiss|first=Lois|date=June 26, 2019|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nUpon its opening, writers praised the Cunard Building's design. ''[[Architectural Forum]]'' magazine published six pieces about the Cunard Building in its July 1921 volume alone.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" />{{efn|For a list of these pieces, see {{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.}}}} In one such piece, art historian [[Royal Cortissoz]] described the external plan as \"indeed organic architecture\", writing that the \"genuine architectural inspiration [sprang] straight from the personality of the designer\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=4, 5, 8}}</ref> ''Architecture and Building'' called the site \"exceedingly well chosen\",<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> and the ''New-York Tribune'' called the Cunard Building \"one of the fine structures of the city\".<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /> Other critics praised the building's manner of construction, and how it had been built above the Broadway subway line.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" />\n\nThe interior was similarly regarded. In a piece for ''American Architect and Architecture'' in 1928, C.H. Blackall described the building as having \"a magnificent counting room\", and that the domed ceiling had \"individuality and a most charmingly successful decorative effect.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKkwAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA11|title=American Architect and Architecture|publisher=J. R. Osgood & Company|year=1928|page=11|access-date=January 30, 2020|issue=v. 133}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> David Dunlap of ''The New York Times'' said in 1991 that the Great Hall was \"one of New York's most magnificent\u2014and least appreciated\u2014public spaces\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/15/travel/hidden-corners-of-lower-manhattan.html|title=Hidden Corners of Lower Manhattan|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=1991-09-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Landmarks Preservation Commission, in its 1995 landmark-designation report, called the hall \"among New York's most impressive interiors\".<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|New York City|Architecture}}\n* [[List of buildings and structures on Broadway in Manhattan]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{commons category|25 Broadway Cunard Building}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |title=Cunard Building |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1928.pdf |date=September 19, 1995 |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995}}}}\n* {{cite web |title=Cunard Building, First Floor Interior |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1929.pdf |date=September 19, 1995 |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995}}}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|title=Cunard Building|ref={{harvid|''Architectural Forum''|1921}}|pages=1\u201324|postscript=:}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=11|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Royal|last=Cortissoz|title=The Cunard Building|pages=1\u20138}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=29|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Ezra|last=Winter|title=Mural Decorations of the Cunard Building|pages=9\u201316}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=49|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=S.O|last=Miller|title=Structural Features of the Cunard Building, New York|pages=17\u201320}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=53|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Carlton S.|last=Proctor|title=Special Problems in Foundations of the Cunard Building|pages=21\u201322|via=}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=54|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Henry C., Jr.|last=Meyer|title=Electrical, Heating and Ventilating Equipment of the Cunard Building|pages=22\u201323|via=}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=56|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Clyde R.|last=Place|title=Plumbing in the Cunard Building|pages=24|via=}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Morris|first=Benjamin Wistar|date=July 1920|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015082471254&view=1up&seq=15|journal=Architectural Forum|volume=33|pages=1\u20136|ref={{harvid|Morris|1920}}}}\n* {{cite journal|year=1921|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hy_nAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PR19|journal=Architecture and Building|publisher=W.T. Comstock Company|volume=53|pages=61\u201364|ref={{sfnref |''Architecture and Building''| 1921}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Broadway (Manhattan)}}\n{{Financial District, Manhattan}}\n\n[[Category:Carr\u00e8re and Hastings buildings]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1921]]\n[[Category:Bowling Green (New York City)]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Cunard Building{{!}}Cunard Building, Liverpool}}\n{{short description|Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Cunard Building\n| image = File:Bowling Green-Battery Pk 01 - Cunard.jpg\n| image_size =\n| image_caption =\n| former_names =\n| alternate_names = Standard & Poors Building\n| status = Complete\n| building_type = Office\n| architectural_style = [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Neo-Renaissance]]\n| classification =\n| location = 25 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]<br />[[Financial District, Manhattan]], New York\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|42|21|N|74|00|51|W|display=inline,title}}\n| groundbreaking_date =\n| start_date = 1920\n| stop_date =\n| topped_out_date =\n| completion_date = 1921\n| opened_date = May 2, 1921\n| inauguration_date =\n| client = [[Cunard Line]]\n| owner =\n| height = {{convert|254.74|ft|m}}\n| material =\n| size =\n| floor_count = 22 (+1 basement)\n| floor_area =\n| elevator_count =\n| architect = [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris III]]\n| architecture_firm = [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]]\n| embedded = {{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = NYC\n| designation1_date = September 19, 1995\n| designation1_number = 1928 (exterior), 1929 (interior)\n}}\n| references = <ref name=\"emporis\" />\n}}\nThe '''Cunard Building''', also known as the '''Standard & Poors Building''', is a 22-story office building located at 25 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]], adjacent to [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green Park]] in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. The Cunard Building was designed in the [[Renaissance architecture|Italian Renaissance]] style by [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris]], in conjunction with consultants [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]].\n\nThe Cunard Building's main facade, on Broadway, is made of limestone and consists of three horizontal sections. The design employs [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] and open \"light courts\" as mandated by the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]]. The structure was designed around an irregular street grid and is located directly above a [[New York City Subway|subway]] line that crosses the building site diagonally. The first floor interior contains an elaborately decorated lobby, as well as a similarly opulent Great Hall, which extends {{Convert|185|ft||abbr=}} with a {{Convert|65|ft|m|abbr=|-tall|adj=mid}} dome. The remaining floors contain various offices and school spaces.\n\nThe Cunard Building was erected for the New York City office of the [[Cunard Line]], a British-American steamship line; construction started in 1920 and the building was completed the next year. Upon completion, the Cunard Building was almost fully leased to tenants of various industries. The Twenty-five Broadway Corporation, a Cunard Line affiliate, owned the building until the 1960s. The Great Hall was vacated after the Cunard Line moved out in 1968; the [[United States Postal Service]] occupied the Great Hall from 1974 until 2000, and [[Cipriani S.A.]] started using the space in 2014. The upper floors continued to host offices and various educational facilities.\n\nUpon completion, the Cunard Building's exterior and interior designs received critical acclaim. The Cunard Building's facade and principal first-floor interior spaces were designated as [[List of New York City Landmarks|landmarks]] by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1995.\n\n== Description ==\nThe Cunard Building is a 22-story building,<ref name=\"emporis\" /> bounded by the [[Bowling Green Offices Building]] (11 Broadway) to the south, Broadway to the east, [[Greenwich Street]] to the west, and Morris Street to the north.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/02/20/archives/cunard-to-have-big-building-here-10000000-structure-of-26-stories.html|title=Cunard To Have Big Building Here; $10,000,000 Structure of 26 Stories Going Up on Site of Old Stevens House.|last=|first=|date=February 20, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune-Cunard-1919\" /> It is located across from [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green Park]] to the southeast, and [[26 Broadway]] and the ''[[Charging Bull]]'' sculpture to the east.<ref name=\"lpc95\" /> While 25 Broadway is considered to be its primary address, it is also known as 13\u201327 Broadway, 13\u201339 Greenwich Street, and 1\u20139 Morris Street.<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web |url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/115358/standard-poors-building-new-york-city-ny-usa |title=Standard & Poors Building |website=Emporis |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"lpc95\" /> The Cunard Building has a [[frontage]] of {{Convert|203|ft||abbr=}} along Broadway, {{Convert|231|ft||abbr=}} along Greenwich Street, and {{Convert|248|ft||abbr=}} along Morris Street.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=61}}</ref> Due to the irregular street grid of the area, none of its corners are at right angles.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=October 1919|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.c2640733&view=1up&seq=260|journal=Architectural Review|volume=26|pages=113\u2013114|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43286591/|title=$20,000,000 Office Building Projects of Cunard and Munson Lines Completed|date=May 1, 1921|work=New-York Tribune|access-date=January 30, 2020|page=37|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nThe Cunard Building was largely designed by [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris]].<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /> The [[massing]] and [[facade]] were devised by [[Carr\u00e8re and Hastings]], while exterior detail was created by Rochette & Parzini.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=5}}</ref> The structure was laid out so that ancillary structures such as smoke stacks, penthouses, and storage tanks could not be seen from the side. Its location near ferry slips, the [[New York City Subway]], elevated [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|Interborough Rapid Transit]] lines, and the [[Hudson & Manhattan Railroad]]'s [[Hudson Terminal]] made the Cunard Building desirable to tenants.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> In the 1970s, the Cunard Building became known as the Standard & Poors Building, after its tenant [[Standard & Poor's]],<ref name=\"Oser 1977\" /> though the name also came to refer to nearby structures.{{efn|The Standard & Poor's Building may refer to [[65 Broadway]]<ref>{{cite aia5|page=22}}</ref> or [[55 Water Street]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Standard & Poor's, Given Subsidies, Is to Stay in New York | website=The New York Times | date=April 25, 1997 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/25/nyregion/standard-poor-s-given-subsidies-is-to-stay-in-new-york.html | access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Form ===\n[[File:Bowling Green NYC Feb 2020 78 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Eastern facade seen from across Broadway]]\nAt the time of the Cunard Building's construction, large buildings in New York City were being erected in a \"C\" or \"H\" shape to maximize illumination of the interior space.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> Additionally, the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]] necessitated the inclusion of [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] on buildings in New York City that were above a certain height.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/26/nyregion/new-yorks-first-zoning-resolution-which-brought-order-to-a-chaotic-building-boom-turns-100.html|title=Zoning Arrived 100 Years Ago. It Changed New York City Forever.|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=July 25, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Cunard Building was the first large structure built in the city after the end of [[World War I]], and set an example for compliance to the 1916 law.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\nThe building is H-shaped, with \"light courts\" facing north toward Morris Street and south toward the Bowling Green Building.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The \"light courts\" are located above the base. The placement of these courts allowed light to enter the Great Hall, located on the first floor.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> Because of the presence of large intersections on either side of the building (Bowling Green to the east and the intersection of Greenwich Street and [[Trinity Place]] to the west), the required setback under the 1916 zoning law was minimal.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> According to Morris, the irregular street grid of the neighborhood made it difficult to determine the orientation of the building; he finally decided on its current alignment since, at the time, it would have been possible to see the [[North River (Hudson River)]] to the south.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Morris|1920|p=1}}</ref>\n\n=== Foundation ===\nThe New York City Subway's [[BMT Broadway Line]] (now the {{NYCS trains|Broadway south day}}) crosses diagonally underneath the Cunard Building from northwest to southeast. Two additional subway lines, the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Lexington south}}) and the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Broadway-Seventh South Ferry}}), run adjacent to the western and eastern boundaries of the building, respectively.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\">{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=21}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.mta.info/document/2461|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Bowling Green (4)(5)|date=2018|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref> The Lexington Avenue Line's [[Bowling Green station]] is located directly under the building's boundary, while the Broadway Line's [[Whitehall Street station]] is located one block south.<ref name=\":0\" /> Because of the confluence of subway tunnels in the area, the Cunard Building's foundation was built around the subway.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\" /><ref name=\"AR p. 22\">{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=22}}</ref>\n\nDuring construction, the engineers considered and rejected an idea for placing the Cunard Building's [[girder]]s on the roof of the Broadway Line tunnel, since that would have resulted in vibrations every time a subway train passed by.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\" /> Furthermore, the subway tunnel was designed to support the weight of several small buildings and might not have been able to support one large building.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=17\u201318}}</ref> Instead, engineers decided to place the building's foundation columns on either side of the subway tunnel, and then erect girders for the building above the tunnel's roof. The foundation columns were placed as close to the subway tunnel as possible, in order to reduce the length of the trusses, which would have had to carry heavy loads. All of the foundation columns were sunk to the depth of the rock underneath.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\" />\n\nA [[cofferdam]] was then built on the eastern border of the site, and on part of the northern border. The rock surface underneath the building site was closer to the ground on the western side of the lot, requiring extensive excavation. On the eastern side of the lot, the rock surface sloped below the elevation of the subway tunnel. A {{Convert|6|ft|m|-thick|abbr=|adj=mid}} wall was built on the southern boundary of the Cunard lot, of which a {{Convert|2|ft||adj=on}} width was located under the Bowling Green Offices Building. The wall served several purposes: it closed the cofferdam, underpinned the subway, and provided support for the columns on the southern side of the Cunard Building.<ref name=\"AR p. 22\" />\n\n=== Facade ===\n\n==== Broadway elevation ====\n[[File:Bowling Green-Battery Pk 03 - Cunard.jpg|thumb|left|Center arches at the base|alt=]]\nThe facade at the Broadway [[Elevation (architecture)|elevation]] is made of [[Indiana Limestone]], making Cunard Building part of a masonry \"canyon\" on lower Broadway.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> It is divided into three horizontal sections on the western and eastern facades. The outermost portions of these facades consist of pavilions that project outward, while the central pavilion is set back {{Convert|5|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 4\">{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> The projecting \"side pavilions\" rise to the maximum height allowed under the 1916 law.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" /> On the Broadway facade, the side pavilions are {{Convert|50|ft||abbr=}} wide, while the central pavilion is about {{Convert|103|ft||abbr=}} wide.<ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" />\n\nThe Broadway facade contains decorative elements that signify the area's historic connections with the maritime industry, including \"nautically-inspired sculpted elements\", decorative [[Keystone (architecture)|keystones]] above the first-floor arches, decorative ship-themed [[roundel]]s above the third-floor loggia, and carvings of seahorses with their riders above the pavilions' setbacks.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 62\" />\n\nWithin the four-story base, the central section is recessed slightly. The first floor contains five double-height arches, set within [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] masonry, facing east toward Broadway.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> The center three arches, within the recessed central pavilion, lead to the Great Hall; the southernmost arch leads to the elevator lobby for the office space above; and the northernmost arch led to a banking area on the north side of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> All the arches contain doors and windows with bronze frames.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> The third and fourth floors contain an Ionic-style [[loggia]] structure supported by [[Italianate architecture|Tuscan-style]] column pairs. Above the base, the facade is mostly composed of smooth limestone, except for rustication around the fifth story windows. The columns of windows around the central pavilion, which is recessed further, are also set within a rusticated facade. The outer pavilions are set back beyond the 18th story to comply with the 1916 Zoning Resolution. The central pavilion contains a loggia between the 19th and 21st stories, also supported by Tuscan-style column pairs, and includes a [[mansard roof]] above the 22nd story. The roofs of the outer pavilions, above the 22nd story, are flat.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\n==== Other elevations ====\n{{multiple image\n|total_width=450\n|image1=Cunard Building side Feb 2020 02.jpg\n|caption1=Morris Street facade, looking up at the light court, which is faced mostly in brick. The section at far left, closest to Broadway, is faced with limestone\n|image2=Cunard Building rear Feb 2020 2.jpg\n|caption2=Greenwich Street facade, with the triple-height window recessed at an angle. Below is the full-height basement, faced with granite\n}}\nOn Morris Street, the first and second stories are faced with limestone, while the basement is faced with a [[Water table (architecture)|water table]] made of granite. Above the second story is a light court. The facade of the eastern wing (facing Broadway) is limestone, while the rest of the Morris Street facade is made of tan brick. There are also numerous glazed doors with bronze frames, as well as glazed paneled windows with metal frames. The remaining windows on Morris Street are [[sash window]]s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\nOn Greenwich Street, the basement is faced with granite and the remaining stories are faced with tan brick. The basement contains service doors, a garage door, and metal window openings. Above the garage door is a large triple-height arched window on the first through third floors, with balconies on the second and third floors; the window is recessed at an angle. The remaining windows on Greenwich Street are sash windows. There is a [[cornice]] of stone above the 22nd floor. The southernmost section of the Greenwich Street facade only goes to the third floor<!-- four stories high, including basement --> to allow light to enter the light court within the southern side of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> The gray brick at both Morris and Greenwich Streets was designed to \"harmoniz[e] closely with the limestone\".<ref name=\"AB p. 62\" />\n\nThe south elevation consists of a brick facade with sash windows. The light court faces south toward the Bowling Green Offices Building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\n=== Interior ===\nAt opening, the Cunard Building featured over {{convert|700,000|ft2||abbr=}} of space, of which {{Convert|500,000|ft2||abbr=}} was made available for tenants when it opened. A basement in the building contained a safe-deposit vault.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /> The structure also included a fireproof internal structure.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 2, 1919|title=Unusual Features Mark Plans of New Cunard Building|url=https://rerecord.library.columbia.edu/pdf_files/ldpd_7031148_064_32.pdf|journal=The Real Estate Record: Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide|volume=104|pages=141|via=[[Columbia University|columbia.edu]]|number=5}}</ref> According to data collected by ''[[The Real Deal (magazine)|The Real Deal]]'' magazine, the precise floor area of the Cunard Building is {{convert|809,401|ft2}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=25 Broadway \u2013 TRD Research | website=The Real Deal | date=March 13, 2019 | url=https://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/property/25-broadway/ | access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe building also contained 36 elevators: 33 for passengers and 3 for freight.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 3\">{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> Of the passenger elevators, 28 were \"high-speed\" elevators for general use and the remaining 5 were private cabs.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Twenty of the \"high-speed\" elevators were local and express elevators, accessible from the elevator lobby at the southern end of the Broadway facade. The other eight were located at the building's northwest corner, near Greenwich and Morris Streets.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" />\n\n==== Lobby and Great Hall ====\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| total_width = 250\n| image1 = Cunard Building 02.JPG\n| caption1 = Lobby\n| image2 = Cunard 6.jpg\n| caption2 = Great Hall\n}}\n\nThe main entrance is from Broadway, through the three center arches, each of which contains a small entrance vestibule inside. The vestibules and the two outer arches all lead to the building's main lobby.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 12\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> The lobby contains a ceiling of five [[groin vault]]s, each of which correspond to one of the arches on the Broadway facade. The floors are made of [[travertine]] with [[marble]] trim and contain maritime-themed bronze medallions.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> The walls are also made of travertine; there is a fireplace on the southern wall and a roll-down gate and doors on the northern wall.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> A passageway runs along the western wall of the lobby, connecting the northern four bays to the Great Hall to the west.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 12\" /> The building's original owners had decided against putting \"miscellaneous minor business adventures\" in the lobby, such as newsstands, shoe-shine stands, and cigar shops.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/>\n\nThe Great Hall, extending {{Convert|185|ft||abbr=}} from east to west,<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /> was described as \"the largest of its kind\" within the United States when completed, and was compared to the waiting rooms of railroad terminals.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> It includes three separate vaults. The central vault is {{Convert|65|ft||abbr=}} tall with a diameter of {{Convert|70|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> There are large arched windows or \"luminary squares\" at the ends of its diagonal axes, under which are Ionic columns.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 63\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=63}}</ref> Flanking the main dome are two spaces with rectangular [[rib vault]]s, which extend the hall to the west and east.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 63\" /> There are additional arched openings through the west and east walls of the Great Hall: the former leads to a window facing Greenwich Street, while the latter leads to the lobby.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> As built, the hall was overlooked by wrought-iron balconies on the east wall, designed by [[Samuel Yellin]].<ref name=\"AB p. 63\" /> The features are reminiscent of [[Thermae|Roman bathhouses]] and the treatment of the artwork resembles that at the [[Villa Madama]]'s loggia in Italy.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\nThe north side of the Cunard Building's first floor contained a banking area, which had a private elevator to the fourth floor and a basement-level bank vault.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> This was initially occupied by a branch of the [[Mechanics and Metals National Bank]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-MM-1921\"/>\n\nThe first floor contains numerous elaborate works of art.<ref name=\"nycland\">{{cite nycland|page=10}}</ref> The lobby ceiling was painted by [[Ezra Winter]] and sculpted by [[C. Paul Jennewein|Carl Jennewein]], and contains decorations of marine animals and children.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"nycland\" /> The lobby's end bays also contain [[bas-relief]]s carved by Jennewein.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> Wrought-iron screens topped by [[lunette]] grilles, designed by [[Samuel Yellin]], separate the passageway from both the lobby to the east and the Great Hall to the west.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> The ceiling of the Great Hall contains maritime-themed frescoes, which Winter painted using the [[fresco-secco]] method,<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=13}}</ref> which depicted maritime activity.<ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=16}}</ref> [[Barry Faulkner]] painted murals of maps into the walls of the Great Hall's niches.<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref name=\"nycland\" /> The [[pendentive]]s of the Great Hall's dome include depictions of oceanic explorers [[Leif Erikson]], [[Christopher Columbus]], [[Sebastian Cabot (explorer)|Sebastian Cabot]], and [[Francis Drake]].<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=6}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> On the Great Hall's floor is a marble compass surrounded by a bronze frieze, designed by [[John Gregory (sculptor)|John Gregory]] as an \"allegory of the sea\".<ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=7}}</ref>\n\n==== Upper stories ====\nEach of the office floors consisted of about {{Convert|48,000|ft2||abbr=}} of space,<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> though the actual rentable space on each floor ranged from {{convert|20,000|to|30,000|ft2}}.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Because of the \"H\" shaped design, all offices had access to windows.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" />\n\nThe upper four floors were later converted for use by the [[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]], which utilizes a side entrance at 1 Morris Street. The school space contains a cafeteria; 30 classrooms; a library; a 400-seat auditorium; and a {{convert|40,000|ft2|adj=on}} athletic complex with a gym, swimming pool, and rock climbing wall.<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20100920/downtown/claremont-prep-opens-new-40-million-school-downtown|title=Claremont Prep Opens New $40 Million School Downtown|last=Shapiro|first=Julie|date=September 20, 2010|website=DNAinfo New York|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Context ===\nThe site of the Cunard Building was occupied by Dutch houses after the colony of [[New Amsterdam]] was founded in the 17th century.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/iconographyofma_02stok#page/220/mode/2up|title=The iconography of Manhattan Island, 1498\u20131909|last=Phelps Stokes|first=I.N.|date=1916|volume=2|pages=220\u2013222|access-date=January 28, 2020|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 1846, the future site of the Cunard Building became a hotel and restaurant operated by Joseph and Lorenzo Delmonico. This later became a hotel called the Stevens House which was popular among shipping and mercantile industry figures.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=2}}</ref> By the 1900s and 1910s, the Stevens House name applied to two 5-story buildings at the corner of Broadway and Morris Street.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /> According to a 1910 photograph, the buildings on 13-27 Broadway were largely commercial and included a restaurant, art publishers, the [[Anchor Line (steamship company)|Anchor Line]] steamship company, hatters, and Stevens House.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/bothsidesofbroad00dele|title=Both sides of Broadway, from Bowling Green to Central Park, New York City.|last=De Leeuw|first=Rudolph M.|date=1910|publisher=De Leeuw Riehl publishing company|others=Columbia University Libraries|isbn=|location=|pages=42|oclc=7536624}}</ref> Meanwhile, the lots facing Greenwich and Morris Streets contained [[Manhattan Railway Company]]'s lost-property building and former vice president [[Aaron Burr]]'s old house.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\">{{cite book | title=Architecture and Building | publisher=W.T. Comstock Company | issue=v. 52 | year=1920 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nCznAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PR54 | access-date=February 5, 2020 | pages=4\u20135}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" />\n\nThe [[Cunard Line]], for whom the Cunard Building was constructed, was one of the preeminent British transatlantic [[steamship]] companies of the 19th century. Its New York City office, which opened in 1846, had always been situated in or around Bowling Green.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> After moving several times, the Cunard Line sought \"an adequate and permanent American headquarters\" by the 1910s.<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /> Benjamin Wistar Morris started planning for a new office building for the Cunard Line by August 1917, before the site had even been purchased. His preliminary plans called for a grandiose ticket lobby for Cunard's ticket offices and a smaller elevator lobby for tenants of the upper floors. Despite subsequent modifications to the draft, the two separate lobbies remained in the final plan.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The individual lots comprising the future Cunard Building were then purchased by the Irons & Todd real-estate firm, which then formed the Todd, Irons & Robertson, Inc. construction company. Irons & Todd eventually hoped to turn over the land to the Twenty-Five Broadway Corporation, a subsidiary headed by an official for the Cunard Line.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" />\n\n=== Construction ===\n[[File:Pilot lore; from sail to steam (1922) (14779091221).jpg|thumb|1922 view from [[Whitehall Street]] to the south]]\nPlans for the Cunard Building were announced in February 1918. At the time, the building was supposed to be 26 stories and cost $10\u201315 million.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"Tribune-Cunard-1919\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43161159/|title=Cunard Line Will Build Skyscraper At Bowling Green: Home of Aaron Burr, Stevens House and Other Landmarks Bought|last=|first=|date=February 20, 1918|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live|page=13|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> One ''New York Times'' writer lamented that the plans would involve the destruction of the Stevens House, described as \"the last quaint landmark standing as an interesting connecting link between\" historic and modern New York City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/03/03/archives/passing-of-the-stevens-house.html|title=Passing of the Stevens House|date=March 3, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Due to World War I, further planning was delayed until June 1919 when Morris was authorized to create \"working drawings, specifications and contracts\".<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /> The demolition of the Stevens House began in July 1919, at which point the Cunard Building's final plans were publicized, showing that it was to comprise only 21 stories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1919/07/20/archives/monumental-broadway-building-for-cunard-steamship-company-a.html|title=Monumental Broadway Building For Cunard Steamship Company; A Structure of Twenty Stories, Representing an Investment of $10,000,000, to be Elected on Site of Old Stevens House on Lower Broadway, Facing Bowling Green|date=July 20, 1919|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Several details were revised in the final plans; for instance, a colonnade on the Broadway facade was replaced with arches.<ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" /> The [[New York City Department of Buildings]] received the blueprints for the Cunard Building in August 1919 and approved the project the next January, allowing construction to begin right afterward.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\nConstruction was hindered by the presence of [[New York City Subway|subway]] lines directly underneath the building site, as well as the irregular plot shape and \"unknowable\" costs.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /> During construction, the underground BMT Broadway Line was carried on a concrete bed held by [[quicksand]] above the bottom of the Cunard Building's excavation site, in order to dampen the noise. The presence of the subways, combined with the fact that the Cunard site had been assembled from numerous separate plots, made construction more difficult.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Morris|1920|pp=2\u20133}}</ref><ref name=\"AR p. 22\" /> In one construction incident in February 1920, rock blasts from the building's excavation resulted in several subway passengers being injured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/02/19/archives/six-hurt-in-subway-as-blast-hits-train-rocks-from-cunard-building.html|title=Six Hurt In Subway As Blast Hits Train; Rocks from Cunard Building Excavation Bombard B.R.T. Passengers Near Whitehall.|date=February 19, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The designs of the interior artworks were devised off-site and then transferred to a studio within the Cunard Building.<ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=9\u201310}}</ref> The paintings were then installed within the building in four months; the artists used scaffolds to paint the ceilings while the foundations were still being built beneath them.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\nThe Cunard Building opened in May 1921<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> at a total cost of $15 million.<ref name=\"The Nautical Gazette 1921 p. 434\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mqk5AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA434|title=The Nautical Gazette|year=1921|page=434|access-date=January 29, 2020|issue=v. 100}}</ref> Despite increasing material costs at the end of World War I, the project had been completed on time, within 3% of its original budget.<ref name=\"AB p. 62\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=62}}</ref> The Cunard Building was one of several structures built on the lower section of Broadway in the early 20th century that would be affiliated with the maritime trade.<ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|pp=4, 8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/10/03/archives/lower-new-yorks-building-activity-recent-broadway-purchase-by.html|title=Lower New York's Building Activity; Recent Broadway Purchase by Harriman Interests, Near the New Cunard Structure an Object Lesson of Recent Trade Expansion|date=October 3, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Usage ===\nAt opening, the Great Hall was the home of Cunard and Anchor Lines, which occupied the Great Hall, first three stories, basement, and top floors.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> The remaining floors housed numerous other tenants,<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/05/01/archives/new-cunard-building-imposing-office-structure-at-25-broadway-opens.html|title=New Cunard Building; Imposing Office Structure at 25 Broadway Opens Its Doors Tomorrow--Striking Architectural Features|date=May 1, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> including [[Atlas Portland Cement Company]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/02/10/archives/5000000-involved-in-two-big-leases-times-square-corner-leased-by.html|title=$5,000,000 Involved in Two Big Leases|date=February 10, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Anaconda Copper]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43288262/|title=Pay $4,200,000 For Space in Steamship Row|date=November 4, 1920|work=New-York Tribune|access-date=January 30, 2020|page=20|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> [[Merchant Shipbuilding Corporation]], [[Consolidated Steel Corporation]], [[International Motor Truck Company]], and Atlantic, Gulf & West Indies Steamship Lines.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> A branch of the [[Mechanics and Metals National Bank]] was located at the first floor, within the retail space on the northeast corner.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-MM-1921\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/05/16/archives/bank-branch-moved-mechanics-and-metals-opens-an-office-in-the.html|title=Bank Branch Moved; Mechanics and Metals Opens an Office in the Cunard Building.|date=May 16, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Even before the Cunard Building's official opening, it was almost fully leased, with only {{Convert|24,000|ft2|m2|abbr=}} remaining unused by April 1921.<ref name=\"The Nautical Gazette 1921 p. 434\" /> Factors in the Cunard Building's near-complete occupancy included relatively low rents, the inclusion of 21-year leases, the timely completion of the project, and a shortage of available office space in the Financial District.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> In later years, other industries moved into the Cunard Building as well, such as attorneys, railroad and steamship companies, shipbuilding companies, brokers, engineers, and raw materials companies.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> These included the [[New York Central Railroad]], which moved into the building in 1946.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/04/10/archives/ny-central-in-lease-takes-floor-in-25-broadway-for-foreign-freight.html|title=N.Y. Central in Lease; Takes Floor in 25 Broadway for Foreign Freight and Marine|date=April 10, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe building's owners were given a loan of $8 million in 1930,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/10/archives/lends-8000000-at-4-on-the-cunard-building.html|title=Lends $8,000,000 at 4 % On the Cunard Building|date=October 10, 1931|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and another $2.82 million in 1944.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1282862777/D445EE0D35DD4530PQ|title=Loan of $2,820,000 For Cunard Building|date=April 18, 1944|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|page=28|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1944/04/11/archives/2820000-loan-placed-on-the-cunard-building.html|title=$2,820,000 Loan Placed On the Cunard Building|date=April 11, 1944|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In subsequent years, the assessed taxes for the Cunard Building was reduced multiple times. The New York Supreme Court gave the building's owners tax reprieves in 1946,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/01/01/archives/cunard-building-gets-assessment-reduction.html|title=Cunard Building Gets Assessment Reduction|date=January 1, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> 1948,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/03/31/archives/cunard-building-valuations-cut.html|title=Cunard Building Valuations Cut|date=March 31, 1948|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and 1950.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/04/22/archives/court-cuts-valuations-lowers-assessments-on-hotel-lincoln-and.html|title=Court Cuts Valuation; Lowers Assessments on Hotel Lincoln and Cunard Building|date=April 22, 1950|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 1955, the owners completed a $3 million project to add air conditioning to the Cunard Building, one of the largest such retrofits in an existing structure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1323294095/D445EE0D35DD4530PQ|title=Space in Cunard Building Cooled at $3,000,000 Cost|date=August 14, 1955|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|page=3C|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/08/21/archives/cunard-building-aircooled.html|title=Cunard Building Air-Cooled|date=August 21, 1955|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAshforth, Todd & Company purchased the building in 1962.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/11/09/archives/25-broadway-building-is-sold-by-cunard-line.html|title=25 Broadway Building Is Sold by Cunard Line|date=November 9, 1962|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Cunard Line continued to operate the ticket hall until 1968, when it moved to [[555 Fifth Avenue]];<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> the vacant space was then leased by brokerage company Francis I. duPont Co.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/12/19/archives/news-of-realty-cunard-tenancy-francis-i-dupont-leases-space-at-25.html|title=News of Realty: Cunard Tenancy; Francis I. duPont Leases Space at 25 Broadway|date=December 19, 1968|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was sold again in 1971, this time to the Cementation Company of America, a subsidiary of [[Trafalgar House (company)|Trafalgar House Investment Group]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/07/01/archives/trafalgar-house-reveals-576million-cunard-bid.html|title=Trafalgar House Reveals $57.6\u2010Million Cunard Bid|date=July 1, 1971|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Initially, the owners had difficulty finding tenants for the Great Hall due to its vast size.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/119455656/F536749CA6244088PQ|title=Tenant Hunted for Cunard Building's 'Great Hall'|date=October 1, 1972|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service]] leased the Great Hall in 1974, intending to relocate its post office from the nearby [[Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House]] two years later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/09/16/archives/cunard-will-lease-its-great-hall-to-postal-service-move-planned-in.html|title=Cunard Will Lease Its Great Hall to Postal Service|last=Horsley|first=Carter B.|date=September 16, 1974|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By 1977, the USPS had moved into the Great Hall, and [[Standard & Poor's]] had signed a 20-year lease for space at the Cunard Building.<ref name=\"Oser 1977\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/12/07/archives/about-real-estate-gradual-changes-for-the-old-cunard-building.html|title=About Real Estate|last=Oser|first=Alan S.|date=December 7, 1977|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was sold to Zev W. Wolfson for $15 million by 1979.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/10/10/archives/real-estate-a-foreign-interest-in-manhattan.html|title=Real Estate|date=1979-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[City College of New York]]'s Center For Worker Education was established on the seventh floor of the Cunard Building in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccny.cuny.edu/news/%E2%80%9C-realm%E2%80%9D-opens-ccnys-sixth-annual-taffny-film-festival|title='The Realm' opens CCNY's sixth annual TAFFNY film festival|last=|first=|date=June 11, 2019|website=www.ccny.cuny.edu|publisher=The City College of New York|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Elizabeth Berger Plaza 78 - L\u00e9man Manhattan.jpg|alt=L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School sign|thumb|[[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]] sign outside the Morris Street entrance]]\n\nIn 1995, the exterior and the first floor interior of the Cunard Building, along with several other buildings on Bowling Green,{{efn|Namely [[26 Broadway]]; the [[Bowling Green Offices Building]]; and the [[International Mercantile Marine Company Building]]<ref name=\"Dunlap 1995\" />}} were formally designated as New York City landmarks.<ref name=\"Dunlap 1995\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/15/realestate/bringing-downtown-back-up.html|title=Bringing Downtown Back Up|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=1995-10-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{efn|The interior designation included the entrance vestibules and lobby, the passage to the Great Hall, and the Hall up to the height of its rotunda.<ref name=\"lpc95\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=1}}</ref>}} Two years later, S&P vacated its spaces at the Cunard Building, as well as at [[26 Broadway]] directly to the east, when the company started leasing space at nearby [[55 Water Street]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Oser|first=Alan S.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/03/realestate/downtown-is-looking-up.html|title=Downtown Is Looking Up|date=August 3, 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  The post office closed in 2000.<ref>{{cite web | last=Geier | first=Stephanie | title=A Look Inside the Opulent Cunard Building in NYC | website=Untapped New York | date=December 4, 2015 | url=https://untappedcities.com/2015/12/04/a-look-inside-the-opulent-cunard-building-in-nyc/ | access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Afterward, the Great Hall went unused again for over a decade. ''The New York Times'' cited the hall's landmark status as a factor in the difficulty of leasing the space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/23/realestate/commercial/the-tricky-task-of-renovating-a-buildings-landmark-interior.html|title=The Tricky Task of Renovating a Building Without Altering Its Landmark Insides|last=Hughes|first=C. J.|date=November 22, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The doors were locked, barring visitors from entering the Great Hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/nyregion/so-you-think-you-can-see-a-landmark.html|title=So, You Think You Can See a Landmark?|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=2006-01-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During the mid-2000s, the [[Sports Museum of America]] considered opening within the Great Hall,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2004/11/02/sports-hall-switches-sides-founder-crosses-bway-to-keep-national-museum-in-play/|title=Sports Hall Switches Sides \u2013 Founder Crosses B'way To Keep National Museum In Play|last=Cuozzo|first=Steve|date=2004-11-02|website=New York Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pennington|first=Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/13/sports/ncaafootball/sports-museum-and-heisman-find-place-in-lower-manhattan.html|title=Sports Museum and Heisman Find Place in Lower Manhattan|date=2005-04-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> but the museum ultimately opened in 2008 at 26 Broadway.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/12/arts/artsspecial/12sport.html|title=Luring Sports Fans of All Seasons to Lower Manhattan|date=2008-03-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2014, the Great Hall was leased to [[Cipriani S.A.]] for the operation of an event venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribecacitizen.com/2014/01/09/cipriani-is-adding-another-grand-space-to-its-empire/|title=Cipriani Is Adding Another Grand Space to Its Empire|date=January 9, 2014|website=Tribeca Citizen|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/02/16/lower-broadway-finally-blossoming-after-years-of-neglect/|title=Lower Broadway finally blossoming after years of neglect|last=Cuozzo|first=Steve|date=February 17, 2015|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe upper floors remained in use by multiple tenants, including school and college campuses. In 2002, [[Deloitte]] leased three floors of the Cunard Building after its previous offices at the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] were destroyed in the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/27/business/commercial-real-estate-deloitte-picks-light-flexibility-and-link-to-history.html|title=Commercial Real Estate; Deloitte Picks Light, Flexibility and Link to History|last=McDowell|first=Edwin|date=2002-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]] moved to the Cunard Building in 2010,<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/05/nyregion/05claremont.html|title=Claremont Prep Is Sold to For-Profit Firm|last=Anderson|first=Jenny|date=April 4, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 30, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{efn|At the time of the purchase, it was known as the Claremont Preparatory School;<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\" /> the name was changed to L\u00e9man in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/08/31/in-private-school-world-a-rush-to-be-international/|title=In Private School World, a Rush to Be 'International'|last=Anderson|first=Jenny|date=2011-08-31|website=City Room|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>}} occupying the top four floors for its middle and high school campuses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/10/07/take-a-look-inside-manhattans-first-and-only-boarding-school/|title=Inside Manhattan's first & only boarding school|last=Ridley|first=Jane|date=October 7, 2014|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> [[Relay Graduate School of Education]], a private graduate school for teachers, moved into the building in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/25/education-nonprofit-moves-into-historical-cunard-building/|title=Education nonprofit moves into historical Cunard Building|last=Weiss|first=Lois|date=June 26, 2019|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nUpon its opening, writers praised the Cunard Building's design. ''[[Architectural Forum]]'' magazine published six pieces about the Cunard Building in its July 1921 volume alone.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" />{{efn|For a list of these pieces, see {{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.}}}} In one such piece, art historian [[Royal Cortissoz]] described the external plan as \"indeed organic architecture\", writing that the \"genuine architectural inspiration [sprang] straight from the personality of the designer\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=4, 5, 8}}</ref> ''Architecture and Building'' called the site \"exceedingly well chosen\",<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> and the ''New-York Tribune'' called the Cunard Building \"one of the fine structures of the city\".<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /> Other critics praised the building's manner of construction, and how it had been built above the Broadway subway line.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" />\n\nThe interior was similarly regarded. In a piece for ''American Architect and Architecture'' in 1928, C.H. Blackall described the building as having \"a magnificent counting room\", and that the domed ceiling had \"individuality and a most charmingly successful decorative effect.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKkwAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA11|title=American Architect and Architecture|publisher=J. R. Osgood & Company|year=1928|page=11|access-date=January 30, 2020|issue=v. 133}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> David Dunlap of ''The New York Times'' said in 1991 that the Great Hall was \"one of New York's most magnificent\u2014and least appreciated\u2014public spaces\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/15/travel/hidden-corners-of-lower-manhattan.html|title=Hidden Corners of Lower Manhattan|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=1991-09-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Landmarks Preservation Commission, in its 1995 landmark-designation report, called the hall \"among New York's most impressive interiors\".<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|New York City|Architecture}}\n* [[List of buildings and structures on Broadway in Manhattan]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{commons category|25 Broadway Cunard Building}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |title=Cunard Building |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1928.pdf |date=September 19, 1995 |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995}}}}\n* {{cite web |title=Cunard Building, First Floor Interior |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1929.pdf |date=September 19, 1995 |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995}}}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|title=Cunard Building|ref={{harvid|''Architectural Forum''|1921}}|pages=1\u201324|postscript=:}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=11|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Royal|last=Cortissoz|title=The Cunard Building|pages=1\u20138}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=29|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Ezra|last=Winter|title=Mural Decorations of the Cunard Building|pages=9\u201316}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=49|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=S.O|last=Miller|title=Structural Features of the Cunard Building, New York|pages=17\u201320}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=53|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Carlton S.|last=Proctor|title=Special Problems in Foundations of the Cunard Building|pages=21\u201322|via=}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=54|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Henry C., Jr.|last=Meyer|title=Electrical, Heating and Ventilating Equipment of the Cunard Building|pages=22\u201323|via=}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=56|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Clyde R.|last=Place|title=Plumbing in the Cunard Building|pages=24|via=}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Morris|first=Benjamin Wistar|date=July 1920|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015082471254&view=1up&seq=15|journal=Architectural Forum|volume=33|pages=1\u20136|ref={{harvid|Morris|1920}}}}\n* {{cite journal|year=1921|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hy_nAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PR19|journal=Architecture and Building|publisher=W.T. Comstock Company|volume=53|pages=61\u201364|ref={{sfnref |''Architecture and Building''| 1921}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Broadway (Manhattan)}}\n{{Financial District, Manhattan}}\n\n[[Category:Carr\u00e8re and Hastings buildings]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1921]]\n[[Category:Bowling Green (New York City)]]\n", "name_user": "Vami IV", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cunard_Building_(New_York_City)"}
